<title>
SOL.2 and SOL.3
</title>
</head>
<body>

<img src="/itc.gif" alt="ITC">
<hr>

<h2>POSTGRADUATE DIPLOMA AND MSC DEGREE COURSES  SOL.2/3</h2>

<h1>SOIL SURVEY AND APPLICATIONS OF SOIL INFORMATION 1996</h1>

Soil information varies widely in quality and quantity from country to country. The nature, location
and value of soil resources are still unknown over large regions. Available information is frequently
inappropriate when compared with the objectives of land use planning, especially at local and
regional levels.
<p>
Simultaneously, the development of soil databases, geographic information systems (GIS) and
modelling is creating an increased need for more and improved soil data. Training in soil survey and
related soil science fields is therefore vitally important.
<p>
The Soil Science Division of ITC is concerned with education, research and consulting in soil
resource inventory and its applications to land evaluation, conservation and management in rural,
peri-urban and urban environments.
<p>
The postgraduate diploma course (course code SOL.3) and the MSc degree course (SOL.2) are
organized by the Soil Science Division of ITC's Department of Land Resource and Urban Sciences.
<p>
The department also offers courses in forest survey, rural and land ecology survey, urban survey
and human settlement analysis, forestry for rural development, socio-economic information for
natural resource management, environmental systems analysis and monitoring, geoinformation
systems for rural applications, geoinformation systems for urban applications.
<p>
The SOL courses deal with surveying, processing, interpreting and transferring (to users) soil data
and information. Subjects covered include the genesis, characteristics, distribution, present
utilization and potential multipurpose use of soil resources, particularly in developing countries.
<p>
In the courses, extensive use is made of aerial photo and satellite image interpretation, as well as
field prospecting and laboratory determinations. Digital processing of satellite remote sensing data
and geographic information systems (GIS) are intensively employed.

<h2>OBJECTIVES</h2>

Upon completion of the courses, participants should be able to:
<ul>
<li> carry out and contribute to soil surveys with emphasis on the use of aerospace remote sensing
   techniques;
<li> apply a sound knowledge of the multipurpose utilization of soil survey information and the use of
   geographic information systems;
<li> carry out applied research in selected soil science fields (SOL.2).
</ul>
<p>
To achieve these objectives, participants will:
<ul>
<li> take part in lectures and practicals in about equal proportion;
<li> prepare, execute and report on a soil survey fieldwork project (SOL.3);
<li> plan and implement a research project and write an MSc thesis (SOL.2).
</ul>

<h2>TARGET GROUPS</h2>

The SOL.3 course is intended for soil scientists, agronomists and other professionals, trained at
university level and engaged in soil survey for government or private organizations. It is also suitable
for university/college staff teaching the subject.
The SOL.2 course is intended for professionals who wish to develop their knowledge and skills in soil
science or a closely related field, including mapping based on aerial photos and other remote sensing
data and the use of geographic information systems.

<h2>ADMISSION REQUIREMENTS AND APPLICATIONS</h2>

For admission to the SOL.3 and SOL.2 courses, applicants should hold a BSc degree from a recognized
university in one of the disciplines in which soil science is part of the curriculum, or be able to
demonstrate an equivalent level of education in one of these disciplines. Preferably they should also
have some years of working experience. 
<p>
Applicants for the SOL.2 course should have gained their BSc degree with good marks.
They should attain an average weighted mark of at least 75 in the SOL.3 course and show an aptitude
for independent study.
<p>
Interpretation of aerial photographs and satellite images is an important part of the course curriculum.
Candidates should therefore have good stereoscopic vision as well as normal colour vision. Proficiency
in the English language is also required (minimum requirement Test of English as a Foreign Language
(TOEFL) 500 or British Council test 6.0).
<p>
Applications for admission should be forwarded directly to ITC using the official application form which
is available from ITC's Student Registration Office.

<h2>COURSE STRUCTURE AND CONTENTS</h2>

<h3>SOL.3</h3>
The postgraduate course programme consists of lectures, practicals, workshops, excursions and
a fieldwork project. The curriculum is divided into a number of modules as listed below.

<dl>
<dt>August 
<dd>Natural resource management - an integrated approach

<dt>September-November 
<dd>Soil survey principles (concepts, methods, techniques)

<dt>December 
<dd>Land evaluation

<dt>January-February 
<dd>Remote sensing and geographic information systems:
            digital processing and interpretation of satellite images for soil information and its applications
            use of geographic information systems for handling and interpreting of soil data for various
             applications

<dt>March
<dd>Interpretation of soil information for multiple purposes (land evaluation, erosion hazard/conservation
   planning, environmental management, and land use planning)

<dt>April-June
<dd>Fieldwork (project preparation, fieldwork in a Mediterranean or tropical country, map compilation and
   report writing)
</dl>

<h3>SOL.2</h3>
The first five modules of the MSc degree course are identical to those of the SOL.3 course. The
remainder of the course, i.e., the second part of SOL.2, is conducted largely on an individual basis and
centres on a research topic leading to a thesis. Advanced coursework is required in a minimum of four
subjects. 
<p>
Students select their research topic in one of the following fields:
soil genesis and classification; soil geomorphology relationship; survey methods; soil variability
studies; digital processing and interpretation of satellite images; soil survey interpretation and land
evaluation for multiple purposes; land degradation, conservation and management; environmental
management; soil informatics and geographic information systems.

<h2>STARTING DATE AND DURATION</h2>

In 1996 the courses in Soil Survey and Applications of Soil Information start in the second week
of August and last 11 months (SOL.3) and 18 months (SOL.2). The first week is reserved for the
introduction and the last week for presentations of final assignment results, clearance formalities and
the diploma/degree ceremony. 

<h2>QUALIFICATION AWARDED</h2>

After completing the course and passing the required examinations, participants are awarded a
postgraduate diploma (SOL.3) or an MSc degree (SOL.2) accompanied by a course record.

<h2>ACCOMMODATION</h2>

Course participants are accommodated in the Dish Hotel. This is situated in the centre of Enschede,
ten minutes' walk from the ITC building.

<h2>STUDY COSTS, SUBSISTENCE AND ACCOMMODATION EXPENSES</h2>

The course fees for the 11-month SOL.3 course are NLG 11,000 and that of the 18-month SOL.2
course NLG 23,500. Additional fixed costs for SOL.2/3 courses are a maximum NLG 6,630. Subsistence
allowance including accommodation is estimated at NLG 1,545 per person per month. Please note that
international travel expenses are not included.

<h2>FELLOWSHIPS</h2>

For SOL.3 and SOL.2 course applicants from selected developing countries, the Netherlands'
government awards some fellowships under the Netherlands Fellowship Programme (NFP). In
accordance with Netherlands government policy, women are especially encouraged to apply. NFP
fellowship applications should be submitted through the appropriate organization in the candidate's
home country and with the approval of the candidate's employer, to reach the Royal Netherlands
Embassy at least four months before the starting date of the course. 
<p>
Since the number of NFP fellowships is rather limited, course applicants are advised to try to obtain
funding from other donor agencies. Details and addresses of sponsors in the applicant's country can
be obtained from the ITC Student Registration Office. Please note that ITC has no funds of its own,
neither does ITC have any influence on those organizations that grant fellowships.

<h2>FURTHER INFORMATION</h2>

The International Institute for Aerospace Surveys and Earth Sciences (ITC) is the largest institute for
international higher education in the Netherlands. The main objective of ITC is to assist developing
countries in human resources development in aerospace surveys, remote sensing applications, the
establishment of geographic information systems and the management of geoinformation.
<p>
To this end ITC concentrates on three main activities: education/training, research and advisory
services. In-house expertise covers an extensive range of disciplines in the fields of aerospace data
acquisition and processing, photogrammetry, cartography, land resource and urban sciences and earth
resource surveys. More details on ITC, the courses it offers and their costs are available in ITC's
General Information brochure. This brochure and other information can be obtained from:


<pre>
ITC Student Registration Office
Attn. Mrs. A. Scheggetman
P.O. Box 6
7500 AA  Enschede
The Netherlands

Phone : +31 (0)53 874 205
Fax   : +31 (0)53 874 238
Telex : 44525 itc nl
E-mail: <a href="mailto:scheggetman@itc.nl">scheggetman@itc.nl</a>
</pre>

All ITC courses are regularly revised and updated. The information here applies only to the 1996 course.
This leaflet will be updated each year and new copies can be obtained from the ITC Student
Registration Office.


