<h2>POSTGRADUATE DIPLOMA AND MSC DEGREE COURSE  FOR.2/3</h2>

<h1>FOREST SURVEY 1996</h1>

The intensifying pressure on forest resources and the growing awareness of their crucial  role in our
environment places increasing demands on the knowledge and skills of foresters. They must be
able to manage and develop forest resources in order to provide a sustainable supply of timber,
water and other related products and services.
<p>
The preparation, control and execution of a forest management plan require a wide range of
information, much of which is spatially referenced. Remote sensing and geographic information
systems (GIS) are now considered indispensable instruments in the supply of up-to-date information
for forest management.
<p>
ITC's postgraduate diploma (course code FOR.3) and MSc degree (FOR.2) Forest Survey courses
focus on the application of remote sensing and GIS in the problem areas of sustainable manage
ment of closed forests, rehabilitation of degraded (forest) land, and watershed management and
environmental protection. In the MSc course, management of woody biomass for energy in rural
areas is also addressed. Candidates interested in the energy specialisation should request for the
special brochure on rural energy and development.
<p>
The courses are organized by ITC's Forest Science Division of the Department of Land Resource
and Urban Sciences. Related courses include forestry for rural development, rural and land ecology
survey, soil survey and socio-economic information for natural resource management.

<h2>OBJECTIVES</h2>

The Forest Survey courses are designed to strengthen forestry and related institutions, by training
staff in the acquisition and use of aerospace information and GIS for forest management.
<p>
Upon completion of the course, participants should be able to:
<ul>
<li>define the multidisciplinary nature of forest management;
<li>identify an organization's needs for geographic information in problem areas;
<li>select a cost-effective forest survey design for acquisition of aerospace and ground data;
<li>analyze aerospace images and collect field data;
<li>integrate the data into a geographic information system (GIS);
<li>operate a GIS to support decision-making for forest management.
</ul>
<p>
In addition to the above, the participants in the MSc degree course in Forest Survey should be
able to:
<ul>
<li>appraise, design, implement and evaluate methods for cost-effective data collection and data
       management for the survey and monitoring of forest land;
<li>use a decision-support system to prepare alternative models for forest management.
</ul>
<p>
To achieve these objectives, participants will:
<ul>
<li>work periodically with participants from other courses, involved in natural resource management;
<li>critically study and compare survey designs to meet user requirements;
<li>work extensively with aerial photographs and satellite images, and with    geographic information
systems in several application fields;
<li>apply and validate the acquired knowledge and skills under field conditions.
</ul>
<p>
In addition, the MSc course participants will:
<ul>
<li>plan and implement a research project on methodological aspects of aerospace survey, or on
       developing alternative management plans using a decision-support system
</ul>


<h2>TARGET GROUPS</h2>

The course is designed for officers employed by forest agencies and staff from forestry training institutes
wishing to develop their knowledge and skills in the field of forest survey.

<h2>ADMISSION REQUIREMENTS AND APPLICATIONS</h2>

For admission to the FOR.3 and FOR.2 courses, applicants should hold a BSc or BA degree from a
recognized university in forestry or in one of the earth, agricultural or social sciences, or be able to
demonstrate an equivalent level of education in one of these disciplines. They preferably should also
have some years of working experience. 
<p>
Applicants for the FOR.2 course should have gained their BSc degree with good marks. Applicants
intending to carry out an MSc study in the field of "Forestry for Rural Development" or "Rural Energy
and Development" will both follow the FRD.3 programme during the first seven months. For further
information see the FRD.3 brochure and the special brochure on "MSc degree courses in Rural Energy
and Development". However, they should both apply for the FOR.2 course.
<p>
ITC alumni should have attained an average weighted mark of at least 75 in their FOR.3 or FRD.3
course and show an aptitude for independent study.
<p>
Interpretation of aerial photographs and satellite images is an important part of the course curriculum.
Candidates should therefore have good stereoscopic vision as well as normal colour vision. Proficiency
in the English language is also required (minimum requirement Test of English as a Foreign Language
(TOEFL) 500 or British Council test 6.0).
<p>
Applications for admission should be forwarded directly to ITC using the official application form
which is available from ITC's Student Registration Office.

<h2>COURSE STRUCTURES AND CONTENTS</h2>

<h3>FOR.3</h3>
The postgraduate course programme consists of lectures, practicals, workshops, excursions and a
fieldwork project. The curriculum is divided into a number of blocks containing one or more modules as
shown below:

<dl>
<dt>Block 1 (3 weeks):
<dd>Natural resource management<b>*</b>

<dt>Block 2 (13 weeks):
<dd>Introduction to aerospace survey, computer handling, field data collection and statistical
analysis, global forestry issues, forest inventory, surveying and mapping

<dt>Block 3 (4 weeks):
<dd>Land evaluation for land use planning<b>*</b>

<dt>Block 4 (8 weeks):
<dd>Remote sensing and geographic information systems<b>*</b>

<dt>Block 5 (4 weeks):
<dd>Application of remote sensing and GIS in forest monitoring and biomass survey

<dt>Block 6 (12 weeks):
<dd>Final project: planning, field data collection, data analysis and report preparation
</dl>
<b>*</b> These blocks are common to most courses in the Department of Land Resource and Urban
   Sciences

<h3>FOR.2</h3>
The first five blocks of the MSc degree course are identical to those of the postgraduate course. The
remainder of the course is conducted largely on an individual or group basis and centers on a research
topic leading to a thesis. Advanced course work is required in four subjects.

<dl>
<dt>Blocks 1-5:
<dd>see FOR.3

<dt>Block 7:
<dd>Field exercise to develop skills in survey techniques

<dt>Block 8:
<dd>Advanced subjects

<dt>Block 9:
<dd>Research project, including field data collection, and thesis preparation
</dl>

<h2>STARTING DATE AND DURATION</h2>

In 1996 both courses in Forest Survey will start in the second week of August and last 11 months
(FOR.3) or 18 months (FOR.2). For returning ITC alumni the programme starts in March 1996, and lasts
11 months. The first week of the courses is reserved for the introduction and the last week for
presentations of final assignment results, clearance formalities, the closing ceremony and diploma/degree
ceremony.

<h2>QUALIFICATION AWARDED</h2>

After completing the course and passing the required examinations, participants are awarded a
postgraduate diploma (FOR.3) or an MSc degree (FOR.2) accompanied by a course record.

<h2>ACCOMMODATION</h2>

Course participants are accommodated in the Dish Hotel which is situated in the center of Enschede,
ten minutes' walk from the ITC building.

<h2>STUDY COSTS, SUBSISTENCE AND ACCOMMODATION EXPENSES</h2>

The course fees for the 11-month FOR.3 course are NLG 11,000 and for the 18-month FOR.2 course
NLG 23,500. Additional fixed costs for FOR.2/3 courses are a maximum NLG 5,850. Subsistence
allowance including accommodation is estimated at NLG 1,500 per person per month. Please note that
international travel expenses are not included.

<h2>FELLOWSHIPS</h2>

For FOR.2 and FOR.3 course applicants from selected developing countries, the Netherlands
government awards some fellowships under the Netherlands Fellowship Programme (NFP). In
accordance with Netherlands government policy, women are especially encouraged to apply. NFP
fellowship applications should be submitted through the appropriate organization in the candidate's
home country and with the approval of the candidate's employer, to reach the Royal Netherlands
Embassy at least four months before the starting date of the course. 
<p>
Since the number of NFP fellowships is rather limited, course applicants are advised to try to obtain
funding from other donor agencies. Details and addresses of sponsors in the applicant's country can
be obtained from the ITC Student Registration Office. Please note that ITC has no funds of its own,
neither does ITC have any influence on those organizations that grant fellowships.

<h2>FURTHER INFORMATION</h2>

The International Institute for Aerospace Surveys and Earth Sciences (ITC) is the largest institute for
international higher education in the Netherlands. The main objective of ITC is to assist developing
countries in human resources development in aerospace surveys, remote sensing applications, the
establishment of geographic information systems and the management of geographic information.
<p>
To this end, ITC concentrates on three main activities: education/training, research and advisory
services. In-house expertise covers an extensive range of disciplines in the fields of aerospace data
acquisition and processing, photogrammetry, cartography, land resource and urban sciences and earth
resource surveys. More details on ITC, the courses it offers and their costs are available in ITC's
General Information brochure. This brochure and other information can be obtained from:
<p>
<pre>
ITC Student Registration Office
Attn. Mrs. A. Scheggetman
P.O. Box 6
7500 AA  Enschede
The Netherlands

Phone : +31 (0)53 874 205
Fax   : +31 (0)53 874 238
Telex : 44525 itc nl
E-mail: <a href="mailto:scheggetman@itc.nl">scheggetman@itc.nl</a>
</pre>
<p>
All ITC courses are regularly revised and updated. The information here applies only to the 1996 course.
This leaflet will be updated each year and new copies can be obtained from the ITC Student
Registration Office.

