<body>

<img src="/itc.gif" alt="ITC">
<hr>

<h2>POSTGRADUATE DIPLOMA COURSE FRD.3</h2>

<h1>FORESTRY FOR RURAL DEVELOPMENT 1995</h1>

Trees and other woody plants play an important and frequently indispensable role in sustainable rural
development in the tropics. Trees are a source of wood and other products, they contribute to the
productive capacity of agricultural lands and they are considered to be highly protective of the
environment.
<p>
Rural forestry focuses on the planning, management and controlled utilization of forests and trees in
rural areas. The involvement of local people in the different stages of planning and implementation is a
specific characteristic of rural forestry.
<p>
The course (course code FRD.3) is organized by ITC's Forest Science Division of the Department of Land
Resource and Urban Sciences. Related courses include forest survey, rural and land ecology survey, soil
survey and socio-economic information for natural resource management.

<h2>OBJECTIVES</h2>

The general objective of the course is to develop the participants' knowledge and skills to enable them to
prepare alternative models, suitable for integration in land use planning activities, which strengthen
the place and role of trees and shrubs for sustainable rural development.
<p>
Upon completion of the course, participants should be able to:
<ul>
<li>identify the place and role of trees and shrubs within a land use system;
<li>plan and implement appropriate survey techniques, including technical, social and economic
   analytical tools to evaluate issues of supply and demand;
<li>describe the role of rural communities in woody biomass development, using a participatory
   approach;
<li>tap and systematize the pool of indigenous knowledge and practices;
<li>describe the constraints and opportunities for improving the management of woody biomass
   resources;
<li>integrate the above in a set of alternative development plans.
</ul>
<p>
To achieve these objectives, participants will:
<ul>
<li>be involved in a participatory educational process;
<li>communicate and interact with participants from other courses involved in natural resource
   management;
<li>critically analyze their own working practices;
<li>develop understanding and skills in survey techniques relevant for rural forestry, with emphasis on
   "rapid rural appraisal" techniques;
<li>apply and validate acquired knowledge and skills under field conditions;
<li>use GIS techniques for developing alternative management models.
</ul>

<h2>TARGET GROUPS</h2>

The course is designed for:
<ul>
<li>foresters involved in community forestry projects and programmes;
<li>officers from related backgrounds engaged in rural development;
<li>teachers and trainers in the field of forestry for rural development;
</ul>

<h2>ADMISSION REQUIREMENTS AND APPLICATIONS</h2>

For admission to the FRD.3 course, applicants should hold a BSc or BA degree from a recognized
university, in forestry, agricultural or rural development, or be able to demonstrate an equivalent level of
education in one of these disciplines. Preferably they should also have some years of working experience. 
<p>
Interpretation of aerial photographs and satellite images is an important part of the course curriculum.
Candidates should therefore have good stereoscopic vision as well as normal colour vision. Proficiency in
the English language (minimum requirement Test of English as a Foreign Language (TOEFL) 500 or
British Council test 6.0) is also required.
<p>
Applications for academic admission should be forwarded directly to ITC using the official application form
which is available from ITC's Student Registration Office.

<h2>COURSE STRUCTURE AND CONTENTS</h2>

The training method followed in the course is based on the participants' experience and was especially
developed for adult learning.
<p>
The curriculum is divided into four cycles and consists of lectures, practicals, workshops, participants'
contributions, literature review and excursions. Fieldwork forms an important and integral part of the
course. Four weeks of fieldwork will be carried out in a tropical country.
<p>
<b>Cycle 1</b> (7 weeks): Concepts and approaches:
<br>
A Introduction to natural resource management
<br>
B Analysis of participant's own (forestry) situtation and working experience
<br>
C Identification of social and cultural factors influencing rural forestry. With emphasis on the following:
<ul>
<li>introduction to rural development;
<li>relation farmer-forester and social forestry;
<li>common property resource management;
<li>indigenous knowledge and tree management practices and agroforestry;
<li>rural energy
</ul>
D Development of an approach for FRD.
<p>
<b>Cycle 2</b> (20 weeks): Survey techniques and tools:
<br>
A Introduction on data collection and survey methods
<br>
B The following tools and techniques used in the field of FRD are emphasized:
<ul>
<li>participatory and rapid rural appraisal (PRA and RRA);
<li>aerial photograph and map interpretation;
<li>tools and techniques to identify the place and role of trees and shrubs;
<li>rural energy surveys;
<li>remote sensing/GIS;
<li>computer handling
</ul>
C Land use planning
<br>
D Integration of the tools and techniques with the developed approach for FRD.
<p>
<b>Cycle 3</b> (12 weeks): Fieldwork programme:
<br>
A Preparation for fieldwork
<br>
B Fieldwork in a (sub-)tropical country
<br>
C Reporting on fieldwork activities and results
<br>
D Fieldwork seminar.
<p>
<b>Cycle 4</b> (6 weeks): Applications:
<br>
A Personal study topic
<br>
B EXIT workshop with special emphasis on:
<ul>
<li>how to apply newly acquired knowledge and skills in your personal career;
<li>how to introduce newly acquired knowledge and skills in your organisation.
</ul>

<h2>STARTING DATE AND DURATION</h2>

In 1996 the FRD.3 course starts in the second week of August and lasts 11 months. The first week is
reserved for the introduction and the last week for presentations of final assignment results, clearance
formalities and the diploma presentation.
<p>
Participants who plan to study Forestry for Rural Development at MSc level should apply for the FOR.2
MSc course and indicate clearly Forestry for Rural Development as the field of study. A brochure with
more details about the FOR.2 MSc course, including an application form, can be obtained from the ITC
Student Registration Office.

<h2>QUALIFICATION AWARDED</h2>

After completing the course and passing the required examination, participants are awarded a
postgraduate diploma accompanied by a course record.

<h2>ACCOMMODATION</h2>

Course participants are accommodated in the DISH Hotel. This is situated in the centre of Enschede,
ten minutes' walk from the ITC building.

<h2>STUDY COSTS, SUBSISTENCE AND ACCOMMODATION EXPENSES</h2>

The course fees for the 11-month FRD.3 course are NLG 11,000. Additional fixed costs for the FRD.3
course are NLG 4,300. Subsistence allowance including accommodation is estimated at NLG 1,545 per
person per month. Please note that international travel expenses are not included.

<h2>FELLOWSHIPS</h2>

For FRD.3 course applicants from selected developing countries, the Netherlands government awards
some fellowships under the Netherlands Fellowship Programme (NFP). In accordance with Netherlands
government policy, women especially are encouraged to apply. NFP fellowship applications should be
submitted through the appropriate organization in the candidate's home country and with the approval of
the candidate's employer, to reach the Royal Netherlands Embassy at least four months before the
starting date of the course. 
<p>
Since the number of NFP fellowships is rather limited, course applicants are advised to try to obtain
funding from other donor agencies. Details and addresses of sponsors in the applicant's country can be
obtained from the ITC Student Registration Office. Please note that ITC has no funds of its own, nor does
ITC have any influence on those organizations that grant fellowships.

<h2>FURTHER INFORMATION</h2>

The International Institute for Aerospace Surveys and Earth Sciences (ITC) is the largest institute for
international higher education in the Netherlands. The main objective of ITC is to assist developing
countries in human resources development in aerospace surveys, remote sensing applications, the
establishment of geographic information systems and the management of geoinformation.
<p>
To this end ITC concentrates on three main activities: education/training, research and advisory services.
In-house expertise covers an extensive range of disciplines in the fields of aerospace data acquisition and
processing, photogrammetry, cartography, land resource and urban sciences and earth resource surveys.
More details on ITC, the courses it offers and their costs are available in ITC's General Information
brochure. This brochure and other information can be obtained from:
<p>
<pre>
ITC Student Registration Office
Attn. Mrs. A. Scheggetman
P.O. Box 6
7500 AA  Enschede
The Netherlands

Phone     : +31 (0)53 874 205
Fax       : +31 (0)53 874 238
Telex     : 44 525 itc nl
E-mail    : <a href="mailto:scheggetman@itc.nl">scheggetman@itc.nl</a>
</pre>
<p>
All ITC courses are regularly revised and updated. The information here applies only to the 1996 course.
This leaflet will be updated each year and new copies can be obtained from the ITC Student Registration
Office.

