<head>
<title>
RLE.3
</title>
</head>
<body>

<img src="/itc.gif" alt="ITC">
<hr>


<h2>POSTGRADUATE DIPLOMA COURSE RLE.3</h2>

<h1>RURAL AND LAND ECOLOGY SURVEY 1996</h1>

The 'green cover' of the Earth, including both agricultural crops and natural vegetation, provides the materials
to meet the basic needs of mankind for food, fuel, fiber and shelter. The increasing size and demands of the
population cause a continuous change of the green cover of the earth. This process may be the direct result
of operations on a particular piece of land, or it may be an indirect result of, for example, pollution or global
atmospheric change.
<p>
Up-to-date knowledge on the state of the green cover of the earth, and the agricultural land use which affects
it, is essential for the sustainable development of agricultural lands, as well as the conservation of our natural
heritage. The survey of the green cover and the way it is exploited, with the modern techniques remote sensing
(RS) and geographic information systems (GIS) is the focal point of this course.
<p>
The postgraduate diploma course (course code RLE.3) is organized by the Vegetation and Agricultural
Sciences Division within ITC's Department of Land Resource and Urban Sciences. The department also offers
courses in the fields of forest survey, soil survey, urban survey, and socio-economic information for natural
resources management.
<p>
The participants of the Msc course follow the taught modules of the postgraduate course, after which they
begin with an individual research project, resulting in a thesis. For further information please refer to the
brochure on the MSc course.

<h2>OBJECTIVES</h2>

The learning objective of the course is to develop the participant's skills to survey plant cover and agricultural
land use in rural, i.e. non-urban, areas using remote sensing and GIS techniques.
<p>
To achieve these objectives, the course is designed to improve the participants' ability to:
<ul>
<li>translate the geoinformation requirements on plant cover and agricultural land use of a client agency into
specific objectives, methodologies and a survey plan and to carry out the survey;
 <li>collect ground survey data on plant cover and agricultural land use;
 <li>correlate ground survey data with aerial photography and satellite images in a GIS environment;
 <li>prepare a plant cover or agricultural land use database and map.
</ul>

<h2>TARGET GROUPS</h2>

The course is designed for mid career professionals requiring training in the survey of plant cover and
agricultural land use for rural development, environmental conservation or natural resource management
purposes.
<p>
The course therefore addresses primarily those with a professional background in agriculture, rangeland
management, landscape ecology, environmental management, nature conservation or related subjects. They
may be working in survey and rural development organizations, extension services, research institutes and
university departments, or projects and non-governmental organizations.

<h2>ADMISSION REQUIREMENTS AND APPLICATIONS</h2>

Applicants should hold a BSc or BA degree from a recognized university, in agricultural science, biological or
environmental sciences or geography or be able to demonstrate an equivalent level of education in one of
these disciplines.
<p>
Interpretation of aerial photographs and satellite images is an important part of the course curriculum.
Candidates should therefore have good stereoscopic vision as well as normal colour vision.
<p>
Proficiency in the English language (minimum requirement Test of English as a Foreign Language (TOEFL)
500 or British Council test 6.0) is also required.
<p>
Applications for academic admission should be forwarded directly to ITC using the official application form
which is available from ITC's Student Registration Office.

<h2>COURSE STRUCTURE AND CONTENTS</h2>

The curriculum is divided into modules, all including theoretical and practical work. Detailed objectives and
schedules for each module are given in the RLE.3 course calendar, which will be mailed upon request to the
Director of Studies, Dr. H. van Gils.
<p>
The natural resource management module aims to develop a better understanding of the need and the
potential of geoinformation in natural resource management, through analysis of problems and solutions in the
management of natural resources brought forward by the course participants.
<p>
The plant cover and agricultural land use survey module aims to provide the knowledge and skills to
design and carry out a survey of plant cover and agricultural land use, including photo interpretation, the
collection and classification of ground truth data and the production of a plant cover or agricultural land use
map.
<p>
The land evaluation module aims to provide an introduction to the concepts and procedures of land
evaluation and to raise an awareness of how land evaluation can be utilized for agricultural land use planning
in the context of natural resource management.
<p>
The RS/GIS module aims to provide skills in the use of remote sensing and GIS technology for the survey
of plant cover and agricultural land use.
<p>
During the postgraduate case study module, the students are trained to prepare and carry out a plant cover
or agricultural land use survey.
<p>
The exit module aims to prepare the participants to apply the newly acquired skills in their future careers.
Particular attention will be paid to how to introduce these skills in the organization in which the participant is
employed.

<h2>STARTING DATE AND DURATION</h2>

In 1996 the RLE.3 course will start in the second week of August and will last 11 months. The first week is
reserved for the introduction and the last week for presentations of final assignment results, clearance
formalities and the diploma ceremony.

<h2>QUALIFICATION AWARDED</h2>

After completing the RLE.3 course and passing the required examinations, participants are awarded a
postgraduate diploma accompanied by a course record.

<h2>ACCOMMODATION</h2>

Course participants are accommodated in the Dish Hotel. This is situated in the center of Enschede, ten
minutes' walk from the ITC building.

<h2>STUDY COSTS</h2>

The course fees for the 11-month RLE.3 course are NLG 11,000. Additional fixed costs for RLE.3 courses are
NLG 3,900. Subsistence allowance including accommodation is estimated at NLG 1,500 per person per month.
Please note that international travel expenses are not included.

<h2>FELLOWSHIPS</h2>

For RLE.3 course applicants from selected developing countries, the Netherlands' Government awards some
fellowships under the Netherlands Fellowship Programme (NFP). In accordance with Netherlands Government
policy, women especially are encouraged to apply. NFP fellowship applications should be submitted through
the appropriate organization in the candidate's home country and with the approval of the candidate's employer,
to reach the Royal Netherlands Embassy at least four months before the starting date of the course.
<p>
Since the number of NFP fellowships is rather limited, course applicants are advised to try to obtain funding
from other donor agencies. Details and addresses of sponsors in the applicant's country can be obtained from
the ITC Student Registration Office. Please note that ITC has no funds of its own, neither does ITC have any
influence on those organizations that grant fellowships.

<h2>FURTHER INFORMATION</h2>

The International Institute for Aerospace Surveys and Earth Sciences (ITC) is the largest institute for
international higher education in the Netherlands. The main objective of ITC is to assist developing countries
in human resources development in aerospace surveys, remote sensing applications, the establishment of
geographic information systems and the management of geoinformation.
<p>
To this end ITC concentrates on three main activities: education/training, research and advisory services. In-
house expertise covers an extensive range of disciplines in the fields of aerospace data acquisition and
processing, photogrammetry, cartography, land resource and urban sciences and earth resource surveys.
More details on ITC, the courses it offers and their costs are available in ITC's General Information brochure.
This brochure and other information can be obtained from:

<pre>
ITC Student Registration Office
Attn. Mrs. A. Scheggetman
P.O. Box 6
7500 AA  Enschede
The Netherlands

Phone     : +31 (0)53 874 205
Fax       : +31 (0)53 874 238
Telex     : 44525 itc nl
E-mail    : <a href="mailto:scheggetman@itc.nl">scheggetman@itc.nl</a>
</pre>

All ITC courses are regularly revised and updated. The information here applies only to the 1995 course. This
leaflet will be updated each year and new copies can be obtained from the ITC Student Registration Office.

<p>
