<title>
SIG.2 and SIG.3
</title>
</head>
<body>

<img src="/itc.gif" alt="ITC">
<hr>

<h2>POSTGRADUATE DIPLOMA AND MSC DEGREE COURSES SIG.2/3</h2>

<h1>SOCIO-ECONOMIC INFORMATION FOR NATURAL RESOURCE MANAGEMENT 1996</h1>

The courses in Socio-Economic Information for Natural Resource Management (NRM) are designed to improve
effective information management within and between the various parties -government, NGOs, researchers and
resource users- involved in data collection and decision- making in NRM.
<p>
The courses develop knowledge and skills in the inter-connected fields of: spatial aspects of land and resource
planning and policy support, and information acquisition and its management, with a particular focus on geo-
referenced, socio-economic information.
<p>
The MSc degree course code is "SIG.2" (18 months) and the postgraduate diploma course code is "SIG.3" (11
months).
<p>
Within the MSc degree course, natural resource management issues can be addressed through specializations in
land use planning or rural energy development.
<p>
The programme is organized by the Social Science Division within ITC's Department of Land Resource and Urban
Sciences. The department also offers courses in rural and land ecology survey, forestry for rural development,
environmental systems analysis and monitoring, urban survey, soil survey, forest survey, and geographic
information systems for rural applications and for urban applications.

<h2>OBJECTIVES</h2>

The objectives of SIG courses are to provide a theoretical background and practical training in tasks of
strengthening decision-making in spatial aspects of development planning and natural resource management.
<p>
Upon completion of either course, participants should be able to:
<ul>
<li> assess the information needs of decision makers in the fields of NRM;
<li> design, execute and interpret different types of surveys to collect socio-economic information;
<li> determine the useful socio-economic information that can be extracted from maps, aerial photos and remote
sensing;
<li> analyze and manage the information to provide useful outputs to support decision-making;
<li> utilize a number of tools, techniques and models supporting decision-making in these fields.
</ul>
<p>
To achieve these objectives, participants will:
<ul>
<li> obtain theoretical knowledge through lectures and literature study;
<li> train in practial skills in exercises and field visits;
<li> prepare multidisciplinary approaches in team-work with other courses;
<li> prepare for and execute fieldwork;
<li> write a final report (SIG.3) or an MSc thesis (SIG.2).
</ul>

<h2>TARGET GROUPS</h2>

The courses are designed for mid-career specialists from institutions associated with spatial development planning
and NRM at national, sub-national and rural scales, of whom the majority have been trained and work in either
the social and economic sciences or in natural resources. Some, but not all participants may have special
experience in information collection and management.

<h2>COURSE STRUCTURE AND CONTENTS</h2>

The courses run together for the first seven months untill February 1997, following which they separate into: the
postgraduate diploma course (SIG.3) for four more months, and the MSc degree course (SIG.2) for 11 more
months.
<p>
The emphasis of SIG.3 is on tools and techniques; whereas the emphasis of SIG.2 is on the theoretical basis and
concepts of the fields of socio-economic information in NRM.

<h3>POSTGRADUATE DIPLOMA COURSE (SIG.3)</h3>

The curriculum of the SIG.3 course is divided into a number of blocks as shown in the following:
<p>

<h3>SIG.3 and SIG.2 (combined)</h3>
Block 1 (2 weeks) Natural resource management (NRM)
<br>
Block 2 (4 weeks) Socio-economic information requirements for decision-making in NRM
<br>
Block 3 (4 weeks) Socio-economic data collection methods
<br>
Block 4 (2 weeks) Information from maps, aerial photos and remote sensing for socio-economic surveys
<br>
Block 5 (4 weeks) Information structuring and analysis for decision support methods in NRM
<br>
Block 6 (4 weeks) Land evaluation and land use planning
<br>
Block 7 (8 weeks) Remote sensing and geographical information systems
<br>
<h3>SIG.3</h3>
Block 8 (16 weeks) Preparation for and execution of SIG.3 field work, and exit workshop

<h3>MSC DEGREE COURSE (SIG.2)</h3>

The first seven blocks of the SIG.2 course are identical to the SIG.3 course. The remainder of the programme
offers two different specializations in natural resource management: Land Use Planning or Rural Energy and
Development.
<p>
The specialisations continue for four months course work (March through June) with blocks of lectures, practicals
and workshops, and with emphasis given to library research, self-study and seminars.
<p>
The final and significant element of the MSc programme is the writing of a research thesis which involves
literature review, research design, field research, writing and presentation, within the context of social science
research interests. This occupies the final seven months, July to January.
<p>
In addition to the objectives of the overall SIG course, the Land Use Planning specialisation should improve the
participants' abilities to:
<ul>
<li> analyze the issues, institutions and parties involved in land use planning for development;
<li> design social survey techniques for land use planning information requirements, including airphoto
interpretation, socio-economic surveys and rapid rural appraisal;
<li> utilize and interpret GIS tools for land use planning;
<li> assess and perform techniques in land use planning, including land evaluation, environmental impact
assessment, economic evaluation, and decision support methods;
<li> critically assess information needs for implemention of policy instruments in land use planning/NRM policies.
</ul>
<p>
The objectives of the Rural Energy Development specialization in SIG.2 are to improve the participants' ability
to:
<ul>
<li> utilize social and economic analytical tools for rural energy planning;
<li> model and analyze relationships between rural energy planning and land use planning;
<li> critically assess decision support methods and policy instruments for rural energy/environment policies;
<li> determine information needs and design surveys in three energy planning areas: energy needs, natural resources,
and technology options.
</ul>
<p>
Note: Students opting for the 18 month rural energy specialisation in SIG.2 will join with the course, 'Forestry
for Rural Development' (FRD.3) for most of their first seven months, focussing on woody biomass energy. If you
are interested in the RED specialisation, please request the special brochure on 'MSc degree courses in rural energy
and development'.

<h2>ADMISSION REQUIREMENTS AND APPLICATIONS</h2>

For admission to the SIG.3 and SIG.2 courses, applicants should hold a BSc or BA degree from a recognized
university in one of the earth, agricultural or social sciences, or be able to demonstrate an equivalent level of
education in one of these disciplines. Preferably they should also have some years of working experience.
<p>
Applicants for either course should have gained their BSc degree with good marks. In order to continue with the
SIG.2 course, students should attain an average weighted mark of at least 75% during the SIG.3/SIG.2 combined
course (the first seven months), and should show an aptitude for independent study and field research.
<p>
Interpretation of aerial photographs and satellite images is an important part of the course curriculum. Candidates
should therefore have good stereoscopic vision as well as normal colour vision. Proficiency in the English
language is also required (minimum requirement Test of English as a Foreign Language (TOEFL) 500 or British
Council test 6.0).
<p>
Applications for admission should be forwarded directly to ITC using the official application form which is
available from ITC's Student Registration Office.

<h2>STARTING DATE AND DURATION</h2>

In 1996 the courses in Socio-Economic Information for Natural Resource Management start in the second week
of August and last 11-months (SIG.3) or 18-months (SIG.2). The first week is reserved for the introduction and
the last week for presentations of final assignment results, clearance formalities and the diploma/degree ceremony.

<h2>QUALIFICATION AWARDED</h2>

After completing the course and passing the required examinations, participants are awarded a postgraduate
diploma (SIG.3) or an MSc degree (SIG.2) accompanied by a course record.

<h2>ACCOMMODATION</h2>

Course participants are accommodated in the Dish Hotel which is situated in the centre of Enschede, ten minutes'
walk from the ITC building.

<h2>STUDY COSTS, SUBSISTENCE AND ACCOMMODATION EXPENSES</h2>

The course fees for the 11-month SIG.3 course are NLG 11,000 and that of the 18-month SIG.2 course NLG
23,500. Additional fixed costs for SIG.2/3 courses are a maximum NLG 5,100. Subsistence allowance including
accommodation is estimated at NLG 1,500 per person per month. Please note that international travel expenses
are not included.

<h2>FELLOWSHIPS</h2>

For SIG.2 and SIG.3 course applicants from selected developing countries, the Netherlands' Government awards
some fellowships under the Netherlands Fellowship Programme (NFP). In accordance with Netherlands
government policy, women especially are encouraged to apply. NFP fellowship applications should be submitted
through the appropriate organization in the candidate's home country and with the approval of the candidate's
employer, to reach the Royal Netherlands Embassy at least four months before the starting date of the course.
<p>
Since the number of NFP fellowships is rather limited, course applicants are advised to try to obtain funding from
other donor agencies. Details and addresses of sponsors in the applicant's country can be obtained from the ITC
Student Registration Office. Please note that ITC has no funds of its own, neither does ITC have any influence
on those organizations that grant fellowships.

<h2>FURTHER INFORMATION</h2>

The International Institute for Aerospace Surveys and Earth Sciences (ITC) is the largest institute for international
higher education in the Netherlands. The main objective of ITC is to assist developing countries in human
resources development in aerospace surveys, remote sensing applications, the establishment of geographic
information systems and the management of geoinformation.
<p>
To this end ITC concentrates on three main activities: education/training, research and advisory services. In-house
expertise covers an extensive range of disciplines in the fields of aerospace data acquisition and processing,
photogrammetry, cartography, land resource and urban sciences and earth resource surveys. More details on ITC,
the courses it offers and their costs are available in ITC's General Information brochure. This brochure and other
information can be obtained from:

<pre>
ITC Student Registration Office
Attn. Mrs. A. Scheggetman
P.O. Box 6
7500 AA  Enschede
The Netherlands

Phone :    +31 (0)53 874 205
Fax   :    +31 (0)53 874 238
Telex :    44525 itc nl
E-mail:    <a href="mailto:scheggetman@itc.nl">scheggetman@itc.nl</a>
</pre>

All ITC courses are regularly revised and updated. The information here applies only to the 1996 course. This
leaflet will be updated each year and new copies can be obtained from the ITC Student Registration Office.

<p>
