<html>
<head>
<title>
GIC.2, GIU.2, GIR.2, GIC.3, GIU.3 and GIR.3
</title>
</head>
<body>

<img src="/itc.gif" alt="ITC">
<hr>

<h2>POSTGRADUATE DIPLOMA AND MSc DEGREE COURSES  GIC/GIU/GIR</h2>

<h1>GEOINFORMATION SYSTEMS FOR CADASTRAL, URBAN AND RURAL APPLICATIONS 1995</h1>

Geographic information systems (GIS) are used for the capture, storage, integration, analysis and
retrieval of spatially referenced data. Such systems have a wide range of applications, including 
land registration, urban and regional planning and natural resource management. ITC offers
postgraduate diploma and Master of Science degree courses in the application, development and
management of geographic information systems in three specializations: for cadastral (GIC),
urban (GIU) and rural (GIR) applications. 
<p>
The codes of the postgraduate diploma courses are GIC.3, GIU.3 and GIR.3 and of the MSc degree
courses GIC.2, GIU.2 and GIR.2, respectively. The courses are organized by an interdepartmental
course board of the departments of Geoinformatics and of Land Resource and Urban Sciences.
The GIR.2 course is organized in cooperation with the Wageningen Agricultural University.

<h2>OBJECTIVES</h2>

To prepare staff from organizations dealing with land related data to initiate, stimulate and
manage the process of developing of a digital geographic information system (GIS) in their
organization.
<p>
To prepare staff from educational institutes to develop course elements related to the
establishment and operation of geographic information systems.
<p>
Upon completion of the courses, participants should be able to:
<ul>
<li>analyze the information requirements of an organization;
<li> contribute to the design of an appropriate GIS;
<li>contribute to managing the process of change from an analogue to a digital environment;
<li> identify the technical capabilities of a range of systems;
<li> plan, design, implement and maintain a GIS in an application area relevant to their
organization;
<li>design and carry out an individual research project utilizing GIS (MSc).
</ul>
<p>
To achieve these objectives, participants will:
<ul>
<li>take part in lectures, case studies and practicals to gain theoretical knowledge and technical
experience (postgraduate);
<li>expand on theoretical subjects, prepare and carry out research projects and write a thesis
(MSc).
</ul>

<h2>TARGET GROUPS</h2>

The courses address active professionals in senior technical or managerial positions in
organizations dealing with land related data. They are or will be involved in the design, planning
and application of a geographic information system in their organizations. Participants will
generally have a background in one of the spatial sciences (e.g., land surveying, cartography,
photogrammetry, urban and regional planning, geography, agricultural sciences, forestry,
environmental sciences, etc.) 

<h2>ADMISSION REQUIREMENTS AND APPLICATIONS</h2>

For admission to these courses, applicants should hold a BSc degree from a recognized
university in one of the spatial sciences, or be able to demonstrate an equivalent level of
education. Preferably they should also have some years of working experience. 
<p>

Applicants for the MSc courses should have gained their BSc degree with good marks. They
should attain an average weighted mark of at least 75 in the Postgraduate course and show an
aptitude for independent study.
<p>
Proficiency in the English language is also required (minimum requirement Test of English as a
Foreign Language (TOEFL) 500 or British Council test 6.0).
<p>
Applications for admission should be forwarded directly to ITC using the official application form
which is available from ITC's Student Registration Office.

<h2>COURSE STRUCTURE AND CONTENT</h2>

<h3>Postgraduate diploma courses (GIC.3, GIU.3, GIR.3)</h3>

<p>
Block I:  Fundamentals of GIS (3 months):
<br>
including computing, theory of GIS, spatial data capture, processing and visualization,
information analysis, database design and implementation.
<p>
Block II: Specialization per application area and common technical training in dBase IV, Arc/Info,
ILWIS (3 months):
see below.
<p>
Block III:Management of information systems (2 months):
<br>
system development methodology, economics of GIS, GIS management issues, municipal
information system design and implementation, system specifications, software training on CASE
tools.
<p>
Compulsory and/or optional subjects:
<br>
linear programming, cadaster and land reform, advanced databases, Arc/Info under Unix, Oracle,
national information infrastructure, project planning and management of change, etc.
<p>
Block IV:Final project (3 months):
<br>
Individual project work on participant's own subject of interest.

<h3>Master of Science courses  (GIU.2 GIC.2 GIR.2)</h3>
<p>
Blocks I, II and III as above, continuing with: 
<p>
Block V: Advanced course work (4 months)
<br>
advanced GIS and database subjects, knowledge-based systems and application- specific
subjects. Starting and managing thesis research.
<p>
Block VI: Research (fieldwork) and thesis writing  (maximum 9 months).
<p>

<h2>GIS FOR CADASTRAL APPLICATIONS</h2>

The cadastral specialization is conducted predominantly by the Department of Geoinformatics. It
is designed for professionals working with multi-purpose land management organizations such as
cadastre, land registry, valuation and taxation departments, local governments, surveying and
mapping organizations, utility companies. 
<p>

The specialization consists of a series of theoretical and practical modules in GIS theory,
computer science, information analysis and modelling and aspects of (multi-purpose) cadastre.
Practicals are organized around actual multi-purpose cadastre problems (condensed to case
studies). Practicals are carried out in small groups using personal and mini computers and on
advanced workstations. Participants gain knowledge and experience with several systems, dealing
with tasks ranging from data capture to visualization.
<p>
In addition to the common subjects described above, the following specialization subjects are
given:
<ul>
<li>      land registration and cadastre;
<li>      cadastral surveying and mapping;
<li>design and implementation of integrated cadastral databases;
<li>cadastral database implementation on various systems (dBase IV, Microstation, PC-Arc/Info,
Informix, Oracle);
<li>multipurpose cadaster GIS/LIS, property valuation and taxation, land consolidation;
<li>real estate management;
<li>utility information systems;
<li>decision support systems;
<li>facility management.
</ul>
<p>
In the MSc course the participant specializes in a conceptual, technical or application-oriented
topic of GIS. Subjects are related to advances in databases and knowledge-based systems, spatial
modelling, information system infrastructure, development and maintenance.
Research is related to the research programme of the Department of Geoinformatics. The
personal interest of the participant is also taken into consideration.

<h2>GIS FOR URBAN APPLICATIONS</h2>

The urban specialization is conducted by the Division of Urban Survey and Human Settlement
Analysis within the Department of Land Resource and Urban Sciences. Emphasis is on
applications of GIS for:
<ol>
<li>strategic urban planning: land use monitoring, structure plan
preparation, urban modelling environmental planning.
<li>operational planning: the development of systems to support plan implementation and
administration such as for development control or plot allocation, utility network management,
etc.
</ol>
<p>
The specialization consists of a series of lectures and complementary application practicals. The
practicals are organized around actual urban planning problems (condensed to case studies) and
illustrate how particular types of software can contribute to analysis and design of alternatives.
Practicals are carried out individually or in small groups of two or three persons using personal
computers. 
<p>
In addition to the common subjects described above, the following specialization subjects are
given:
<ul>
<li>statistical analysis for urban policy evaluation;
<li>analytical urban thematic mapping;
<li>land use change analysis;
<li>site suitability analysis and site selection;
<li>catchment-area analysis;
<li>facility planning;
<li>urban modelling;
<li>locational geography;
<li>      software training on  SPSS, Arc/Info-CAD, ILWIS.
</ul>
<p>
In the MSc course the participant specializes in a technical or application topic of urban
information systems, depending on his/her personal interest and/or professional occupation.
Research is related to the research programme of the division. MSc research may be carried out
using advanced workstations.


<h2>GIS FOR RURAL APPLICATIONS</h2>

The rural specialization is conducted by various divisions of the Department of Land Resource
and Urban Sciences. Emphasis is on the understanding of procedures of data capture and
processing as practiced by earth- and social scientists.
<p>
The specialization examines the characteristics of geographic information systems in
organizations to support environmental monitoring and planning, regional and agricultural
development planning, water resource management, etc.
Management of the process of change from an analogue to a digital environment is emphasized.
Participants take part in formal lectures, practicals and case studies.
<p>
In addition to the common subjects described above, the following specialization subjects are
given:
<ul>
<li>      data capture through remote sensing and image processing;
<li>land evaluation and land use planning with GIS;
<li>information analysis on regional planning and natural resource management organizations;
<li> land registration and land reform;
<li> linear programming and modelling techniques;
<li> decision support systems;
<li>software training on Arc/Info, ILWIS, etc.
</ul>
<p>
The MSc course is offered in cooperation with the Wageningen Agricultural University (WAU) and
participants will follow blocks V and VI at WAU. At WAU, participants follow further GIS, database
and knowledge systems theory, which can be complemented with a choice of subjects from the
MSc courses offered by the University.
Thesis work is preferably done in the context of ongoing research at ITC and the University.
Individual preferences are taken into consideration.

<h2>STARTING DATE AND DURATION</h2>

The GIS courses start in the first week of September. The Postgraduate courses last 11 months
and the MSc courses last 21 months (Rural 17 months). The first week is reserved for the
introduction and the last week for presentations of final assignment results, clearance
formalities and the diploma/degree ceremony.

<h2>QUALIFICATION AWARDED</h2>

After completing the course and passing the required examinations, participants are awarded a
postgraduate diploma or an MSc degree accompanied by a course record.

<h2>ACCOMMODATION</h2>

Course participants are accommodated in the Dish Hotel which is situated in the center of
Enschede, ten minutes' walk from the ITC building.
<p>
During blocks V and VI, GIR.2 course participants are accommodated by Wageningen Agricultural
University in Wageningen.

<h2>STUDY COSTS</h2>

The course fees for the 11-month Postgraduate GIS courses are NLG 11,000 and for the 21-
month MSc GIS courses NLG 26,500 (Rural NLG 22,500). Additional fixed costs for the
Postgraduate GIS courses are NLG 3,800 and for the MSc courses NLG 5,200. Subsistence
allowance including accommodation is estimated at NLG 1,500 per person per month. Please note
that international travel expenses are not included.


<h2>FELLOWSHIPS</h2>

For Postgraduate and MSc course applicants from selected developing countries, the Netherlands
government awards some fellowships under the Netherlands Fellowship Programme (NFP). In
accordance with Netherlands government policy, women especially are encouraged to apply. NFP
fellowship applications should be submitted through the appropriate organization in the
candidate's home country and with the approval of the candidate's employer, to reach the Royal
Netherlands Embassy at least four months before the starting date of the course. 
<p>
Since the number of NFP fellowships is rather limited, course applicants are advised to try to
obtain funding from other donor agencies. Details and addresses of sponsors in the applicant's
country can be obtained from the ITC Student Registration Office. Please note that ITC has no
funds of its own, nor does ITC have any influence on those organizations that grant fellowships.

<h2>FURTHER INFORMATION</h2>

The International Institute for Aerospace Surveys and Earth Sciences (ITC) is the largest institute
for international higher education in the Netherlands. The main objective of ITC is to assist
developing countries in human resources development in aerospace surveys, remote sensing
applications, the establishment of geographic information systems and the management of
geoinformation.
<p>
To this end ITC concentrates on three main activities: education/training, research and advisory
services. In-house expertise covers an extensive range of disciplines in the fields of aerospace
data acquisition and processing, photogrammetry, cartography, land resource and urban sciences
and earth resource surveys. More details on ITC, the courses it offers and their costs are
available in ITC's General Information brochure. This brochure and other information can be
obtained from:

<pre>
ITC Student Registration Office
Attn. A. Klijnstra
P.O. Box 6
7500 AA  Enschede
The Netherlands

Phone     : +31-53-874 207
Fax       : +31-53-874 238
Telex     : 44525 itc nl
E-mail    : <a href="mailto:klijnstra@itc.nl">klijnstra@itc.nl</a>
</pre>

All ITC courses are regularly revised and updated. The information here applies only to the 1995
courses. This brochure will be updated each year and new copies can be obtained from the ITC
Student Registration Office.

<p>
