<h2>MSC DEGREE COURSE  RLE.2</h2>

<h1>RURAL AND LAND ECOLOGY SURVEY 1996</h1>
<p>
The 'green cover' of the earth, which includes both agricultural crops and natural vegetation, provides
basic needs of mankind. The increasing size and demand of the population causes a continuous change
of the green cover of the earth. 
<p>
Sustainable development of agricultural lands, as well as the conservation of our natural heritage, requires
up-to-date information on plant cover and agricultural land use.  Mapping and monitoring techniques
contribute to the acquisition of this information. Modelling, land evaluation and land use planning methods
integrate this information with data from other sources and provide management options.
<p>
The course (course code RLE.2) is organized by the Vegetation and Agricultural Sciences Division within
ITC's Department of Land Resource and Urban Sciences, which also organizes other courses in the field
of forest survey, soil survey, urban survey and socio-economic information for natural resource
management.
<p>
A closely related course is the postgraduate diploma course in Rural and Land Ecology Survey (RLE.3)
and the MSc degree course in Environmental Systems Analysis and Monitoring (ESM.2).

<h2>OBJECTIVES</h2>

The MSc course is designed to train the participants in the mapping and monitoring of plant cover and
agricultural land use, and the application of the results of these surveys for a specific objective such as
rural development, natural resource management or environmental conservation.

<h2>TARGET GROUPS</h2>

The course is designed for mid-career professionals requiring training in the survey and interpretation of
plant cover and agricultural land use data for rural development, environmental conservation and/or
natural resource management purposes, and who are pursuing an academic MSc degree.
<p>
This course will address primarily professionals with a background in the fields of agriculture, nature
conservation, rangeland management, landscape ecology, environmental management or related subjects
working in survey and rural development organizations, extension services, research institutes and
university departments, or projects and non-governmental organizations. 

<h2>ADMISSION REQUIREMENTS AND APPLICATIONS</h2>

Applicants should hold a Bachelor's Degree from a recognized university in agriculture, biological or
environmental sciences, geography or be able to demonstrate an equivalent level of education. Preferably
they should also have some years of working experience.
<p>
Interpretation of aerial photographs and satellite images is an important part of the course curriculum.
Candidates should therefore have good stereoscopic vision as well as normal colour vision.
<p>
Sufficient proficiency in the English language (minimum requirement Test of English as a Foreign
Language (TOEFL) 500 or British Council test 6.0) is required.
<p>
Applications for academic admission should be forwarded directly to ITC using the official application form
which is available from ITC's Student Registration Office.

<h2>COURSE STRUCTURE AND CONTENTS</h2>

The course is divided into modules, all including theoretical and practical work. Detailed objectives and
schedules for each module are given in the RLE.2 course calendar, which will be mailed upon request to the
Director of Studies, Dr. H. van Gils.
<p>
The natural resource management module aims to develop a better understanding of the need and
   the potential of geoinformation in natural resource management, through analysis of problems and
   solutions in the management of natural resources brought forward by the course participants.
<br>
The plant cover and agricultural land use survey module aims to provide the knowledge and skills
   to design and carry out a survey of plant cover and agricultural land use, including photo interpretation,
   the collection and classification of ground truth data and the production of a plant cover or agricultural
   land use map.
<br>
The land evaluation module provides an introduction to the concepts and procedures of land evaluation
   and to raise the awareness how land evaluation can be utilized for land use planning in the context of
   natural resource management.
<br>
The remote sensing/GIS module aims to provide skills in the use of remote sensing and GIS technology
   for the survey of plant cover and agricultural land use.
<p>
In the module of advanced subjects, topics will be treated relevant for the research module such as
databases, advanced GIS and remote sensing, agro-ecological and spatial modelling, or decision support
systems, etc.
<p>
In the research module the students are trained to prepare and execute a research project. This mostly
includes fieldwork in a (sub)tropical country and results in an individual thesis.

<h2>STARTING DATE AND DURATION</h2>

In 1996 the RLE.2 course starts in the second week of August and lasts 18 months. The first week is reserved
for the introduction and the last week for presentations of final assignment results, clearance formalities and
the degree ceremony.

<h2>QUALIFICATION AWARDED</h2>

After completing the RLE.2 course and passing the required examinations, participants are awarded an MSc
Degree accompanied by a course record.

<h2>ACCOMMODATION</h2>

Course participants are accommodated in the DISH Hotel which is situated in the centre of Enschede, ten
minutes' walk from the ITC building.

<h2>STUDY COSTS</h2>

The course fees for the 18-month RLE.2 course are NLG 23,500. Additional fixed costs for the RLE.2 course
are NLG 5,300. Subsistence allowance including accommodation is estimated at NLG 1,500 per person per
month. Please note that international travel expenses are not included.

<h2>FELLOWSHIPS</h2>

For RLE.2 course applicants from selected developing countries, the Netherlands Government awards some
fellowships under the Netherlands Fellowship Programme (NFP). In accordance with Netherlands Government
policy, women especially are encouraged to apply. NFP fellowship applications should be submitted through
the appropriate organization in the candidate's home country and with the approval of the candidate's
employer, to reach the Royal Netherlands Embassy at least four months before the starting date of the course. 
<p>
Since the number of NFP fellowships is rather limited, course applicants are advised to try to obtain funding
from other donor agencies. Details and addresses of sponsors in the applicant's country can be obtained from
the ITC Student Registration Office. Please note that ITC has no funds of its own, neither does ITC have any
influence on those organizations that grant fellowships.

<h2>FURTHER INFORMATION</h2>

The International Institute for Aerospace Surveys and Earth Sciences (ITC) is the largest institute for
international higher education in the Netherlands. The main objective of ITC is to assist developing countries
in human resources development in aerospace surveys, remote sensing applications, the establishment of
geographic information systems and the management of geoinformation.
<p>
To this end ITC concentrates on three main activities: education/training, research and advisory services. In-
house expertise covers an extensive range of disciplines in the fields of aerospace data acquisition and
processing, photogrammetry, cartography, land resource and urban sciences and earth resource surveys.
More details on ITC, the courses it offers and their costs are available in ITC's General Information brochure.
This brochure and other information can be obtained from:

<pre>
ITC Student Registration Office
Attn. Mrs. A. Scheggetman
P.O. Box 6
7500 AA  Enschede
The Netherlands

Phone : +31 (0)53 874 205
Fax   : +31 (0)53 874 238
Telex : 44525 itc nl
E-mail: <a href="mailto:scheggetman@itc.nl">scheggetman@itc.nl</a>
</pre>

All ITC courses are regularly revised and updated. The information here applies only to the 1996 course. This
leaflet will be updated each year and new copies can be obtained from the ITC Student Registration Office.

