<html>
<head>
<title>
SIG.5
</title>
</head>
<body>

<img src="/itc.gif" alt="ITC">
<hr>

<h1>WORKSHOP INFORMATION MANAGEMENT FOR NATURAL RESOURCE DEVELOPMENT</h1>


Economic development and concern for the environment require that
land resources should be handled with care.
<p>
Governmental institutions play an important role in influencing the process
of land use.
<p>
This is also referred to as Land Use Planning, Spatial Planning or Zoning.
Such planning requires a large amount of information on the natural
resources and on how people use them.
<p>
This information should be available to an organisation in a form and
correlation with other information that allows analysis comparison.
<p>
Data collection on land and land use has improved in the past decades
through the use of remote sensing.
<p>
Data storage and processing has improved with digital data base
techniques and the development of Geographic Information Systems
(GIS).
<p>
Quality of decisions can be improved trough the development of an
organization's information system which combines man, knowledge,
hardware and software. 
<p>
Organisations involved in land management deal with complex problems
and therefore have complex information systems.
It is vital that these systems should be well defined, developed and
managed in order to prevent inappropriate decisions and wasted
investments.
<p>
It is of great importance that management and staff of these organisations
are fully aware of the methods of information system development for their
particular type of work and the scope and limitations of techniques such as
remote sensing and GIS.
<p>
ITC's three-week workshop on Information Management for Natural
Resource Development has been designed for this purpose.
<p>
The workshop deals with the question of how geographic information
Systems can be used in organizations which deal with aspects of natural
resource management. It gives participants insight in theoretical, practical
and managerial aspects of GIS technology.
<p>
The code of the workshop is "SIG-5".
It is organized by ITC's department of Land Resource and Urban Sciences
and an interdepartmental course board on Geo Information Systems. 
<p>
The department also offers courses in: 
<ul>
<li><b>FOR</b>  Forest Survey
<li><b>RLE</b>  Rural and Land Ecology Survey
<li><b>USH</b>  Urban Survey and Human Settlement Analysis
<li><b>FRD</b>  Forestry for Rural Development
<li><b>SIG</b>  Socio-Economic Information for Natural Resource Management
<li><b>ESM</b>  Environmental Systems Analysis and Monitoring
<li><b>GIR</b>  Geographic information Systems for Rural Applications
<li><b>GIU</b>  Geographic information Systems for Urban Applications
</ul>




<h2>OBJECTIVES</h2>

To present an overview of aspects of the design, implementation and
management of GIS for land management organisations.
<p>
To explain the elements and functions of GIS.
<p>
To specify the data, data storage and data processing requirements of
information systems for land management.
<p>
To consider the managerial aspects of introducing digital information
technology in an organization.
<p>
To give participants some practical training with GIS.
<p>

Upon completion of the workshop, participants should be able to:
<ul>
<li>initiate, stimulate and participate in the process of information system
design and implementation;
<li> contribute to the specification of the data and information requirements
of the home organization;
<li> advice on the methods to be used to introduce digital information systems in
land- related organizations.
</ul>
<p>
To achieve these objectives participants will:
<ul>
<li>gain theoretical knowledge on geographic information systems for natural
resource management;
<li>be exposed to methods and techniques for system development;
<li>elaborate a case study with practical exercises;
<li>exchange experiences with fellow participants and ITC staff.
</ul>

<h2>TARGET GROUPS</h2>

The workshop is designed for senior level technical and management
staff of organizations handling land- related data for rural development,
environmental management, water resource development, etc.
It is also suitable for staff from universities, research and survey institutes,
etc., working in similar areas of specialization. 
 
<h2>ADMISSION REQUIREMENTS</h2>

Participants should hold a senior position with a reasonable amount
work experience in their organizations and have a good working knowledge
of English.
Some basic computer handling experience is an advantage but not a 
prerequisite. A maximum of 16 persons can be accommodated in the
workshop.
<p>
Applications for academic admission should be forwarded directly to
ITC using the official application form which is available from ITC's Student
Registration Office.

<h2>Workshop Structure and Contents</h2>

<dl>
<dt>Part 1.   NATURAL RESOURCE MANAGEMENT

<dd>Management will be discussed in the context of tasks of organizations. 
This requires a clear definition of what is to be managed, who is the
manager, and how this management can best be utilized and implemented
(what are the tools available).
<p>
The information required for management can then be assessed. Questions
will be raised and scenarios presented and workshop participants will be
actively involved in exercise to relate these to their own organizations.


<p>
<dt>Part 2.   INFORMATION SYSTEMS AND GIS.

<dd>The history of Information Systems and GIS is presented.
The characteristics of information systems in land management organisations
are further analyzed and the character of the spatial data (geo data) is
investigated.  
<p>
The theory and techniques of spatial data handling will be briefly outlined.
Participants will learn about the elements and operations of GIS.
<p>
Finally the specifications for a GIS to support management tasks can
be assessed.

<p>
<dt>Part 3.   DATA CAPTURE, STORAGE AND PROCESSING.

<dd>Attention is given to spatial data capture with the help of remote sensing
techniques.
Techniques for non spatial data acquisition are also discussed.
<p>
The data must be stored in a database for which an appropriate design
has to be made.
The theory of data modelling is discussed.
<p>
Modelling and optimization techniques to process data into information
are also reviewed.

<p>
<dt>Part 4.   EXERCISE TO DESIGN, IMPLEMENT AND OPERATE A GIS
     FOR NATURAL RESOURCE MANAGEMENT.

<dd>Participants will apply these techniques to an organization and carry out
an exercise with GIS software to familiarize themselves with the strengths
and weaknesses of such techniques for their management tasks.
<p>
Special attention is given to the management of the process of information
system development and implementation: which subsystems should receive
priority; how the correct hard and software can be selected, installed and
operated; what organizational changes are required.
<p>
Time is reserved for discussions, exchange of experiences and presentations
by the participants.
<p>
There are several workshop related excursions (in the Netherlands). 
</dl>


<h2>STARTING DATE AND DURATION</h2>

In 1996 the workshop will start in the first week of March and last three
weeks.


<h2>QUALIFICATION AWARDED</h2>

Participants will receive a certificate of attendance. 


<h2>ACCOMMODATION</h2>

Workshop participants are accommodated in the Dish Hotel. This is situated
in the centre of Enschede, ten minutes' walk from the ITC building.


<h2>STUDY COSTS, SUBSISTENCE AND ACCOMMODATION EXPENSES</h2>

The fees for the three-week SIG.5 workshop are NLG 1,000.
Additional fixed costs are NLG 1,200. Subsistence allowance including
accommodation is estimated at NLG 1,500 per person per month. Please
note that the international travel expenses are not included. 

<h2>FELLOWSHIPS</h2>

For SIG.5 workshop applicants from selected developing countries, the
Netherlands government awards some fellowships under the Netherlands
Fellowship Program (NFP). In accordance with the Netherlands government
policy women especially are encouraged to apply. NFP fellowship
applications should be submitted through the appropriate organization in the
candidate's country and with the approval of the candidate's employer, to
reach the Royal Netherlands Embassy at least 4 months before the starting
date of the workshop.
<p>
Since the number of fellowships is rather limited, workshop applicants
are advised to try to obtain funding from other donor agencies. Details
and addresses of sponsors in the applicant's country can be obtained
from ITC Student Registration Office. Please note that ITC has no funds of
its own, nor does ITC have any influence on those organizations that grant
fellowships.

<h2>Further Information.</h2>

A shorter version of the workshop (one or two weeks) can also be given at
ITC or abroad. If required, it can be adapted to specific requirements.
For more information please contact ITC Consultancy Services, P.O.Box 6,
7500 AA Enschede.
<p>
The International Institute for Aerospace Surveys and Earth Sciences
(ITC) is the largest institute for international higher education in the
Netherlands. The main objective of ITC is to assist developing countries
in human resources development in aerospace surveys, remote sensing
applications, the establishment of geographical information systems and the
management of geoinformation.
<p>
To this end ITC concentrates on three main activities: education/training,
research and advisory services. In-house expertise covers an extensive
range of disciplines in the fields of aerospace data acquisition and
processing, photogrammetry, cartography, land resource and urban sciences
and earth resource surveys. More details on ITC, the courses it offers and
their costs are available in ITC's General Information brochure. This brochure
and other information can be obtained from:

<pre>
ITC Student Registration Office
Attn. Ms. A. Scheggetman
P.O. Box 6
7500 AA  Enschede
The Netherlands

Phone   : +31-53-874 205
Fax     : +31-53-874 238
Telex   : 44525 itc nl
E-mail  : <a href="mailto:scheggetman@itc.nl">scheggetman@itc.nl</a>
</pre>

All ITC courses are regularly revised and updated. This brochure will
be updated each year and new copies can be obtained from the ITC
Student Registration Office.

<p>
