<html>
<head>
<TITLE>IPL Services</TITLE>
</head>
<body>

<pre>
<img src="/itc.gif" alt="ITC">                        <img src="/ipl.gif" alt="IPL">
</pre>
<p>

<hr>
<H1>IPL Services</H1>

The Image Processing Laboratory (IPL) of ITC offers several production services to staff and
students from ITC and <i>third parties</i>. Since there have been changes in the hard- and software configuration at the IPL
in the recent years, a new overview of the total package of services is required. In first instance we
will use the Geoinformatics Quarterly Report to inform staff from the Department on our services.
Eventually we will inform the rest of ITC via the CCRS.
<p>
The production services of IPL can be subdivided into four main categories :
<ul>
<li>Input
<li>Image Processing/Conversion
<li>Output
<li>Network
</ul>


<h2>Input Services</h2>

IPL can import data from various systems into its environment. Basically there are two types of input
:
<ul>
<li>    Extracting <b>digital</b> data from computer storage media (e.g. tapes, floppy disks)
<li>    Scanning <b>hardcopy</b> material (e.g. maps, photographs)
</ul>

For scanning, the IPL has a SHARP JX-300 color scanner (A4 size) connected to an Archimedes RISC
Computer. The scanner is capable of scanning at a maximum resolution of 300 dpi in Black and
White or in 24 bit color (256 steps in Red, Green and in Blue). The output from the scanning
system is a TIFF file which can be converted to various other formats on various different media (for
details please read Output Services).
<p>
IPL has contacts with other laboratories that can scan at higher densities
and larger formats.
<p>
The IPL has access to the following input devices :
<ul>
<li>hp2      - DAT (Digital Audio Tape) 1.2 Gb capacity
<li>hp2      - MO (Magneto-Optical) 2x650Mb capacity
<li>hp2      - Floppy disks (3&#189;" High Density)
<li>sun1     - QIC Streamer tape 250 Mb capacity
<li>sun2     - CCT (Computer Compatible Tapes) reader (1600-6250 bpi density)
<li>sun2     - EXABYTE (8mm) 2.5Gb+5Gb+compressed capacity
<li>sun2     - CD-ROM (ISO 9660)
<li>pc        - QIC Streamer Tape (DOSARCH)
<li>pc        - QIC Streamer Tape (SYTOS)
<li>pc        - Floppy disks (3&#189;", 5&#188;" Low/High Density)
<li>Frame grabbers - single frame from VHS and SVHS both PAL as well as NTSC
</ul>


The image data on the media can have the following formats :
<ul>
<li> ILWIS                  
<li>GIF
<li> ERDAS (lan, gis, ant)       
<li>PM (Portable Map)
<li> ERDAS (img)            
<li>PBM (Portable Bit Map)
<li> POSTSCRIPT             
<li>X11 (Bitmap)
<li> PCX                         
<li>IRIS
<li> SUN RASTER FILE        
<li>JPEG
<li> TIFF                        
<li>BMP (Windows Bitmap)
<li> GRID (ARC/INFO)             
<li>GRASS
<li> SPANSS                 
<li>X windows raster 
<li>and many others!
</ul>
<p>

IPL can also handle data which has been compressed or combined into an archive. The following
archives can be read :
<ul>
<li> DOSARCH format (QIC Streamer Tape)  
<li> SYTOS format (QIC Streamer Tape)
<li> UNIX tar and cpio archives (on DAT, EXABYTE or CD-ROM)
<li> UNIX compress and gzip
<li> FASTBACK archives
<li> DOS BACKUP archives (only for some specific versions of DOS)
<li> PKZIP and Unix zip
</ul>

Data can only be extracted from the media which is used for the input devices, when the data
format/structure is known. If the structure is not known then extraction can become a time
consuming trial and error procedure.


<h2>Processing/Conversion Services</h2>

Since the IPL is an image processing laboratory the possibilities in processing of data are almost
unlimited. Within the framework of this report just a few important and usually time consuming
procedures will be mentioned :
<ul>
     <li>    Radiometric and geometric corrections. Geo-referencing can be done if Ground
          Control (Maps or GPS) is supplied.
     <li>    Contrast enhancement, saturation enhancement, spatial enhancement (filtering).
     <li>    Spectral and spatial classification.
     <li>    DEM generation from stereoscopic SPOT data or aerial photographs. Ortho image
          generation from SPOT data or aerial photographs.
</ul>

The processing will in general be executed on the Hewlett Packard (HP) Unix Workstations. Only for specific
tasks or software IPL will rely on the SUN Workstations (Context Vision environment, Prodigeo) or on PC
configurations.
<p>
All machines of IPL are in a network offering a flexible working environment
for processing of large data sets.
<p>
A lists of image processing software packages at hand at the IPL :
<ul>
<li><a href="/ilwis/">Ilwis</a> (PC)
<li>Erdas (PC)
<li>Erdas (HP Workstation)
<li>Erdas IMAGINE (HP Workstation)
<li>XV (HP Workstation)
<li>DMS/SPM (PC)
<li>Alexander (PC)
<li>Alexander (Archimedes)
<li>Context Vision (SUN Workstation)
<li>Prodigeo (SUN Workstation)
<li>Khoros (HP Workstation)
</ul>


<h2>Output services</h2>

Output can be generated onto two different categories of media :
<ul>
<li>    Computer storage media (tapes, floppies etc.)
<li>    Hard copies on other media
</ul>

The long list of available input devices can serve (in reverse) as a list for the output devices
by IPL, except we don't have a CD-R (CD-Recordable). Thus data in various formats (see list of input formats) can transferred to
CCT, DAT, EXABYTE, Floppy disk, streamer tape etc. 
<p>
Hard copies can be generated on different quality levels. A lower quality can be generated
quickly and is usually cheaper.
<p>
Low quality (thermal wax color prints):
<ul>
<li>    300 dpi, 8 colors, A3 size print on paper
<li>    150 dpi, 125 colors, A3 size print on paper
<li>    100 dpi, 1000 colors, A3 size print on paper
<li>    75 dpi, 1728 colors, A3 size print on paper
</ul>

Medium quality (B&W and ink-jet):
<ul>
<li>    300 dpi B&W laserprint, A4 and A3 size print on paper
<li>    600 dpi B&W laserprint, A4 and A3 size print on paper
<li>    300 dpi color inkjet print, A4 and A3 on paper
</ul>

High quality :
<p>
The IPL has an Optronics film writer, which is capableof writing 10*10 inch
films at resolutions of 100, 50 and 25 micron! The following films can be used:
<ul>
<li>B&W negative (256 levels)
<li>Colour positives (16.7 mil. colors)
</ul>

The low quality color prints can be copied on color copy machines without loosing to much
information.
The high quality film plots can be enlarged by ITC Photolab up to a maximum size of 50*60 cm
(CIBACHROME). For larger formats the film has to be processed externally, by companies who will
charge exceptional prices. A format of > 100*100 cm within 24 hours service can be processed by
a photolab in Enschede. Output will have slightly reduced quality because of an additional
conversion to negative film.

<h2>Network Services</h2>
In addition to the above mentioned traditional input, output and Image
Processing services the IPL is also exploring the virtual world of the
Information Highway, the <i>Internet</i>. Currently the IPL runs the following
services:
<ul>
<li>An FTP-server on <a href="ftp://ftp.itc.nl/">ftp://ftp.itc.nl</a>
<li>A WWW-server on <a href="http://www.itc.nl/">http://www.itc.nl</a>
</ul>

If you need more information about these services,
please contact the IPL staff at
<address>
<a href="mailto:ipl@itc.nl">ipl@itc.nl</a>
</address>
<br>
Furthermore, we welcome your <i>contributions</i> to these services.

<p>
