</DOCHDR>
<H1>Introduction</H1>

At the start of the BCRS project Alexander: "A computer interactive learning package
for applications of Remote Sensing and Geo-Information Systems (RS & GIS)" the
project team was optimistic about the availability of both CD-ROM hardware, software
and applications. However, suitable standards were slow in coming and not generally
applicable. Potential users were slow in buying. And RS data sellers were raising their
prices even for data intended for the educational data. A half year before the end of
the project it was decided to spend more time on investigating the emerging
standards and markets and to delay the production of a sample disc until the
occasion of a specific request of a buyer.
<P>
Considering the data - in the case of GIS - "vector" data are already supported via
public domain maps on floppy disc or other media. And, increasingly, scanned raster
maps with one form or other of data compression become available or can be
generated on request.
In the case of Remote Sensing data the most important data are digitized
photographs. The analog to digital conversion can be done locally with 800 dpi to
1000 dpi scanners and the Kodak PhotoCD (Professional) offers interesting
possibilities.
However the availability of other Remote Sensing data is not as widespread and cost
effective as had been hoped for.
<P>
Therefor this report concentrates on available types of Remote Sensing data and
present options for storing on and retrieving data from CD-ROM under a wide variety
of formats.
<p>
<i>Prof. N.J. Mulder</i>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT10-B02-256</DOCNO>
