<H1>The Image Atlas</H1>


An image atlas is a collection of marvellous images. These images are not just
beautiful to look at: they also can be used for a diversity of applications in daily life.
With these images floods can be predicted or icebergs detected. With these images
a geologist can discriminate details which lead him to underground water-stores and
new deposits of mineral resources. With these images maps can be made of the
vegetation in large areas.
Many more applications are possible, <A href="#table 1">table 1</A> lists just a few.
<P>
Examining the earth from space looks like a wonderful means. Most of the scientists
are enthusiastic. Some scientist air their criticism and refuse to see the potential
these images can offer. The best way is to see for yourself and judge if these images
offer anything else besides just beauty. And to try and recognize and understand the
many details these images show; possibly aided by proven Image Processing and
GIS techniques.
<P>
In order to give maximum flexibility for selecting images for exercises a good Image
Atlas should cover a number of examples from the following items:
<UL>
     <LI><A href="table3.html">Types of Satellites</A> (Platforms)
     <LI><A href="table3.html">Types of Sensors</A> (spatial, temporal and spectral resolution)
     <LI>Digitized Aerial Photographs
     <LI><A href="#table 2">Regions of the World</A>
     <LI><A href="#table 1">Application Areas</A>
</UL>
This way the designer
of exercises has the maximum degree of freedom to design exercises and the trainee
can pick an image matching his own interest.
<P>
For more GIS based applications it might be useful to add the following items:
<UL>
     <LI>Vector maps
     <LI>Digital Elevation Models
</UL>
These can aid the interpretation of a satellite image.
<P>
The next chapter goes into more detail about some Platforms and their sensors.
Chapter 3 gives a description of the New Media: the CD-ROM. Chapter 4 describes
the latest descendant of the CD-ROM family: the Kodak Photo CD. A manual of the
Freeware program hpcdtoppm - it can convert the Kodak PCD image format - can be
found in appendix G. Appendix F lists some commonly used CD-ROM Drives and
Recorders. The other appendices list a large number of Institutes, Organizations,
Companies and Persons that supply data on CD-ROM.
<P>
