<H1>Satellite Platforms and their Sensors</H1>

<H2>Sensors</H2>

A major characteristic of an image in Remote Sensing is the wavelength band it
represents. Some images are measurements of the spatial disposition of reflected
solar radiation in the ultraviolet, visible and near-to-middle infrared range of
wavelengths. Others are measurements of the spatial distribution of energy emitted
by the earth itself (dominant in the so-called thermal infrared wavelength range); yet
others, particularly in the microwave band of wavelengths, measure the relative return
from the earth's surface of energy actually transmitted from the vehicle itself. Systems
of this last type are referred to as active since the energy source is provided by the
Remote Sensing platform; by comparison Remote Sensing measurements that
depends upon an external energy source, such as the sun, are called passive.
Together with the frame size of an image, in equivalent ground kilometres, the
number of spectral bands, radiometric resolution, temporal resolution and spatial
resolution determine the data volume provided by a particular sensor and thus
establish the amount of data to be processed. As an illustration consider the Landsat
Thematic Mapper instrument. It has 7 wavelength bands with 8 bit radiometric
resolution, which have 30m spatial resolution. [Band 6 of TM - the thermal band - is in fact
lower in radiometric as well as spatial resolution, 7 bits and 120m, but is usually supplied in the same -
 resampled - sample size as the other bands]. An image frame of 185 km x 185 km therefore
represents approximately 270 Mbytes of digital image data.

<H2>Weather Satellite Sensors</H2>

Weather Satellites and those used for earth resources sensing operate in much the
same bands of wavelength. Perhaps the major distinction in the image data they
provide lies in the temporal and spatial resolution available. Whereas data acquired
for earth resources purposes generally has pixels** that represent samples** which
cover an area on the earth of less than 100 meter by 100 meter, that used for
meteorological applications usually has much coarser samples - often of the order of
1 km x 1 km or even 5 km x 5 km. Having made this distinction however it is
important to note that because of similarity in wavebands, meteorological satellite
data such as that from the <a name="noaa"><strong>NOAA</strong></a> Advanced Very High Resolution** Radiometer
(AVHRR) does find application in Remote Sensing when large synoptic views are
required. The temporal resolution (time interval between samples of the same location
on earth) of weather satellites is high. <a name="meteosat"><strong>Meteosat</strong></a> 30 minutes, NOAA 11+12
approximately every 2 hours, SPOT 26 days, Landsat 16 days.
<P>
[** Please note that a pixel is the representation of a sample of the real world. As such it doesn't have
a size of its own, but often the term pixelsize is loosely used for the size of the sample of a certain
pixel. Resolution is defined as the smallest distance between objects before they become
indistinguishable. Resolution is not necessarily the same as the sample size! Furthermore note that
the sample size and resolution can be used for spatial as well as temporal, spectral and radiometric
measurements. So although the NOAA satellite in fact has a LOW spatial resolution scanner (1.1km)
it has a Very High temporal, spectral and radiometric Resolution scanner. Radiometric resolution is the
number of significant greylevels of the sensor; often 8 bit (256 levels). NOAA gives 10 bit (1024).]
<H2>Earth Resource Satellite Sensors</H2>
The <A name="landsat"><STRONG>LANDSAT</STRONG><A> earth resources satellite system was the first designed to provide near
global coverage of the earths's surface on a regular and predictable basis.
Consequently it has been the "workhorse" image data acquisition system for Remote
Sensing purposes and has become the benchmark against which newer systems are
judged. The first three Landsats have identical orbit characteristics. The orbits are
near polar and sun synchronous - i.e., the orbital plane precesses about the earth at
the same rate that the sun seems to rotate around the earth. In this manner data is
acquired at about the same local time on every pass. All Landsat satellites acquire
image data nominally at 9:30 AM local "sun" time on a descending (North to South)
path. Fourteen orbits are covered each day, and the fifteenth, at the start of the next
day, is 159 km advanced from orbit 1, thus giving a second day coverage continuous
with that of the first day. This advance in daily coverage continues for 18 days and
then repeats. Consequently complete coverage of the earth's surface is given, with
251 revolutions in 18 days.
<P>
Three Imaging instruments have been used with the Landsat satellites. These are the
<a href="#rbv"><EM>Return Beam Vidicon</EM></a> (RBV), the <a href="#mss"><EM>Multispectral Scanner</EM></a> (MSS) and the
<a href="#tm"><EM>Thematic Mapper</EM></a> (TM).
<P>
As the name suggests the <A name="rbv"><em>RBV</em></A>'s were essentially television camera-like instruments
that took "snapshot" images of the earth's surface along the track of the satellite.
Image frames of 185x185km were acquired each shot, repeated at 25 s intervals to
give contiguous frames in along track direction at the equivalent ground speed of the
satellite. Three RBV cameras were used on Landsat 1 and 2, distinguished by
different transmission filters that allowed three spectral bands of data to be recorded.
In Landsat 3 two RBV cameras were used; however both operated panchromatically
and were focused to record data swaths of 98 km, overlapped to give a total swath
of about 185 km. By doing so a higher (40m) spatial resolution was possible
compared to the earlier RBV system (80m).
<P>
The Multispectral Scanner or <A name="mss"><em>MSS</em></A> has been carried by all five Landsat satellites. It
is a line scanner which sweeps the ground below the satellite and builds up an image
of the earth's surface as the satellite moves along the track. Because the velocity of
the spacecraft is to high to permit the scanning of the image one line at the time, a
total of six scan lines are viewed by the sensor for each sweep of the mirror that
directs reflected light from the ground. The forward motion of the satellite is such that
the mirror is back in position to scan the next six lines after it has completed its
retrace cycle. The scanner collects data in four spectral bands. A fifth band, operating
in the thermal infrared region, was included in the MSS carried by Landsat 3.
However, very little data became available due to failure soon after launch.
<P>
The <A name="tm"><em>Thematic Mapper</em></A> is a mechanical scanning device as for the MSS, but has
improved spectral, spatial and radiometric characteristics. Seven wavelength bands
are used. Note that band 7 is out of place in the progression of wavelengths as it was
added after the initial phase at the request of the geological community. Whereas the
MSS of all Landsats scans and obtains data in one direction  only, the TM acquires
data in both scan directions again with a swath width of 185 km. Sixteen scan lines
are swept simultaneously giving a 480 m strip across the satellite path. This permits
a lower mirror scan rate compared with the MSS and thus gives a higher effective
dwell time for a given spot on the ground, making possible the higher spatial
resolution and improved dynamic range.
<P>
The French satellites <a name="spot"><strong>SPOT</strong></a> 1, 2 and 3 (Systeme Probatoire d'Observation de la
Terre), launched respectively in 1986, 1990 and 1993, carry two imaging devices
referred to as <a name="hrv"><em>HRV</em></a>'s. These instruments utilize a different technology for image
acquisition from that employed in the Landsat MSS and TM devices. Rather than
using oscillating mirrors to provide cross-track scanning during the forward motion of
the space platform, the SPOT HRV instruments consist of a linear array of charge
coupled device (CCD) detectors. These form what is commonly referred as a "push
broom" scanner. Each detector in the array scans a strip in along track direction - by
several thousand such detectors a wide swath can be imaged without the need for
mechanical scanning. Moreover, owing to the long effective dwell time this allows for
each pixel, it has a higher spatial resolution. A trade-off however is that CCD
technology was not available for wavelengths into the middle infrared range at the
time of early SPOT development. Consequently the spectral bands provided by the
HRV are not unlike those of the Landsat MSS. An interesting property of the HRV is
that it incorporates a steerable mirror to allow imaging to either side of the nadir. This
allows daily coverage for a short period along with a stereoscopic viewing capability.

<h2>Radar Remote Sensing</h2>

Remote Sensing image data in the microwave range of wavelengths is generally
gathered using the technique of side-looking radar. When used with aircraft platforms
it is more commonly called <a name="slar"><strong>SLAR</strong></a> (Side-Looking Airborne Radar). For space-borne
platforms a 20m azimuth resolution would require an antenna of 1km length, which
is clearly impracticable. Therefore when radar image data is to be acquired from
spacecraft, a modification of SLAR, referred to as Synthetic Aperture Radar or <a name="sar"><strong>SAR</strong></a>
is used. Essentially this utilizes the motion of the space vehicle, during transmission
of the ranging pulses, to give an effectively long antenna, or so-called synthetic
aperture.
<P>
The first earth observational space mission to carry a synthetic aperture imaging
radar was the <a name="seasat"><strong>Seasat</strong></a> satellite launched in June 1978. Although only short lived it
recorded about 126 million square kilometres of image data, including multiple
coverage of many regions.
<P>
A modified version of the Seasat SAR was flown as the <a name="sir-a"><strong>SIR-A</strong></a> sensor on the second
flight of <a name="shuttle"><strong>Space Shuttle</strong></a> in November of 1981. In contrast to Seasat however, in which
the data was digital, the data in SIR-A was recorded and processed optically and thus
is available only in film format. In eight hours SIR-A collected data of 10 million km2
of the Earth's surface - including many inaccessible areas, covered almost
continuously by cloud, which were imaged for the very first time. The objectives of the
mission were:
<ul>
  <li>to carry out geoscientific investigations, which required a radar system alone
     or in combination with other sensors.
  <li>to explore areas that are difficult to study using visible and thermal sensors,
     e.g. cloudy areas, dense forests.
</ul>
<P>
Like Seasat and SIR-A, <a name="sir-b"><strong>SIR-B</strong></a> operated in the L-band (23 cm) and was horizontally
polarised. However, SIR-B was designed to acquire digitally processed imagery at
selectable incidence angles between 15&#176; and 60&#176;. Topography is revealed best at low
incidence angles, with higher angles providing more information on surface
roughness. The ability to image a specific area at a variety of incidence angles would
provide an excellent means of characterising the terrain. Thus, one central objective
of the SIR-B experiment was to study the effect of different illumination geometries
on the data to allow decisions about the design of future imaging radar systems.
<P>
A feature of the later <a name="sir-c"><strong>SIR-C</strong></a> instrument due for launch in 1994 will be the use of cross
polarized returns (VH and HV) and the use of multiple wavelengths (L X and C band).
<p>
Modern radar satellites include the <a name="ers-1"><strong>ERS-1</strong></a> and <a name="jers-1"><strong>JERS-1</strong></a>. The ERS-1 carries a number
of sensors, one of which is a synthetic aperture radar intended largely for sea state
and oceanographic application but more and more  recognized as being very useful
for other applications as well. The JERS-1 carries two imaging instruments; one is an
optical sensor - called <a name="ops"><em>OPS</em></a> - with provision for stereoscopic imaging and the other
an imaging radar.
<p>
Canada intends orbiting a synthetic aperture radar satellite, to be known as <a name="radarsat"><strong>Radarsat</strong></a>
in December 1994. The data provided will be a valuable complement to that from
ERS-1 and JERS-1. Radarsat will also be able to operate in several non-standard
imaging modes, including one which will give a 510 km swath.
<p>
Airborne imaging radar systems in SLAR and SAR technologies are also available.
As with airborne multispectral scanners these offer a number of advantages over
equivalent satellite based systems including flexibility in establishing mission
parameters and proprietary rights to data. However the cost of data acquisition is also
high.

<h2>Aerial Photography and Photography from Space</h2>

Around 1839 Photography was developed by two frenchmen Niepce and Daguerre.
Already shortly after the invention cameras were taken on <strong>hot-air-balloon</strong> flights.
These first aerial photographs were meant as a curiosity, but soon the military
recognized the strategic importance. Due to this military interest a lot of effort was put
into technical improvement of the equipment. Around 1850 the french officer Lausedat
developed a special camera for topographic images. Besides airballoons also <strong>kites</strong>
and <strong>rockets</strong> were used to carry cameras. Around 1858 the french balloonist
Tournachon was the first to use aerial photographs for the production of maps. Only
small areas were covered. With the invention of the <strong>Zeppelin</strong> large areas were
systematically photographed because the Zeppelin was steerable. However, until the
coming of the <strong>aeroplane</strong>, maps were still created by surveyors. It wasn't until 1930
before producers of maps started to use aerial photographs as the very basis for their
maps. Thus it became possible to map in a short time even areas were surveyors
can't go. In 1932 the Topographische Dienst of the Netherlands started using aerial
photographs.
<p>
<a name="aerial photo">Aerial photographs</a> for the production of maps can only be taken with precision
instruments under very favourable circumstances. Only a few companies have the
men and material at their disposal to take vertical aerial photographs. The basis of
the equipment is a small yet powerful aeroplane (usually twin-engined) that can fly
a stable course at low altitudes. The camera is mounted in a hole of the hull with the
lens pointing vertically downwards. The aerographical film must be of a very high
quality and must not show any geometrical distortions during and after exposure. In
the fine grain structure of the film even very small objects remain visible.
<p>
During a photoflight there must be a good cooporation between the pilot and the
navigator/photographer. At the preparation of the flight the altitude, type of camera,
type of film and the route are determined according to the demands of the client. The
flight must be done in straight line. Beforehand these lines are drawn in a map
including information about the altitude and course. The navigator leads the flight. He
supplies the pilot with course corrections and operates the camera. The photographs
must form straight strips and overlap about 60% for stereoscopic processing at a later
stage. The camera must be kept horizontal and parallel to flying direction as much
as possible. The pilot tries to keep a constant altitude and speed and takes care to
keep the plane stable (no pitch, yaw or roll), even during course corrections.
However the weather remains the most important factor for usable photographs. The
best time of year is the period between half of February and the end of May. Because
of the higher sun not many details are lost in the shadows, and because the trees
don't have leaves yet little remains hidden underneath. Furthermore flown can be only
on days with sunny and clear weather. So only a few days per year are suited for
making aerial photographs.
<p>
First an aerial photograph must corrected and interpreted. Information not clear from
the photograph is checked in the field. Next to the aerial photography,
photogrammetry plays an important roll in the production of maps. This science
developed techniques and equipment for doing very accurate measurements in aerial
photographs. For the photogrammetric processing very precise instruments are
needed because measurements must be done at just a few hundredths of a
millimetre. For example at a scale of 1:10,000 10 cm in the terrain is equivalent to
0.01 mm on the photograph. This 0.01 mm (10 micrometer) is also the approximate
resolution of aerographic film. So, supposing the film can shown 256 shades of grey
(= 8 bit or 1 byte), the data content of a 10x10" panchromatic film is 5 billion (5*10^9!)
bits or about 600 Mb. For digital processing of photographs it is necessary to convert
the analogue photographic material to a digital form. Optical scanners can scan
photographs at 12.5 &#181;m resolution with geometric distortions (or positional placement)
being in the order of magnitude of 5 &#181;m (Optronics International Inc.). Modern
laserscanners can scan photographs at 25 &#181;m (1000 dpi) but geometric distortions
may still be quite high (one undocumented source mentions 40 &#181;m) and unacceptable
for certain photogrammetric applications.
<p>
The most important photogrammetric techniques are based on the possibility of
stereoscopically viewing two overlapping photographs. This overlapping area can be
viewed in three dimensions. Thus the height of the terrain or buildings can be
measured. Errors in altitude, course and orientation of the plane during the exposure
of the film can be corrected using photogrammetric techniques. 
<p>
During the first <a name="spacelab"><strong>Spacelab</strong></a> mission, which took place between 28 November and 8
December 1983 a cartographic investigation was undertaken, known as the "<em>Metric
Camera</em> Experiment". The camera was a standard Zeiss RMK A30/23 aerial survey
camera suitably modified to interface with the Spacelab. The objective of the
experiment was to test the mapping capability of high resolution space photography
for:
<ul>
  <li>  compiling topographic and thematic maps, at scales of 1:50,000 - 1:100,000,
     particularly in unpopulated or less developed regions of the world.
  <li>  updating and revising topographic and thematic maps.
</ul>

The <a name="metric camera"><em>Metric Camera</em></a> was built by the German Aerospace Research Establishment
(DFVLR) and German industry. It had a focal length of 305 mm and produced colour
infra-red and black and white photography in 23 x 23 cm format at an altitude of
250km. 1:820,000 scale imagery was acquired with a ground coverage of 190km x
190km per frame and a resolution of approximately 20 m. To allow stereoscopic
evaluation of the photography the images were taken with at least 60% overlap in the
flight direction. Immediately after the Shuttle had landed in California, the films were
retrieved and sent to Europe for processing. The first images were available three
days later.
<p>
Approximately 1000 photographs were taken of which 550 were on colour infra-red
film and about 450 on black and white film. In total an area of 11 million km2 was
photographed, 70% of this area was either cloud free of only partly  cloud covered
and is suitable for evaluation.
<p>
<h3>The advantages of film systems include:</h3>
<ul>
  <li>  very high spatial resolution, integrity and large area coverage
  <li>  excellent stereoscopic capability for compilation of topographic elevations and
     contours
  <li>  lack of data transmission problems
  <li>  simple ground processing
  <li>  compatibility with usual photogrammetric mensuration and basic interpretation
     equipment, which is widespread around the world
  <li>  immediately useful to mapping and resource management organisations in
     developing countries
  <li>  film as information carrier is relatively low-cost and reliable (compare a 10x10"
     film with 600Mb of computer media)
</ul>
So it is not surprising to find that aerial photography still is the "workhorse" for the
acquisition of data for many Remote Sensing and GIS applications.

<h2>Aircraft Scanners</h2>

Multispectral line scanners, similar in principle to the Landsat MSS and TM
instruments, have been available for use in civil aircraft since the late 1960's. As with
satellite image acquisition it is the forward motion of the aircraft that provides along
track scanning whereas a rotating mirror or linear detector array provides sensing in
across track direction. There are several operational features that distinguish the data
provided by aircraft scanners from that produced by satellite-borne devices. These
are of significance to the image processing task. First, the data volume can be
substantially higher. This is a result of having (1) a large number of spectral bands
available and (2) a large number of pixels produced per mission, owing to the high
spatial resolution available. Recording of the data during a mission usually requires
use of a high density digital tape recorder or a robust disc unit carried on board the
aircraft.
<p>
A second feature of importance relates to the field of view (FOV) - that is  the scan
angle either side of nadir over which data is recorded. In the case of aircraft scanning
the FOV is typically 70&#176; to 90&#176;. Such a large angle is necessary to acquire an
acceptable swath of data from aircraft altitudes. By comparison the FOV for the
Landsats 1 to 3 is 11.56&#176; while that for the Landsats 4 and 5 is slightly larger
at about 15&#176;. The consequence of the larger FOV with aircraft scanning is
that significant distortions in image geometry can occur at the edges of the scan
(relative to a vertical, downward looking photograph). Often these have to be
corrected by digital processing.
<p>
Finally, the attitude stability of an aircraft as a Remote Sensing platform is much
poorer than the stability of a satellite in orbit, particularly the Landsat 4 generation for
which the pointing accuracy is 0.01&#176; (0.2 mrad) with a stability of 10^-6&#176; 
per second (20*10^-6 mrad/s). Because of atmospheric turbulence, variation in aircraft
attitude described by pitch, roll and yaw can lead to  excessive image distortion.
Sometimes the aircraft scanner is mounted on a three axis stabilized platform to
minimize these variations. It is more common however to have the scanner fixed with
respect to the aircraft body and utilize a variable sampling window on the datastream
to compensate for aircraft roll.
<p>
Use of airborne multispectral scanners offers a number of benefits. Often the user
can select the wavebands of interest in a particular application, and small bandwidths
can be used. Also, the mission can be flown to specific user requirements concerning
time of day, bearing angle and spatial resolution, the last being established by the
aircraft height above the ground. As against these however, data acquisition from
aircraft platforms is expensive by comparison with satellite recording since aircraft
missions are generally flown for a single user and do not benefit from the volume
market and synoptic view available to satellite data.

<h2>Airborne Remote Sensing in the Netherlands</h2>

The NLR operates a Fairchild Metro II and, in co-operation with the Delft University
of Technology, a Cessna Citation II for Remote Sensing flights with three advanced
Systems: CAESAR, PHARS/PHARUS and DUTSCAT. They have been employed in
several campaigns, including international campaigns of ESA for the preparation of
future satellite missions. The sensor systems are owned by the National Remote
Sensing Board (BCRS).
<p>
The airborne optical scanner <a name="caesar"><strong>CAESAR</strong></a> (CCD Airborne Experimental Scanner for
Applications in Remote Sensing) is a multichannel optical pushbroom scanner,
operating in the visible and near infrared wavelengths CAESAR can be configured in
several wavelength modes, each mode being adapted to one of several Remote
Sensing applications, including observation of inland waters, vegetation and land in
a high spatial resolution. CAESAR can also be flown in a bidirectional mode, enabling
vegetation analysis and the generation of stereo images. Custom-made software
provides absolute radiometric calibration of the CCD array and the correction of
distortions in raw data due to aircraft motion.
<p>
<a name="phars"><strong>PHARS</strong></a> is a C-band <em>VV</em>-polarized airborne synthetic aperture radar (SAR) developed
as a testbed in the Dutch <a name="pharus"><strong>PHARUS</strong></a> project, which aims at the development and
realization of a fully polarized airborne synthetic aperture C-band radar.
<p>
The Delft University of Technology Scatterometer (<a name="dutscat"><strong>DUTSCAT</strong></a>) is a six-band
microwave scatterometer system. NLR's involvement in the project concerns the on-
board data recording, the integration in NLR's research aircraft and the operation of
the equipment. The airborne character and the availability of six frequency bands in
the range from 1.2 to 17.25 GHz make DUTSCAT a unique scatterometer, useful in
the preparation of European satellite radar missions.
</DOC>
