<h1>The CD-ROM Family Tree</h1>

It took a long time before the CD-ROM was accepted as data storage for computers.
Nowadays a lot of software and operating systems appear on CD-ROM. At the same
time new applications for the CD are developed. This spawns a confusing number of
CD-formats more or less compatible with each other.

<h3>What is a CD-ROM?</h3>

CD-ROM means "Compact Disc Read Only Memory". A CD-ROM is physically
identical to a Digital Audio Compact Disc used in a CD player, but the bits recorded
on it are interpreted as computer data instead of music. You need to buy a "CD-ROM
Drive" and attach it to your computer in order to use CD-ROMs.
<p>
A CD-ROM has several advantages over other forms of data storage, and a few
disadvantages. A CD-ROM can hold about 650 megabytes of data, the equivalent of
thousands of floppy discs. CD-ROMs are not damaged by magnetic fields or the X-
rays in airport scanners. The data on a CD-ROM can be accessed much faster than
a tape, but CD-ROMs are 10 to 20 times slower than hard discs.
<p>
You cannot write to a CD-ROM. You buy a disc with the data already recorded on it.
There are thousands of titles available.

<h3>The audio CD</h3>

Everything started in 1980 with the announcement of the audio CD. The standard
technical specification of the audio CD or Compact Disc Digital Audio (CD-DA) was
put down in the <a name="red book"><em>"Red Book"</em></a> (so called because of the color of the cover). The audio
CD contains digitized music. Every second of music is represented by 1.4 million bits.
Apart from the music the CD also contains error correction and synchronization. Thus
the CD contains three times more bits than needed for the audio alone. The CD can
contain approximately 74 minutes of music so the CD can contain billions of bits of
information. This enormous capacity makes the CD suitable for storage of computer
data.

<a name="iso 9660"><h3>ISO 9660</h3></a>

Instead of reading the data sequentially for music the computer data should be
organized in a structured way in order to guarantee a fast random access of the data.
This file system structure of the CD-ROM was published in 1985 as the "High Sierra"
specification. The name "High Sierra" was derived from a hotel where the standard
was developed. Later this specification was officially adapted, with minor
modifications, by the International Standards Organization as the ISO 9660 standard
and put down in the <a name="yellow book"><em>"Yellow Book"</em></a>.
<p>
The ISO 9660 standard is a specification for PC's and has two levels. Level one looks
like the DOS filing system. File names consist of eight characters a dot and an
extension of three characters. The only characters allowed are the alphanumeric and
the underscore. Directories, contrary to DOS, can have no extensions.
All alphabetics are in UPPER case; some software maps this to lower case. Either
the file name or the extension may be empty, but not both ("F." and ".E" are both
legal file names).
<p>
There is a "File Version Number" which can range from 1-32767, and is separated
from the extension by a semi-colon. The file version number is ignored on many
systems.
Subdirectories are allowed to nest up to eight levels deep. Level two ISO-9660 allows
longer filenames, up to 32 characters. But many of the other restrictions still apply.
Level two discs are not usable on some systems, particularly MS-DOS.
<p>
The Macintosh has its own HFS format. It is unrelated to High Sierra and ISO-9660
formats. HFS stands for Hierarchical File System which is the file system of the
Macintosh. It has specific properties like resource and data forks and long file names.
<p>
Also Commodore had its own CD format, called CDTV, for the file system of the
Amiga. It is already extinct by now.
<p>
For Unix there is the <a name="rock ridge"><em>"Rock Ridge"</em></a> extension of the ISO 9660. The Rock Ridge
extensions use some undefined fields in the ISO-9660 standard to allow full unix-like
filenames, symbolic links, and deep directories. "Rock Ridge" is named after the town
in the movie "Blazing Saddles" for no particular reason.

<h2>Multimedia</h2>

<a name="cd-i"><h3>CD-I</h3></a>

Then there's the CD-I. CD-I means "Compact Disc Interactive". It is meant to provide
a standard platform for mass consumer interactive multimedia applications. (text,
images/video, audio)
<p>
The CD-I specifications are put down in the <a name="green book"><em>"Green Book"</em></a> which not only describes
the data structure of the disc but the equipment for playing it as well.
So it is more akin to CD-DA, in that it is a full specification for both the data/code and
stand-alone playback hardware: a CD-I player has a CPU, RAM, ROM, OS, and
audio/video/(MPEG) decoders built into it. Portable players add an LCD screen and
speakers/phonejacks.
<p>
There are three books by Philips IMS and published by Addison Wesley:
<pre>
"Introducing CD-I" ISBN 0-201-62748-5
"The CD-I Production Handbook" ISBN 0-201-62750-7
"The CD-I Design Handbook" ISBN 0-201-62749-3
</pre>

<a name="cd-xa"><h3>CD-XA</h3></a>

CD-ROM/XA is an extension to the Yellow Book Standard. A track on a CD-ROM/XA
disc can contain computer data, compressed audio data, and video/picture data.
Many CD-ROM drives do not support CD-ROM/XA. CD-ROM/XA extends CD-ROM
by adding some of the CD-I disc features, such as interleaving raw audio/video and
other data.

<a name="cd-r"><h3>CD-Recordable</h3>


The <a name="orange book"><em>"Orange Book"</em></a> specifies the CD-R recordable discs.
It is subdivided into two parts. Part I defines the Magneto Optical CD-MO disc.
A CD-MO consists of optional Pre-Mastered (READ-ONLY) area and a Recordable
(re-writable) user area.
<p>
Orange Book Part II also defines a second type of CD-WO (Write Once) disk called
a "Hybrid Disc". This disc consists of a Pre-recorded Area and a Recordable Area.
The Pre-recorded area is a READ ONLY area where the information is manufactured
into the disc. (This area is written per the Red, Yellow, and Green Book
specifications, and can be played on any CD-Player.) The Recordable areas are
where additional recordings can be made in one or more sessions. Only the first
session on the disc is readable by old CD-Players; additional software will be needed
to read the additional sessions. Such a CD-player is then said to be multi-session.

<a name="cd-bridge"><h3>CD-Bridge Disc</h3></a>

The CD-Bridge Disc defines a way to add additional information in a CD-ROM / XA
track in order to allow the track to be played on a CD-I player. the result is a disc that
can be played on both a CD-I player connected to a TV set and on a CD-ROM / XA
player connected to a computer.
<p>
An example of a CD-Bridge Disc is the new Photo-CD disc. The Photo-CD disc will
be playable in CD-I players, Kodak's Photo CD players and in computers using CD-
ROM/XA drives.

<a name="pcd"><h3>The Kodak Photo CD</h3></a>

The Photo CDs will be Mode 2 Form 1 sectors per the CD-ROM / XA specifications.
The disc will be written per the Orange Book Part II "Hybrid Disc" specifications. This
will allow photographs to be written to the disc in several different sessions.
Additionally, the disc will use the CD-Bridge disc format to allow the disc to be
readable by both CD-I and CD-ROM / XA players.
<p>
The photographs written to the disc in the first session will use the ISO 9660 format.
These photographs will be readable with the existing CD-ROM / XA players
connected to a computer running new software written for the Photo CD picture
structure. Additionally, the photographs will be displayable on CD-I Players and Photo
CD Players connected to a TV set.
<p>
Photographs written to disc after the first session will be displayable on CD-I Players
and Photo CD players. New software and/or firmware will be needed to read these
additional photographs with existing CD-ROM/XA players.

<h3>Electronic Book</h3>

Another special format is the Electronic Book by Sony. It's an 8 cm disc instead of
the usual 12 cm for CD-ROM. The disc is CD-XA compatible. Sony developed a
portable player, the Data Discman, for it. (Only recently Sony also released the
MiniDisc, which is a 7 cm CD-ROM and Recordable for audio).

<a name="blue book"><h3>Blue Book</h3></a>

The <em>"Blue Book"</em> is the standard for LaserDiscs.
("Blue Book" is apocryphal. Pioneer reportedly has a pre-mastering guide that may
or may not have a blue cover, but it is not a statement of the LD standard.)

<h2>Confused?</h2>

As may be clear from the previous section the CD-ROM comes in many different
formats. It's not always clear which CD can be played in which player. The confusion
starts with the CD-XA with offsprings like the "Hybrid Disc", the "Bridge Disc" and the
"Photo CD". These, in fact, are all hybrids between the CD-ROM and the CD-I. This
way the companies are gambling on two horses: multimedia PC and multimedia TV.
Companies try to make their players compatible with all the formats. And as long as
there is no standard to cover all possibilities the confusion will last **. Fact is that only
the audio CD-DA, with additional software, can be played in any player.
<p>
     [** An attempt is made by ECMA 168. ECMA is the European Computer Manufacturers Association. ECMA 168 allows
     greater information interchange using CD-ROM for publishing applications. In addition, it supports incremental
     recording and updating of information stored on a CD-WO disc. It is extensible to support future application and
     information processing system requirements. ECMA 168 is a volume and file format standard for write-once CD and
     CD-ROM. It was approved as a European standard by the ECMA General Assembly in June of 1992. It provides for
     full Orange Book functionality, including multisession recording, track-at-once recording, and packet recording. When
     used with an Orange Book writer, this will allow write-once CD to be used more like a general-purpose storage
     peripheral than is possible using ISO 9660. ECMA 168 also incorporates the functionality of Rock Ridge: the ability
     to use Unix-style filenames, Unix permissions, and deep directory hierarchies. Much thought was put into character
     set issues, and ECMA 168 accommodates multiple-byte character sets such as ISO 10646. Although ECMA 168 is
     not upward-compatible with ISO 9660, it is possible to write a "conformant disc" containing both sets of volume and
     file structures. If such a disc is Yellow Book compatible (a CD-ROM or a CD-WO written disc-at-once), it could be read
     on either an ISO 9660 system or an ECMA 168 system. There are many common elements between ECMA 168 and
     ECMA 167, which is a new standard intended primarily for WORM and erasable optical disks. Hopefully this will
     encourage developers to support both standards.]

<h2>Conclusion</h2>

The only possible conclusion is that a CD-XA player capable of reading multi-session
CD's is the best option for your computer. Most of the discs can be read. It can read
the common ISO 9660 (High Sierra) discs as well as the Kodak Photo CDs. The
latter, of course, is a very interesting option for Image Processing. However you'll
need to buy/acquire additional software to be able to unravel the Kodak Photo CD
image format. Currently an excellent Freeware program is available that can do the
job. (see <a href="hpcdtoppm.ps">here</a> for a manual of hpcdtoppm). It converts the PCD format to a format
called Portable BitMap (PBM). Public Domain programs exist to convert PBM to
almost every known image format.
<p>
A list of available CD players is given <a href="drives.html">here</a>.
<p>
The Kodak PhotoCD is explained into more detail <a href="kodak.html">here</a>.


<p>
<a href="cd-family.gif">Here's a figure of The CD-ROM Family Tree</a>
