<h3>       Detailed description of data available on CD-ROM</h3>

Parts from the following list of CD-ROM's available from other institutions has been
extracted from the NASA Master Directory (MD), which is operated at NSSDC. The
MD is a free, on-line multidisciplinary directory of data sets that are of potential
interest to the Earth and space science community. The MD contains descriptions of
data sets; not the data sets themselves. The intent is to be a first pointer to a wide
variety of data.
<p>
The MD is more that just a directory, however. In order to simplify the process of
finding more detailed information or accessing on-line data, the MD provides
automatic connections - called LINKs - to a number of data systems such as the
NASA Climate Data System (NCDS), Global Land Information System (GLIS),
Canadian Center for Remote Sensing (CCRS), Energetic Ion Composition
Spectrometer File (EICS), Space Environment Laboratory (SEL) and others; as of late
1991, 47 such systems were LINKED to the MD.
<p>
The Master Directory may be reached by several methods as outlined below. The MD
is option #1 of the NSSDC's Online Data and Information Service (NODIS) account.
<p>
Via Direct Dial:
Set modem to 8 bits, no parity, 1 stop bit. For 300, 1200 or 2400 baud, dial (301)
386-9000; for 9600 baud, dial (301) 286-4000.
<p>
<pre>
At:  System Prompt:      "ENTER NUMBER"..............
     You Enter:          MD <CR>
     System Prompt:      "CALL COMPLETE"............
     You Enter:          <CR>

>From this point on, the procedure is common to all other access methods. Skip the
descriptions for network access, and continue with the system prompt response
below.

>From NSI/DECnet (the old SPAN system):
At:  System Prompt Enter:     Set Host NSSDCA <CR>
     (or if you need the node numberSet Host 15548 <CR>)

>From Internet:
At:  System Prompt Enter:TELNET NSSDCA.GSFC.NASA.GOV <CR>
     (or if your nameserver does not recognize this:
                         TELNET 128.183.36.23 <CR>)

>From PINET:
Select option # 2 from the top menu (databases). The next menu option #1 will 
      connect you to the NSSDC Online Data and Information Service.
</pre>
<pre>
         NASA GODDARD SPACE FLIGHT CENTER (NASA/GSFC):

*    First ISLSCP Field Experiment (FIFE)

Summary:
     From the Pilot Land Data System (PLDS). One prototype disc is available with a subset of
     satellite, aircraft the data are written in ASCII, and some of the image data are in compressed
     form. Decompression software, image display and browse software for point data sets are
     provided on disc or associated IBM-PC compatible diskette. The complete data set is
     scheduled to be available on a series of CD-ROMs over the next 18 months. Data are free to
     the NASA affiliated research community.

Contact:  PLDS User Support Office at GSFC 
          (301) 286-9761
          MCMANUS@PLDSG3.GSFC.NASA.GOV

*    The International Satellite Cloud Climatology Project (ISCCP) Monthly Cloud Products on CD-
     ROM

*    The Greenhouse Effect Detection Experiment (GEDEX)

Summary:
     This CD-ROM is a compilation of over sixty data sets identified as being relevant in
     Greenhouse Effect research. Data sets include surface, upper air, and/or satellite-derived
     measurements of temperature, solar irradiance, clouds, greenhouse gases, fluxes, albedo,
     aerosols, ozone, and water vapor, along with Southern Oscillation Indices. Many of the data
     sets provide global coverage. Temporal coverage varies, with several surface station data sets
     covering more than 100 years while most of the satellite-derived data exist only within the most
     recent ten years. Spatial resolutions vary from zonal to 2.5 degree grids, while most are
     monthly in their temporal resolution. All data exist on the disks in a single format and can be
     easily accessed with PC software tools provided.

Contact:  Global Change Data Center
          DAAC User Support Office
          NASA/Goddard Space Flight Center
          Code 935
          Greenbelt, MD 20771
          (301)286-3209
          DAACUSO@NSSDCA.GSFC.NASA.GOV

                   NASA AMES RESEARCH CENTER

*    The Airborne Antarctic Ozone Experiment (AAOE), Including Halley Bay Ozonesonde Data on
     CD-ROM

Summary:
     This CD-ROM contains atmospheric composition and dynamics data collected over Antarctica
     for the purpose of studying the ozone hole and was based in Punta Arenas, Chile during
     August and September 1987. The data was primarily collected onboard the NASA ER-2 and
     DC-8 aircraft which flew into the ozone hole, along with ozonesonde data collected from April
     through November at 4 Antarctic stations--Halley Bay, McMurdo, Palmer Station, and the
     South Pole. The experiment tested the chemical and dynamical theories of the ozone hole
     using the aircraft data in theoretical computer models of the chemistry and dynamics of the
     stratosphere. The mission was organized and funded by NASA, NOAA, NSF, universities,
     Chemical Manufacturer's Association, and meteorological agencies overseas.

*    The Airborne Arctic Stratospheric Expedition (AASE) and the Meteorological Measurement
     System (MMS) Data CD-ROM's

Summary:
     These CD-ROM's contain atmospheric dynamics and composition data collected over the
     Arctic for the purpose of studying ozone production and loss, and the effect on cloud
     formation. The first CD-ROM contains the Second Edition of data pertaining to the Airborne
     Arctic Stratospheric Expedition (AASE) which was based in Stavanger, Norway during January
     and February, 1989. The second CD-ROM contains all of the 5 Hz data from the ER-2
     Meteorological Measurement System (MMS) taken during the 1989 AASE associated with
     flights during which mesoscale disturbances were observed. This disc was generated as an
     appendix to the primary AASE CD-ROM dataset. The data consists of measurements collected
     onboard the NASA ER-2 and DC-8 aircraft, ozonesonde soundings from three stations
     (Angmagssalik and Scoresbysund, Greenland, and Lerwick, U.K.), aerosol and temperature
     profiles from the SAM II spacecraft, global grid point values of Nimbus-7 TOMS ozone, and
     selected radiosonde soundings from stations in the region of the experiment. The mission was
     organized and funded by NASA, NOAA, NSF, universities, Chemical Manufacturers
     Association, and meteorological agencies overseas, utilizing similar instrumentation that was
     deployed during the Airborne Antarctic Ozone Experiment (AAOE) of 1987.

*    The Stratosphere-Troposphere Exchange Project (STEP) Data on CD-ROM

Summary:
     This CD-ROM contains atmospheric dynamics and composition data collected over the western
     U.S. and Australia for the purpose of studying the different aspects of stratosphere-
     troposphere exchange. STEP was conducted onboard the NASA ER-2 aircraft in January and
     February, 1987 based in Darwin, Australia. This mission was the last of 6 STEP missions
     which started with the Variability and Global Tropospheric Experiment (GTE) Coop assignment
     in April 1984, based in Moffett Field, California. Altogether, 4 science missions and 2
     intercalibration missions comprised STEP, with the science missions designed to investigate
     different aspects of stratosphere-troposphere exchange (in mass, trace gases, and aerosols),
     including cloud-free and cloud-dominated mechanisms in both the mid-latitudes and the
     tropics. STEP also observed the extreme dryness of the stratosphere. STEP was carried out
     under NASA and the National Oceanic Atmospheric Administration (NOAA).

Contact:  Mr. R. Steve Hipskind
          NASA Ames Research Center
          Mail Stop 245-5
          Moffett Field, CA 94035-1000
          (415) 604-5076
          HIPSKIND@HECTOR.ARC.NASA.GOV

                JET PROPULSION LABORATORY (JPL)

*    Tropical Ocean Global Atmosphere (TOGA) Meteorological and Oceanographic Data Sets for
     1985 and 1986, on CD-ROM

Summary:
     This CD-ROM contains atmospheric and oceanic dynamics data collected worldwide in
     association with the 10-year TOGA program for the purpose of studying the ocean/atmosphere
     relationship. The data sources for this CD-ROM are the United Kingdom Meteorological Office,
     (UKMO) Bracknell, Berkshire, U. K.; Marine Environmental Data Service (MEDS), Ottawa,
     Canada; TOGA Sea Level Center, University of Hawaii, Honolulu; NOAA Pacific Marine
     Environmental Laboratory (PMEL), Seattle, Washington; IFREMER and ORSTOM, Plouzane,
     FRANCE; European Center for Medium Range Weather Forecasting (ECMWF), Shinfield Park,
     Reading, Berkshire, UNITED KINGDOM; Climate Analysis Center (CAC), Camp Springs,
     Maryland; and Florida State University, Tallahassee, Florida. The parameters include air
     temperature, dew point temperature, air pressure, winds, wind stress (pseudostress), sensible
     heat, latent heat, sea level, salinity, sea surface temperature, and sub surface temperature for
     the Atlantic, Pacific, and Indian Oceans. These data are both selected observations and
     selected numerical model results for 1985 and 1986.

*    University of Miami/RSMAS Global and Regional Gridded NOAA Advanced Very High
     Resolution Radiometer Multichannel Sea Surface Temperatures

*    Goddard Space Flight Center Global and Regional Gridded NIMBUS-7 Coastal Zone Color
     Scanner Pigment Concentration Data (Monthly averages and climatologies)

*    West Coast Time Series Coastal Zone Color Scanner Pigment Concentration from the
     NIMBUS-7

Contact:  Dr. David Halpern
          NASA/Jet Propulsion Laboratory
          Mail Stop 300-323
          California Institute of Technology
          Pasadena, CA 91109
          (818) 354-5327
          OMNET>D.HALPERN

            NATIONAL SNOW & ICE DATA CENTER (NSIDC)

*    Coordinated Eastern Arctic Experiment (CEAREX) Data on CD-ROM

Summary:
     The National Snow and Ice Data Center and the Office of Naval Research produced a CD-
     ROM sampler containing data from the Coordinated Eastern Arctic Experiment 1 3 4tern Arctic
     Ice, Ocean, and Atmosphere Data.' Data sets include meteorology, hydrography, bio-optics,
     bathymetry, sea-ice acceleration, stress and deformation, ambient noise, and acoustics. 

*    Defense Meterological Satellite Program (DMSP) Special Sensor Microwave/Imager (SSM/I)
     Brightness Temperature - Polar Regions

Summary:
     This CD-ROM contains brightness temperatures for North and South Polar regions, used to
     compute sea ice concentrations. NSIDC uses (swath) antenna temperature data to produce
     gridded brightness temperatures (Tb) for the polar regions. The grid has a resolution of 12.5
     km for the 85 GHz channels, and 25 km for the 19, 22 and 37 GHz channels. Software is
     provided to extract the Tb from the CD-ROMs, to calculate ice concentration at 50 km
     resolution from Tb data, and to display the images on a PC or Macintosh. As of August 1990,
     7 disks have been produced, containing gridded brightness temperatures for north and south
     polar regions for 9 July 1987 through 31 March 1989.

*   NIMBUS-7 Scanning Multichannel Microwave Radiometer (SMMR) Brightness Temperature
     Grids - Northern Hemisphere, Volume 1-12

Summary:
     Contains passive microwave brightness temperatures (5 dual-polarized frequencies ranging
     from 6.6 to 37 GHz) and derived sea ice concentration for the Northern and Southern
     Hemispheres.
     This CD-ROM contains SMMR brightness temperatures for the North Polar region, as well as
     sensor and grid documentation. The SMMR mission objective was to obtain ocean circulation
     parameters on a "nearly all-weather" operational basis. The discs contain irradiance and ice
     concentration data for October 25, 1978 through August 20, 1987 (life of the SMMR sensor).

Contact:  Ms. Claire Hanson
          National Snow and Ice Data Center
          CIRES, Campus Box 449
          University of Colorado at Boulder
          Boulder, CO 80309
          (303) 492-1834 or 5171
          HANSON@KYROS.COLORADO.EDU

         NATIONAL GEOPHYSICAL DATA CENTER (NOAA/NGDC)

*    A Global Ecosystems Database developed by the Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) and
     the National Oceanic Atmospheric Administration (NOAA)

Summary:
     The U.S. Environmental Protection Agency and the National Oceanic Atmospheric
     Administration produced a geographic database for modeling terrestrial climate-biosphere
     interactions. The disc includes complementary multi-thematic data sets on compatible grids,
     registered to a common origin and projection (latitude/longitude). The database has been
     structured to be operable with several existing Geographic Information Systems (GIS), so that
     a complete analytical package could be provided to reviewers and other scientists for
     evaluation, experimentation, and further development. The data sets include monthly global
     vegetation index; monthly temperature, precipitation, and cloudiness; average monthly air
     temperature and precipitation; Olson world ecosystems; Holdridge life zone classifications;
     Matthews vegetation, land use, and seasonal albedo; Zobler soil type, soil texture, and surface
     slope; UNESCO/FAO soil units; FNOC elevation, terrain, and surface characteristics;
     integrated elevation and bathymetry; and the Micro World Data Bank II.

*    Geophysics of North America

Summary:
     This CD-ROM is a collection of land and marine geophysical data for North America. Much of
     the data was collected under the auspices of the Geological Society of America's Decade of
     North American Geology - including gravity, magnetics, earthquake seismology, thermal
     aspect, and stress data. Satellite imagery data, topography, and additional grids of magnetics
     and gravity are also included in this compilation. The disk also includes documentation, and
     access software which allows you to view the data, complete with geographical references and
     data contour overlays.

*   Land Gravity Data Base on CD-ROM

Summary:
     The NGDC has produced a prototype Gravity CD-ROM which contains a variety of land gravity
     data including the following: gravity station data prepared by the Defense Mapping Agency and
     NOAA's National Geodetic Survey; gravity networks and vertical control station descriptions;
     GEOS-3 and SEASAT altimetry data; bouger and free-air anomaly grids; and several regional
     surveys.

*    Deep Sea Drilling Project (DSDP): Marine Geological and Geophysical Data

Summary:
     This CD-ROM contains all the DSDP data, covering three decades and 96 cruises. Data
     include paleomagnetic data for sediments and hard rocks; X-ray mineralogy data;
     carbon/carbonate data, density-porosity and gamma ray attenuation porosity evaluator data;
     paleontology data; lithologic descriptions; age profile data; and sediment and intersitial water
     chemistry data.

*    Gulf of Mexico Imagery from GLORIA Side Scan Sonar

Summary:
     NGDC is making available long-range sidescan sonar data collected in the Gulf of Mexico by
     the United States Geological Survey with the GLORIA (Geological Long Range Inclined Asdic)
     system owned and operated by the British Institute of Oceanogaphic Science. The CD-ROM
     contains 3 sets of imagery data for the Gulf of Mexico Exclusive Economic Zone. The data
     base consists of 326 files comprising the complete set of 6-hour raster-image data; 16 files of
     2-degree area image mosaics derived from the raster-image data; and 2 composite files
     representing the complete eastern and western halves of the Gulf. Software and
     documentation accompany the disk.

*    US East Coast Imagery from GLORIA Side Scan Sonar

Summary:
     This CD-ROM contains sonar imagery of the seafloor for the United State's East Coast
     Exclusive Economic Zone collected by the USGS using the GLORIA system. 

*    Solar Variability Affecting Earth 

Summary:
     This disc contains solar flare reports, sunspot numbers and region histories, total solar
     irradiance, and solar bursts. Also included are all geomagnetic and related indices, cosmic ray
     observations, and NASA's "OMNI" solar wind and interplanetary magnetic field values along
     with model programs. IBM PC-compatible software accompanies the disc to access,
     decompress, and display the data.

