*    SLAR products available from the USGS include contact strip images, radar mosaics, and
     digital data which are distributed on computer tapes. Beginning with the FY90 project, digital
     data are also available on CD-ROM disks. In addition, ancillary products, such as indexes (on
     paper, film, or microfiche), mission flight logs, and custom photographic products may also be
     available.

*    Also Digital Elevation Model (DEM) data is provided by the US Geological Survey and are
     used in a variety of geologic and geographical applications, such as structural analysis,
     hydrology and geohazard risk assessment.

Summary:
     DEM data consists of gridded average elevations obtained from digtized contour maps or from
     scanned high-altitude stereo photography. Data are available at 1:24,000 scale, coresponding
     to 7.5 minute topographic maps. A shaded DEM map of the entire US based on the latter data
     was recently released by the USGS (Miscellaneous Investigations Series Map I-2206).

           DREXEL UNIVERSITY GALE/ERICA DATA CENTER

*    The Genesis of Atlantic Lows Experiment (GALE), on CDROM

Summary:
     This CD-ROM contains atmospheric and oceanic dynamics data collected along the eastern
     U.S. for the purpose of studying physical processes in East Coast winter storms which
     contribute to cyclogenesis. This CD-ROM contains a large subset of the non-imagery data
     collected during GALE produced by the Department of Atmospheric Sciences, University of
     Washington. The field phase of GALE was conducted from January 15 to March 15 1986.
     There were 13 special observing periods (SOP) during the field phase with 8 cases of
     cyclogenesis reported. Meteorological and oceanographic phenomena during SOP's included
     cyclogenesis, rainbands, cold fronts, coastal fronts, cold-air damming, jet streaks, tropopause
     folding, low level jets, cold-air outbreaks, lightning, and marine boundary layer interactions with
     the Gulf stream and mid-shelf oceanic fronts. This disc consists of aircraft flight level data,
     sounding data, surface data and satellite data. 

*    Experiment on Rapidly Intensifying Cyclones Over the Atlantic (ERICA) Field Study, on
     CDROM

Summary:
     This CD-ROM contains atmospheric and oceanic dynamics data collected off the East Coast
     of the U.S. for the purpose of studying the physical processes which lead to explosive
     wintertime storms developing over the Atlantic Ocean. This experiment was carried out under
     the Office of Naval Research (ONR) Heavy Weather at Sea Accelerated Research Initiative
     program. The ERICA field study was conducted from December 1 1988 to February 28 1989.
     The ONR core field study was supplemented by the substantial participation of many other
     agencies and universities from the U.S. and Canada. Data was obtained over the North
     Atlantic Ocean and Cape Hatteras to beyond Newfoundland, centered east of Cape Cod and
     south of Nova Scotia. Measurements in individual rapidly intensifying storms were made from
     aircraft, buoys, satellites, soundings, and radars.

