*    North American Observational Data for July - December 1987 on CD-ROM

Summary:
     This CD-ROM contains atmospheric dynamics surface and upper air data collected over North
     America and the adjacent coastal waters for July-December 1987. The disc is divided into two
     directories: DATA which contains all the data files, and INDEX which holds all the index files
     that allow direct access to the information. The DATA directory consists of: 1) aviation hourlies,
     2) land synoptic data, 3) marine data including ship reports, buoy data, and Coast Guard
     reports, 4) upper air reports from radiosondes, pibals, profilers, satellites, and rocketsondes,
     and 5) PIREP and RECON data. Several decades of hourly surface data from North Bend,
     Oregon, Seattle-Tacoma Airport, Washington, and Los Angeles International Airport, California,
     also reside on this disc. This data was supplied by the National Climatic Data Center (NCDC)
     in Asheville, NC.

*    World WeatherDisc, Climate Data for the Planet Earth since 1700

Summary:
     The CD-ROM contains atmospheric and ocean dynamics data that describe the climate and
     weather of the Earth today and during the past few hundred years. This disc holds climatic
     data for thousands of land stations around the world, with some records going back to the
     1700's. Also included are summaries of global ship observations since 1945, weather
     conditions at thousands of airports throughout the world, upper air conditions during the past
     several decades, frequency and movement of tropical cyclones, monthly surface station
     climatology for 3,625 stations, worldwide, including antarctic and the oceans, time series and
     sea level pressure. The disc contains e specially detailed information on the weather and
     climate of the U.S., including data from thousands of National Weather Service (NWS) and
     associated cooperative stations. These U.S. data sets provide information on temperature,
     precipitation, heating/cooling degree days, freeze occurence, drought and soil moisture, wind,
     sunshine, lightning, tornadoes, and thunderstorms. The data was supplied by the National
     Climatic Data Center (NCDC), Asheville, NC and the National Center for Atmospheric
     Research (NCAR), Boulder, CO.

