Talon    TA-100     - - 360 150 - - - - - - --- -
Talon    TA-200     - - 280 300 - - - - - - --- -
Tandy    CDR-1000   I N 800 175 N N - - - - 200 Y Nice, Cheap 
Texel    DM3021     I S 340 150 Y - - - - - --- -
Texel    DM3024     I S 265 300 Y M - - 2 - 439 Y
Texel    DM3028     I S 240 335 2 M - - 2 - --- - 
Texel    DM5021     E S 340 150 Y - - - - - --- - extrn DM3021 
Texel    DM5024     E S 265 300 Y M - - 2 - 549 - extrn DM3024 
Texel    DM5028     E S 240 335 2 M - - 2 - --- - extrn DM3028 
Toshiba  TXM-3201A  E S 350 150 Y N - - Y - 250 Y
Toshiba  TX-M3301   - - --- --- - - - - - - --- -
Toshiba  XM3300     - - --- --- - - - - - - --- -
Toshiba  XM3301     - - 325 150 Y - - - - - --- -
Toshiba  XM3301B    I S 325 150 Y M - Y Y - 499 Y Works great 
Toshiba  XM3301E1   E S 325 150 Y - - - - - --- -
Toshiba  3401       I S 200 330 2 M Y - 2 - 399 R Very fast 
Trantor  T128       B - --- --- Y S - N - - 100 Y
=====    ========   = = === === = = = = = = === === ========== 
  A          B      C D  E   F  G H I J K L  N   0      Q

  The NeXT CD-ROM is a Sony CDU-541.
  The Sony CDU-6211 is the same as the Sony CDU-7211.
</pre>
A <strong>caddy</strong> is a special container for the CD-ROM before they go into the CD player.
It makes changing of the disc slightly more elaborate but protects the CD-ROM.
Use of a CD-ROM caddy is highly recommended during transport and operation. In
fact every CD-ROM deserves its own caddy because it limits the amount of physical
contact with the disc.

A <strong>jukebox</strong> is a system with one drive containing a number of discs. The machine
automatically changes discs on request. Because of unacceptable response times a
jukebox is not useful in a multi-tasking environment.
<p>
There is a German firm called NSM that sells CD-jukeboxes for bars, etc. They have
their fast 100-disk changer also available for consumer purposes and a CD-ROM
version. In Holland it is sold by:
<pre>
     LaserMusic Nederland
     Leeuwenstein 44
     2627 AM Delft, the Netherlands.
</pre>
A jukebox that handles 240 discs is available from
<pre>
     Kubik Technologies Ltd.
     200-3900 Viking Way
     Richmond, BC V6V 1V7
     604-273-0400
</pre>
A <strong>multi-drive</strong> is a system with several drives in one box.
<p>
A CD has an "index" area which contains track details; this is what is read when you
first stick an audio CD into a player. Photo-CDs have a separate index area each
time they are written (because it is impossible to "update" the index area). A
<strong>multisession</strong> drive is one that knows to look for multiple index areas. The full details
are contained in the Philips/Sony/Kodak <a href="cd-family.html#orange book"><em>"Orange Book"</em></a> standard for writable CDs.
<p>
<i>Why are CD-ROM drives so slow?</i>
<p>
Compact discs were originally designed for music. When you are listening to "Willie
Nelson's Greatest Hits", you are accessing the data sequentially and at a very regular
speed. The only time you need to seek is when you decide to skip over a song, or
back up and listen to "Always on my Mind" one more time.
<p>
In order to fit as much music as possible onto the disc, the data is recorded at the
same linear density near the outer edge of the disc as it is near the center, so there
is more information in the outside tracks than in the inside tracks. In order to deliver
a steady rate of data, the linear velocity of the disc moving under the head is
constant, so the angular velocity of the disc changes when the head moves from the
center toward the outside tracks. This is no big deal when you are playing music, but
when you are trying to do random access to a CD-ROM, the need to accelerate and
decelerate the disc is the biggest obstacle to making it faster. Most magnetic discs
spin at a constant angular velocity, so the data density decreases toward the outside
of the disk, but seeks are faster.
<p>
A few other reasons that CD-ROMs are slow: Optical disc heads tend to be heavier
than magnetic disk heads, so they have more inertia, and take longer to stabilize onto
a new track. Many CD-ROMs contain too much data to make effective use of RAM
caches.
<p>
As time goes by, CD-ROM drives will get a little faster, but don't expect any miracles.

<a name="section 2"><h2>CD-ROM Recorders</h2></a>

Currently there are over twenty CD Writing Systems available. Table 5 lists some CD-
ROM Recorders.
<p>
<a name="recorders">Table 5</a>. <strong>List of CD-ROM Recorders</strong>
<pre>
     Drive             price  Mb  kb/s              comments 
====================== ====== === ===== ========================= 
JVC Personal ROM-Maker $12500 670  ?     complete system, including software
Kodak PCD Writer 200   $5000? 670  350   same as Philips CDD-521 
Philips CDD-521        $5500  600? 350   + $1900 for software 
Pinnacle Micro RCD 202 $3995  580 1024   ISO 9660 and HFS software for Macs
Ricoh RS 9200 CD       $4000? 650  150
Ricoh Profwriter 1     $4800? 540 1024
Sony CDW-900E          $10000            
Yamaha PDS 301         $6000? 680  350  
</pre>
Tim Sullivan, the most recent NEW MEDIA magazine compares over twenty CD
Writing systems. The best in the world is the quadruple speed Yamaha writer.
The worst are the JVC XRW1001 and others OEM'ed from it (Pinnacle RCD-202). All
the rest range between those two.
The big key is not just the mechanism but the mastering software, so keep that in
mind.
<p>
All CD-ROM recorders:
<ul>
<li>    can create all types of CDs (CD-audio, CD-ROM, CD-XA, PhotoCD and CD-I).
     They all can write previously recorded discs (multi session).
<li>    have a SCSI interface.
<li>    can be connected to all common system buses (ISA, EISA, MCA, Nubus)
</ul>
Exceptions are:
<ul>
<li>    Pinnacle Micro RCD 202: NO PhotoCD, NO CD-I
<li>    Ricoh RS 9200 CD: NO Nubus (Macintosh)
<li>    Yamaha PDS 301: NOT multisession, NO Nubus
</ul>
Kodak remarkets the Philips drive as their PCD Writer 200.
<p>
Pinnacle Micro announced at MacWorld Expo in San Francisco a new, recordable
CD-ROM drive with a list price of $3,995! This price includes ISO 9660 and HFS
software for Macs. PC interface kit and software is extra $200.
<p>
The JVC drive comes with software for making ISO-9660, Apple HFS, and hybrid
ISO-9660/HFS discs.
<p>
The blank discs for CD Recorders are not the same as a normal CD. The metal data
surface is gold instead of aluminum. The recorder uses a high powered laser to
modify a dye layer which is between the gold and the plastic. This dye is somewhat
photo sensitive so write once CDs should be stored in a dark place. They should be
stored in an area that does not rise above 40 Celsius (104 F). It takes about half an
hour to burn each disc.
<p>
The blanks come in two sizes. 63 minute, and 74 minute. The time refers to the
amount of digital audio that can be recorded. Since DA is read from the discs at a
constant rate of 150 kb/sec, it is easy to calculate the amount of data they will hold.
The 63' discs will hold about 580 meg, and the 74' discs will hold about 660 meg.
The discs cost about $20.

<h3>How much does it cost to make a CD-ROM?</h3>

You can get a master made for about $1300, and then about $1.50 per disc for
duplication. So to make 1000 discs, it will cost you about ($1300 + (1000 * 1.50)) =
$2800. Publishers often have `first-timer' specials with steep discounts off the list
price. For instance, DMI recently had a special of mastering, 50 discs, and two hours
of tech support for $750.
<p>
The cheapest CD-ROM manufacturer I've seen is Disc Manufacturing, Inc. Pre-
mastering $100 to $800, mastering $800 + $1.30/disk for 15-day turnaround.
Telephone Shogo Karitani at 205-859-4236
<p>
If you only want a few discs, you can have single ISO-9660 `one-offs' made for about
$200 for the first disc, and $100 for additional copies.

