MIME-version: 1.0
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<title>Geoinformatic Description</title>
<html>

<hr>

<img src="/itc.gif">

<hr>

<h3>Short description</h3>

<hr>

The social demand for up-to-date maps and other reliable geographical
information products is growing rapidly. This is caused by the pressure of
urbanization, resource exploitation and management, and the development of
agriculture. Other influencing factors include the protection of the
environment and the need for security and political stability. At the same
time planning and decision making processes have become more and more
complex, and increasingly decentralized. This requires more, faster, more
current and specific geographical information on the one hand, and more
complex types of geographical information (correlation capacity for
interchanging information categories, models to indicate consequences of
actions, etc.) on the other. These demands are forcing national mapping
agencies to extend their range of activities to the supply of
geoinformation products in addition to traditional map production.<p>
The range of surveying and mapping tools is expanding rapidly as a result
of technological developments in the fields of computing,
telecommunication, expert systems, data bases, navigation and point
positioning systems, satellite technology and image processing. These new
integrated tools and techniques are either replacing or complementing
established technologies in map production. Their capacity and potential
capacity for serving the user community is revolutionizing traditional
disciplines.  <p>
Surveying and mapping organizations need qualified personnel to manage the
transition from existing to new and integrated technologies to meet the
growing demand for geoinformation.  <p>
ITC's response to this challenge is to contribute to the training of such
personnel and thereby help strengthen the innovative, production and
management capabilities of the organizations concerned. Courses of a
disciplinary and an interdisciplinary nature are offered. The
interdisciplinary courses have been brought about by the integration of the
disciplines of aerial photography, photogrammetry, cartography, digital
remote sensing and computer science to create a new Department of
Geoinformatics.

<hr>

<a href="/homepage.html"><img src="/itcbutton.gif"></a>

<hr>

<i>Last updated: 
   01.02.1995</i>
<hr>

<A HREF="/new/mail.html"><i>schokker@itc.nl </I></A>

</body>
