<HEAD>
<TITLE>AIHA Strategic Plan</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY>

<H1><CENTER>American Industrial Hygiene Association<BR>
Strategic Plan<BR></H1>
<I>November 1996</I>
                                 
<HR>
The American Industrial Hygiene Association is an organization of professionals dedicated to the
anticipation, recognition, evaluation, and control of environmental factors arising in or from the
workplace that may result in injury, illness, impairment, or affect the well-being of workers and
members of the community.
<HR>
<H3>The AIHA Mission</H3>
The American Industrial Hygiene Association is devoted to promoting, protecting, and
enhancing the profession to affect positively the health and well-being of workers and members
of the community.
<HR>
<P>
<H1>The AIHA Vision</H1></CENTER>
<H2>Vision #1:  Professionalism</H2>
The discipline of industrial hygiene and the expertise of the industrial hygienist will be nationally
and internationally recognized and respected as an essential resource addressing health-related
issues affecting the workplace and the commmunity.
<P>
<H2>Vision #2:  Body of Knowledge</H2>
AIHA will work to enhance and provide access to a body of knowledge contributing to the health
and well-being of the worker and the community.
<P>
<H2>Vision #3: Worker and Community Health and Well-Being</H2>
AIHA will enhance worker and community health and well-being through facilitation of
legislative, regulatory and organizational policies enlightened by scientifically based information
and standards.
<P>
<H2>Vision #4:  Premier Organization</H2>
AIHA will be the premier organization of professionals dedicated to the prevention of workplace
illness or injury that may affect the health or well-being of workers or the community. 
<P> 
<H2>Vision #5:  Forum for Knowledge and Ideas</H2>
AIHA, guided by continuous communication among leaders, members, and clients will provide
an effective forum for the development of knowledge and exchange of ideas through quality
publications, conferences, educational materials, technical seminars, and other activities.
<HR>
<P>
<H1><CENTER>Implementation of the AIHA Vision</H1></CENTER>
<P>
<H2>Strategic Center 1: Programs and Services</H2>
<B>Goal: AIHA will identify, produce, and deliver timely, quality programs, products, and
services to enable its members to enhance their performance to better protect worker health.</B>
<P>
<I><B>Factors:</B><BR></I>
<I><UL><LI>Member profile and member needs are shifting into nontraditional areas.
<LI>The association must take a leadership role in continuously assessing future needs of the
profession and developing timely programs and products to meet those needs.
<LI>Competition for resources requires a more comprehensive marketing approach to program
and product development.
<LI>Program and product development must be considered for nonmember markets as a means
of attracting potential members and as a revenue source for supporting other member
needs.</LI></UL></I>
<P>
<B>Outcomes 1A, Continuing Education:</B><BR>
1A1. Re-engineer the CEC for better focus and workload distribution by May 1997.<BR>
1A2. Begin a 3-year plan to build "road course" and in-house training programs.<BR>
1A3. Increase road course offerings 60% by 1999.<BR>
1A4. By December 1997 begin a 3-year plan to provide crossover training products and
services.<BR>
1A5. By January 1998, begin a 3-year plan for "distance learning" initiatives and  laboratory 
personnel training needs.<BR>
1A6. By December 1998, increase the emphasis on CEUs in addition to IH certification 
maintenance points to serve 10% more allied professionals.<BR>
 1A7. PDCs will identify varying skill levels of courses and offer safety/environmental,
legal/regulatory topic tracks by May 1997.<BR>
1A8. By 1998 expand higher level skill listings by 10% and re-engineer the PDC review systems
to support the new initiatives.
<P>
<B>Outcomes 1B, AIHCE:</B><BR>
1B1. Encourage the submission of extended abstracts from technical sessions and handouts from
roundtable presenters, aiming for the goal of 100% participation by the year 2000.<BR>
1B2. In 1997 expand the length and format of Case Study presentations with 60 - 90 minute
presentations planned for 1998.<BR>
1B3. For 1997 AIHCE offer the options of electronic abstract submission and housing
registration, with a 80% electronic submission rate by the year 2000.<BR>
1B4. In 1998 attract crossover attendance and reposition AIHCE in the E,H & S fields.<BR>
1B5. Increase the number of exhibit booths sold to 1,000 by the year 2000.
<P>
<B>Outcomes 1C, Laboratory Accreditation:</B><BR>
1C1. Conduct a customer satisfaction survey by December 1997.<BR>
1C2. Streamline the accreditation process while maintaining the quality of programs by
December 1997.<BR>
1C3. Expand the use of electronic communications tools to improve information and services to
laboratories and to increase cost efficiency by December 1997.<BR>
1C4. Evaluate potential for laboratory consultation as a separate entity from site visits by
December 1997.<BR>
1C5. By December 1997, evaluate expansion into a  broader definition of Quality Programs
<BR>
1C6. Ensure that existing programs maintain a revenue-positive status and that new programs
achieve revenue positive status within three years of initiation.<BR>
1C7. Maintain relative revenue share by increasing programs or expanding scope of existing
programs. <BR>
1C8. Develop and begin to implement an enhanced marketing program for laboratory services,
aimed towards both internal and external customers by December 1997.<BR>
1C9. Evaluate subsidiary status by Dec. 1997. <BR>
1C10. Evaluate reciprocity status between AIHA programs and other accreditation programs
meeting similar criteria by December 1997.<BR>
1C11. Explore international recognition and/or reciprocity with countries designated by the
AIHA Board of Directors by December 1997.<BR>
1C12. Continue AIHA's  participation in the National Laboratory Accreditation movement.
<P>
<B>Outcomes 1D, Scientific Affairs</B><BR>
1D1. Develop comprehensive plan for Guidelines for Good Practice (GGP) by May 1997. <BR>
1D2. By August 1997 approve a system that enables committees to take a proactive approach in 
developing programs and products to meet growing and changing needs of the profession.<BR>
1D3. Publish a compendium of existing Guidelines for Good Practice by January 1998.<BR>
1D4. Publish GGP on a selected priority topic using established policies and procedures by May
1998.
<P>
<B>Outcomes 1E, Publications/Communications:</B><BR>
1E1. Working with scientific affairs and the technical committees, publish 7 10 new AIHA Press
books each year.<BR>
1E2.  By December 31, 1997,  increase revenues 50% over 1995 by expanding the number of
AIHA publications and distribution markets. <BR>
1E3. Develop <I>The Synergist</I> Online by March 1997.<BR>
1E4. Implement development of electronic <I>AIHAJ</I>, as outlined in business plan with full
text online planned for January 1998.
<P>
<B>Outcomes 1F, Information Systems:</B><BR>
1F1. Install an information system  by December 1997 that will provide comprehensive
marketing data and also enable staff  to carry out their assigned functions more efficiently and
cost effectively.<BR>
1F2. An international information delivery system will be available to AIHA's international
members by December 1998.

<P>
<B>Outcomes 1G, Employment Services:</B><BR>
1G1. Revamp the monthly employment service program to increase the employment
opportunities available to members by 10%. <BR>
1G2. Develop brochures to assist job seekers by December 31, 1997.<BR>
1G3. Increase employer participation at the AIHCE job fair 10% in 1997. <BR>
1G4. Committee will present a roundtable at AIHCE 1997.<BR>
1G5. Develop a program to assist IH members in obtaining employee leasing contracts through
AIHA Employment Services companies and clients by December 1998.
<P>
<B>Outcome 1H, Research and Development</B><BR>
1H1. Prepare a report recommending means for AIHA to influence and support research and
development by August 1997.
<HR>
<P>
<H2>Strategic Center 2:  Public Policy</H2>
<B>Goal:  AIHA will become the recognized leader in the development of public policy
impacting the profession.</B>
<P>
<I><B>Factors:</B></I><BR>
<I><UL><LI>Discussions on reinvention of OSHA and NIOSH present both pros and cons. A
reduction in government involvement may result in less need for employers to hire occupational
health and safety professionals.  However, reduction might  increase the need for third-party
occupational health and safety professionals due to a lack of government resources.
<LI>The Republicans have maintained control of Congress at least through 1998, which will
place more pressure on "reinvention" of OSHA .</UL></LI></I>
<P>
<B>Outcomes 2A:</B>
2A1. Establish AIHA as the essential source for federal regulatory and legislative policy makers
by providing testimony on at least three legislative measures by December 1997. <BR>
2A2. Assist at least five local sections and at least ten SGAOs with specific government affairs
issues by December 1997. <BR>
2A3. Position AIHA as the central source for establishing IH policy on 50 percent of the top ten
key issues affecting occupational health and safety by December 1997.<BR>
2A4. Establish a membership grassroots program that enlists the membership as a whole
 or on a partial basis in government affairs activities or issues at least three or more times by
December 1997.<BR>
2A5. Increase recognition of the IH profession in one federal legislative and two additional
federal regulatory measures by December 1998.
<HR>
<P>
<H2>Strategic Center 3: Volunteer  Resources</H2>
<B>Goal: AIHA will develop programs and services to enhance the ability of its membership
and leadership to achieve the strategic plan goals.</B>
<P>
<I><B>Factors:</B></I><BR>
<I><UL><LI>Because many  volunteers have less free time,  it is important to increase the
number of participating  volunteers and to use their time more effectively.
<LI>As industrial hygienists and environmental and safety specialists cross over in their roles,
the membership universe changes. 
<LI>Economic and political changes could have a negative impact on the size of AIHA's core
member universe thus reducing our ability to direct OSH issues proactively.
<LI>The national population continues to grow in diversity.
<LI>Globalization will continue to impact on AIHA membership.</UL></LI></I>
<P>
<B>Outcomes 3A, Membership:</B><BR>
3A1. Achieve a 6% increase in national members in 1997 and a 5% per year increase in national
members beginning in 1998.<BR>
3A2. Retain 90% of membership from 1996 through 1998.<BR>
3A3. Increase the numbers of female and minority members by 5% each a year.<BR>
3A4. By May 1998, 45% of the AIHCE exhibitors will be organizational members.
<P>
<B>Outcomes 3B, Leadership:</B><BR>
3B1. By 1997, the Nominating Committee will have a process to identify potential leaders for the
AIHA Board of Directors from a wider variety of the membership.<BR>
3B2. By 1998 80% of the technical committee leaders will attend the Leadership Workshop.
<P>
<B>Outcomes 3C. Local Sections:</B><BR>
3C1. National will determine the percentage of national members in each local section by July
1997.<BR>
3C2. National will develop a tiered services and program structure for local sections by January
1998.<BR>
3C3. By 1998, 80% of local sections will be represented at the leadership workshop.<BR>
3C4. Increase mutual memberships by 10%  per year over the 1996 base, starting in 1998. 
<P>
<B>Outcomes 3D, Special Interest Groups:</B><BR>
3D1.  By May 1997 establish three Special Interest Groups: one for consultants and two for
selected technical areas.
<HR>
<P>
<H2>Strategic Center 4: Fiscal Resources</H2>
<B>Goal: AIHA will manage its finances to ensure that it has the resources to meet and integrate
its strategic planning goals, business plans, and budget.</B>
<P>
<I><B>Factors:</I></B><BR>
<I><UL><LI>Changing societal, economic, and professional forces require setting boundaries
and
priorities in expenditure of resources.
<LI>When programs, committees, and other functions serve fewer people or deliver limited
results, the association must assess effectiveness and consider reallocating resources.   
<LI>The association must balance its resource allocation between meeting current needs and
meeting future needs.
<LI>The association derives a large portion of its annual revenues from the activities and output
of its technical committees.</UL></LI></I>
<P>
<B>Outcomes 4A, Financial Goals:</B><BR>
4A1. Member equity will be equivalent to 35% of annual revenue by 2000; 50% by 2010.<BR>
4A2. From 1996 on, increases in expenses will not exceed increases in revenues in the
budget.<BR>
4A3. With 1995 as the base, identify 3 new non-dues revenue sources by 1998. <BR>
4A4. With 1995 as the base, increase total revenue by 10% by 1998.
<P>
<B>Outcome 4B, Product Development:</B><BR>
4B1. Increase productivity and revenues by providing additional financial resources for up to five
selected technical committees for a minimum of three years beginning in 1997. 
<HR>
<P>
<H2>Strategic Center 5: Image and Identity</H2>
<B>Goal: AIHA will be recognized by its external and internal customers as the essential source
for occupational health information, services, and resources, and will continue to promote the
expertise and value of the profession to appropriate publics.</B>
<P>
<I><B>Factors:</I></B><BR>
<I><UL><LI>The meaning of industrial hygiene and the industrial hygienist's role are not fully
understood by external publics, including employers, regulators, legislators, and members of the
community. 
<LI>With current economic and political climates, industrial hygienists need to impart the image
of a versatile, highly qualified and necessary professional.
<LI>Community involvement is an important tool for building recognition of a
profession.</UL></LI></I>
<P>
<B>Outcomes 5A:</B><BR>
5A1. IH status and recognition will grow at least 10% a year with allied professions and trade
press.<BR>
5A2. Recognition of the profession with external audiences will increase 15% per year.<BR>
5A3. Develop a methodology for measuring the value-added benefit of the profession by August
1997.<BR>
5A4. Present an Occupational and Environmental Hygiene Summit by December 1997.<BR>
5A5. Implement a new public relations campaign by October 1997.<BR>
5A6. AIHA will be recognized by 75% of the local section leadership as the essential source for
occupational safety and health information and guidance by 1998.
<HR>
<P>
<H2>Strategic Center 6: International Activities</H2>
<B>Goal: AIHA will maintain an international presence that ensures that AIHA and its members
remain viable players in the international arena. As globalization continues, the association will
take a prominent international role, thus protecting its members and the profession.</B>
<P>
<I><B>Factors:</I></B><BR>
<I><UL><LI>Globalization of the workplace and the economy affects our members in a
multitude
of ways, including  their employment status.
<LI>Industrial hygienists could and should take a leadership role in affecting international
standards for occupational health and safety.</UL></LI></I>
<P>
<B>Outcomes 6A:</B><BR>
6A1. Beginning in 1996, track and monitor key international issues and activities that impact the
industrial hygiene profession.<BR>
6A2. AIHA will be represented yearly at a minimum of 3 international activities affecting the
profession.<BR>
6A3. By May of 1997 AIHA will establish a policy on international chapters.<BR>
6A4. AIHA will develop a strategy to recruit international members by August 1997.
<P>
<HR>
<P>
<H2>Strategic Center 7: Structure and Governance</H2>
<B>Goal: AIHA will be responsive and adaptable to the needs of the membership, prospective
members, and the profession.</B>
<P>
<I><B>Factors:</I></B><BR>
<I><UL><LI>The diversity and the changing roles of the profession require a wider range of
input
and knowledge, some of it in non-traditional arenas.  
<LI>Lack of flexibility in an association's organizational structure creates stumbling blocks in
addressing new areas of knowledge and can prevent active involvement of new members.
<LI>Volunteer leadership is most effective devoting most of its time to long range planning and
policy, instead of operational details.
<LI>Unification of the IH organizations would increase the stature of the
profession.</UL></LI></I>
<P>
<B>Outcomes 7A, Committees and Task Forces:</B><BR>
7A1. Establish methods to measure effectiveness of governance structures by March 1997.<BR>
7A2. Implement practices to improve performances of all leadership groups by March
1997.<BR>
7A3. Ensure that 75% of the committees and task forces will meet established outcome goals and 
perform to expectations by December 1997 with 80% doing so by 2000. <BR>
7A4. Implement committee and task force activity cluster arrangements by March 1997.<BR>
7A5.Explore methods for planning, budgeting, performance and evaluation activities that will
more closely align committee and budget year cycles with AIHA budget cycles by December
1997.
<P>
<B>Outcomes 7B, Local Sections:</B><BR>
7B1. As part of the tier system, National will provide three additional services to local sections
by January 1998.<BR>
7B2. Ensure that 75% of the Local Sections will follow a governance cycle consistent with
AIHA's governance year by 2000.<BR>
<P>
<B>Outcomes 7C, Redefinition:</B><BR>
7C1. By August 1997, redefine the scope and practice of industrial hygiene under contemporary
conditions.<BR>
7C2. By December 1997, present a plan to the Board that outlines the expansion of programs and
services to support a redefinition of industrial hygiene.<BR>
<P>
<B>Outcomes 7D, Professional Unity:</B><BR>
7D1. Explore the possibility of a joint journal by December 1996.<BR>
7D2. Explore the potential combinations of membership directories, dues billings, and other
publications.<BR>
7D3. Seek collaboration (e.g., with ACGIH) in at least three scientific areas by June 1997.<BR>
7D4. Unite the profession by 1998. 
<P>
<B>Outcome 7E, Board of Directors:</B><BR>
7E. Complete a Board policy manual by May 1997.
<P>

<HR>

