<HEAD>
<TITLE>Unification Task Force Report</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H1><CENTER>REPORT AND RECOMMENDATIONS FROM THE UNIFICATION TASK FORCE FOR AAIH, ABIH, ACGIH AND AIHA</CENTER></H1>
<HR>

                 
<H2>Executive Summary of the Report:</H2>

The Unification Task Force (UTF) was guided throughout its deliberations by its charge,
established during a meeting of the Boards of the American Academy of Industrial Hygiene
(AAIH), the American Board of Industrial Hygiene (ABIH), the American Conference of
Government Industrial Hygienists (ACGIH), and the American Industrial Hygiene Association
(AIHA) in Kansas City, May, 1995:

<BLOCKQUOTE>
     "The Unification Task Force (UTF) is charged by the  Boards of Directors of the AAIH,
     ABIH, ACGIH, and AIHA with researching and analyzing all available background
     information and data in order to make recommendations to the four governing bodies
     regarding the efficacy of uniting the four organizations for the benefit of the profession
     and the respective members of the four organizations.<P>

     These recommendations may take the form of one or more proposals ranging from
     maintaining the status quo to any of a number of kinds of unification. The UTF will
     prioritize its recommendations/proposals and provide appropriate rationale and
     explanation for each of them.<P>

     The primary thrust of the UTF will be to determine what forms, if any, of unification are
     advisable and to describe them in sufficient detail topermit the respective organizations to
     fully evaluate the options and make appropriate decisions on each."<P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

After establishing criteria for judging the efficacy of any recommendation, the UTF developed
and critically examined four models: the status quo, a cooperative model, a federated model and
a consolidated model.
<P>
At its final meeting, on April 2, 1996, the UTF unanimously recommended consolidation of the
four participating organizations.
<P>
The full report of their recommendations and the rationale for those recommendations follow. 
<P>

<H2>The Process:</H2>

When charged by the four Boards in May, 1995, the structure of the UTF was also decided. It
would consist of three representatives from each organization, for a total of 12.  The chief staff
officer of each organization was expected to attend each meeting, unless officially excused by
that organization. The chief staff officer served as a representative with voice but no vote.
<P>
Before the first meeting, the UTF selected Dadie Perlov, CAE, founder and principal of the
Consensus Management Group, as facilitator.
<P>
At the first meeting, all participants agreed to a process and ground rules, attached as <A HREF="utfa.html">Addendum
A</A>. They also agreed that the work of the UTF would focus on the best interests of the profession
of industrial hygiene, the individual industrial hygienist, workers and the community.
<P>
The definition of consensus, which is how all UTF decisions were reached, was defined as a
decision which most of the UTF could live with, with "most"  considered to be more than a
simple majority. In fact, the UTF revisited any recommendation which failed to receive a two-thirds positive vote.
<P>
The UTF met formally seven times, for two days each time, between October 1, 1995 and April
2, 1996, and completed many interim assignments and tasks between meetings.
<P>
For each meeting, an Executive Summary of proceedings was prepared, approved by the UTF
and shared with each Board.
<P>
For an interim meeting of all four Boards on March 17, 1996, these summaries were condensed
to focus on key UTF decisions to date. This material, plus presentations by UTF members on
mission, programs, image, public policy, and membership, as well as the structure and
governance of three different models, provided an opportunity for individual members of each
Board to give feedback to the UTF on over 100 items.  Analysis of responses, electronically
recorded through the use of individual key pads, helped guide the thinking of UTF members
when they were called upon to make final recommendations at their last meeting in April.
<P>
It should also be noted that despite regular communications to the members of each organization
via newsletters, very little formal feedback from members was received by any UTF member,
and virtually no mail was sent to the PO Box set up to confidentially receive opinions from
members of any of the participating organizations. On the plus side, there were several important
letters to editors of the ACGIH and AIHA newsletters.  Each received attention by the UTF.
<P>
The UTF also recognized that the best time to intervene in any system or process is before that
system or process is broken.  Therefore, the UTF continually asked itself, "Is what we are now
considering going to be better than the status quo for the individual industrial hygienist, for those
he/she serves, and/or for the profession?" 
<P>
To do this required a solid understanding of the status quo, and its use as a benchmark. As an
early task, the UTF created an extensive description of the status quo, referred to as a "<A HREF="utfgrid.html">Baseline Data Grid</A>". 
<P>
From the beginning of the UTF's work there was uniform recognition that none of the existing
organizations are now "broken".  All are in good health, working towards fulfillment of their
respective missions.  However, after making some reasonable assumptions about the future of the
profession and the environment in which it will function, it became clear that the profession
could be strengthened through certain fundamental changes.
<P>
<H2>Models Considered:</H2>

After agreement as to process, the establishment of baseline data, and a projection of the future,
both for the profession and the environment in which it would function, the UTF then:

<UL>
<LI>Developed a mission for an industrial hygiene professional association.
<LI>Determined criteria (<A HREF="utfb.html">Addendum B</A>) against which decisions were to be evaluated.
<LI>Decided which existing programs must be retained; which currently underway by more
than one association could be consolidated to eliminate undesirable redundancies; which
current programs and services might be eliminated; and which new programs and services
should be considered.
<LI>Examined the strongest possible ways to establish public policy.
<LI>Recognized the importance of attention to image and identity, for the profession and itsprofessional association(s).
<LI>Considered membership criteria, categories and entitlements, along with the roles,
rights and responsibilities of local sections.
</UL>

The UTF considered four basic models, recognizing that there were many permutations possible
within each model, and that some characteristics of a particular model could be transported in
whole or part to another model.
<P>
The four models considered were:
<P>
      The status quo<BR>
      A cooperative model<BR>
      A federated model<BR>
      A consolidated model<BR>

<P>
 For each, the UTF considered:
<P>
<UL>
<LI>      The possible structure(s) needed to advance the predetermined mission and
accommodate the programs, services, public relations and membership access already
established as important for the individual industrial hygienist and the profession. 
<LI>      The kind(s) of governance desired and required.
<LI>      Headquarters and staffing implications.
<LI>      How to finance each model, which resulted in the need to draft pro forma budgets for
each.
</UL>


The working mission created by the UTF was intended to drive all deliberations.  It was designed
to reflect why the association would be in business, and for whom it would be in business. The
mission statement used is:
<BLOCKQUOTE>
    "The 4IH Association will advance the occupational and environmental hygiene
    profession in protecting the health of workers and the surrounding communities."
</BLOCKQUOTE>
After receiving feedback from members of all four Boards at the March 17, 1995 meeting, and
reviewing all UTF decisions to date, it became clear that it was time to reject both the
cooperative and federated models. The polling did not produce a compelling case for either
model, nor could the UTF make a compelling case for either model.

<H3>The Cooperative Model:</H3>

This model represented a slightly more formal extension of the status quo, leaving all
organizations intact, but providing for an unincorporated Coordinating Council.  This Council
would encourage cooperative efforts in appropriate areas, e.g. the production of a combined
membership directory and the pursuit of ethics awareness.
<P>
Although this model would be the least disruptive to existing organizations, that was not a
sufficiently compelling reason to support it. The model was rejected because it created a new
layer of bureaucracy, required more meetings and an additional commitment of time for certain
Board members and staff of each of the participating organizations, with little apparent return for
either the individual industrial hygienist, the profession, or any of the participating organizations. 
Since the Coordinating Council would have no implicit authority, any decisions and requests for
funding or other resources would be open to second guessing by any Board.
<P>
Because accountability had a high value in all UTF deliberations, this model did not make the
grade. It essentially maintained the status quo, with no evidence that substantial improvements
could be expected.

<H3>The Federated Model:</H3>

This model is more complex, and received careful consideration. In essence, it enabled each
existing organization to maintain its identity and corporate status, adding a separately
incorporated "Managing Board" and professional staff for the Federation. Administrative
responsibilities of each participating organization would be transferred to the Federation. The
three existing incorporated entities, ABIH, ACGIH and AIHA would be joined by a fourth, the
Federation itself. In this model, the Academy would remain under the aegis of the ABIH.
<P>
While this structure had some decided advantages, including some cost savings, opportunities for
leadership development, and the consolidation of certain activities, e.g. the production of a single
membership directory, the coordination of all appropriate task forces and committees, and the
physical arrangements for travel, conferences and meetings, it also presented some major
problems. 
<P>
The federated model failed to eliminate non-productive competition for members, a current
reality for ACGIH and AIHA, and one which has the potential to escalate over the next few
years.  It failed to enable a sharpened focus on the image of the profession, and it would
significantly increase bureaucracy. Although much of each current organization would remain
intact, moving into a federation would still cause major disruption for a small return in monetary
savings or other member benefits.  The large number of fiscal contracts needed to enable a single
source of dues collection, i.e. at the Federation level, and the billing, collection and disbursement
of all moneys, was seen as problematic. 
<P>
Because each organization would retain autonomy, nothing would prevent any one of them from
utilizing the Federation less and less as time progressed.  Finally, the difficulty of having four
Executive Directors, with overlapping jurisdictions, was seen as a major management
impediment.  Despite the seductiveness of this option, and after a thorough analysis of the model,
it was not endorsed in the informal polling of the four Boards, or later by the UTF as it met to
make its final recommendations. Both the Boards and the UTF found that federation offered little
if any improvement in efficiency, effectiveness or net worth.  Equally important, the UTF felt
that membership would not perceive the federation as an organization that would add value to the
profession or to the individual member.
<P>
Overall, Federation was seen as no improvement over the status quo.  If anything, it ranked lower
than the status quo in all informal polling of the four Boards.  This reinforced a previous and
similar ranking by the UTF. 

<H3>The Status Quo:</H3>

Attention was then focused on the status quo and the consolidated model.  After careful review,
the UTF also rejected the status quo, and concentrated on creating the best possible consolidated
organization.
<P>
The status quo was rejected largely because there was increasing recognition that the future for
the industrial hygiene profession required concerted, unified attention to meeting the needs of
industrial hygienists and those they serve.  The competition for members, for advertising dollars
and for recognition as a legitimate source for information about the profession all pointed to the
need for a paradigm shift. Questions were also raised about the appropriateness of supporting
multiple headquarters and the attendant costs at a time when government, academe and industry
are all tightening operations. 
<P>
Analysis of the status quo indicated that substantial sums of money were being expended for
organizational maintenance and operations, money which could be shifted into programs and
services for the members or could be used to substantially reduce dues. The large number of
individuals who held multiple memberships was also a consideration.
<P>
A major driver for change was the growing recognition that the profession itself was in flux, with
people coming into it from more diverse sources and with more diverse roles for the industrial
hygienist of the future. As a relatively small profession, the need to consolidate resources,
political power, programs and services became apparent. 
<P>
Perhaps the most defining moment in the search for the UTF's final recommendation came
during a discussion of why the status quo might not be better for the ABIH.  Very quickly, the
UTF determined that being part of a consolidated organization, even as a programmatically
independent subsidiary, offered ABIH:
    
<UL>
<LI>      Easier access to the profession for promotion of the CIH
<LI>      Enhanced resources for ABIH to change IH certification as field practices change
<LI>      A higher level of coordination with the practicing profession 
<LI>      Cost effectiveness for the certification effort
<LI>      Reduced fees for certification maintenance
<LI>      Better communications within the industrial hygiene community
<LI>      Expanded use of technology, available through the consolidated organization
<LI>      Increased opportunity for ABIH to become an umbrella for new certification areas, the
cost of which could initially be underwritten by a financially secure consolidated organization. 
<LI>      Reduced dues for members who are CIHs and full participants in more than one
organization                            
<LI>      Advantages of "one stop shopping", i.e. one place to look for information, programs,
services, materials, positions, etc.
<LI>      Reduce perceptions of "elitism" which sometimes accrues to ABIH
</UL>

    
The awareness that all of those advantages of a consolidated organization could be achieved
while maintaining the integrity of the certification process, in accord with externally established
standards for a credentialing body, was encouraging.
<P>
The need to preserve the credibility of the certification process, extended as well to the
development of TLVs, BEIs and the lab accreditation program, all now accounted for in the
status quo. Once it was clear that all these activities could be securely protected and even
strengthened, along with absolute protection of their independence and credibility, the decision to
move forward towards consolidation was reinforced.  
<P>
<H3>Consolidation:</H3>

During its seventh and final meeting, the UTF unanimously voted to recommend
consolidation.  This was an outcome that could not have been predicted at the outset.  It
resulted from a deliberative process, progressively built,  based on careful attention to previously
determined criteria.  The criteria (<A HREF="utfb.html">Addendum B</A>) were objectively determined and established
before any models were proposed. 
<P>
Consolidation offers industrial hygienists the opportunity to focus their resources, efforts and
attention on programs, services and issues which will accomplish the proposed mission for the
consolidated organization, "..to advance the occupational and environmental hygiene profession
in protecting the health of workers and the surrounding communities".
<P>
This working mission drove the design of the consolidated organization which follows.  It
guided: 

<UL>
<LI>    Selection of programs and services
<LI>    Ongoing attention to "helping the industrial hygienist do his/her job"
<LI>    Considerable cost-saving and consequent reduction in the overall amount of dues dollars
paid by the profession
<LI>    Development of an approach to public policy initiatives which assures a strong voice for
the profession, enabling the organization to identify and address technical, professional and
political issues quickly and accurately, with due regard to diverse opinion and interests within the
profession
<LI>    Design of equitable membership categories and entitlements
<LI>    Utilization of "best practice" standards for the structure, governance and management of
the consolidated organization
</UL>

<A HREF="utfunite.gif">A graphic description of a consolidated organization for the industrial hygiene profession. </A>

<H2>Governance of the Consolidated Organization:</H2>

For the work of the UTF, governance was defined as a process within an organization which
provides the decision-making mechanisms needed to direct and accomplish the business of the
organization.  It is a political process created to determine policy and assure accountability to
members and the profession.
<P>
Recognizing that the effectiveness and efficiency of any organization depends largely on the
quality of governance and management, the consolidated organization was structured to enable
the best of both.
<P>
<H3>A)   The Board of Directors Role:</H3>

     The eleven person Board will be a policy Board.  That is, it will deal with setting the
     direction and tone for the organization.  It will focus on five key policy areas:
<P>
<OL>
<LI>Establishing ends policies, generally called goals or priorities. This planning
     function generally includes ongoing assessment of the needs, wants and expectation of
     members and prospective members, related always to the realities of the external
     environment. 
<P>
     It keeps the organization mission driven and market sensitive.  It assures that the
     organization's plan, based on member interests and needs, guides all programs and
     services, from conferences and publications to public relations and local section support.
     It maintains organizational focus, even as administrations and staff change. 
<P>
<LI>Setting public policy, which requires two key elements: The advance
     identification of compelling issues and positions on behalf of which the organization
     could initiate action, and a system for appropriate response to issues raised externally. 
     The UTF used the matrix on the next page as a sample of a future way to determine the
     importance of any issue and the association's ability to impact it, to determine those
     issues which would receive priority attention.
<P>
     In the consolidated organization, where multiple workplace situations, professional
     interests, philosophies and experiences will influence public policy positions, it will be
     critical for the organization to seek consensus on major issues. The use of technology
     makes such a task eminently feasible. Readily available tools can widen the circle of
     input into the decision-making process.
<P>
     For issues which are highly important and have high impact potential, i.e. issues which
     would reside in quadrant A, it will be essential for the consolidated organization to have
     the ability to respond in a strong voice and in a timely manner. For those issues which
     reside in the B, C and D quadrants of the matrix, it will be necessary for the consolidated  organization to serve as a single source of credible information, but not necessarily as a single voice.  This will encourage and enable soliciting, expressing and explaining differing positions.
 <P>    
     Guidelines for how to establish and promulgate positions, to assure an open process and
     maximum impact, will be essential.
<P>
     A consolidated organization would be best able to affect public policy on the
     international and local levels as well. 
<P>
<LI>Resource allocation:  A fundamental policy role for the Board will be to allocate
     all resources to support all goals and public policies alreadyestablished.  These resources
     include money, human resources, technology and time. 
<P>
<LI>Executive Director relationship:  This Board role provides guidance to and
     evaluation of the Executive Director.  It assures that the chief staff officer has the
     competence to participate in public policy and planning deliberations, and to bring issues
     to the Board, while focusing on his/her primary role, i.e. carrying out all policy directives
     from the Board.
<P>
The above four policy roles all revolve around "what" the organization will do. There is one
important "how" which the association's Board would deal with:
<P>
<LI>How the Board governs: These actions identify the processes which the Board
     will follow in its deliberations.  It can cover everything from where the Board will meet
     to the rules of procedure, if not provided for in bylaws.
</OL>
<H3>B.   Board of Directors Composition:</H3>

     The Board will be composed of 11 members: 5 officers and 6 directors. 
<OL>
<LI>Officers:<BR>
          The Officers will be a President, President-Elect, Vice-President, Immediate Past
President and a Secretary/Treasurer. The President, President-Elect, the Vice-President and the Immediate Past President will each serve a one year term.
<P>
          The Secretary/Treasurer will serve one 2 year term.  To assure continuity, a
          Secretary/Treasurer-Elect will be elected during the second year of that term, and
          will serve as an ex-officio member of the Board for one year, and then assume a
          full 2 year term. 
<P>
     Officers will be eligible for re-election after 3 years off the Board.  For Officers who
     move into other officer positions, terms may be consecutive.
<P>
<LI>Executive Committee:<BR>

          For interim decisions between meetings of the Board, when those decisions
          cannot wait for a regular Board meeting, or cannot be accomplished through
          conference call, the Executive Committee may act on behalf of the Board.
<P>
          The officers would serve as the Executive Committee.
<P>
          It is generally the responsibility of the Executive Committee to provide for the
          annual evaluation of the Executive Director's performance. 
<P>
<LI>Directors:<BR>
          There will be 6 Directors, each elected for a single 3 year term.  Terms will be
          staggered so that each year 2 Directors are elected and seated.
<P>
          Directors will be eligible for re-election to the Board after 3 years off the Board.
<P>
          For Directors who move into officer positions, terms may be consecutive.
</OL>
<H3>C.   Committees and Task Forces:</H3>

     To assist the Board in advancing the organization's mission, and to focus on current and
     ongoing priorities, there will be both committees and task forces.
<OL>
<LI>Two Standing Committees are recommended:
<P>
<UL>
<LI>Finance: To develop and monitor the organization's budgets, investments
          and funds.  This committee is generally chaired by the organization's
          Secretary/Treasurer, working closely with the Chief Financial Officer, a staff
          position, and the Executive Director. 
<P>
          Although this committee will in all likelihood begin its work by reviewing a draft
          budget created by staff, it helps the Board meet its fiduciary responsibilities and is
          generally  provided for in Bylaws. 
<P>
<LI>Nominating: This critical committee assures the identification,
          development and placement of leaders. After hearing from members of all four
          current Boards that this committee should be closely aligned with the grassroots
          membership, the UTF recommends a five member committee, all elected by the
          membership.
<P>
          Each year, the Nominating Committee will nominate a dual slate of candidates for
          service on the next Nominating Committee.  There will also be provision for
          petition candidates.
<P>
          The Immediate Past President of the organization will serve as Chair of the
          Nominating Committee, with voice but no vote. 
<P>
          For the first year of operation of the consolidated organization, the Immediate
          Past-Presidents of both the ACGIH and the AIHA would Co-Chair this
          Committee. 
<P>
          For the nomination of officers and board members, as well as members of the
          Nominating Committee, there will be guidelines which require that all slates
          reflect the diversity of the organization's membership. 
</UL>
<P>
<LI>Other Committees: The Board may wish to establish other Committees,
     particularly for matters which may require long-term attention, or which should be carried
     over from any of the existing membership organizations, e.g. certain technical
     committees, the committee which will oversee activities related to academic accreditation
     (currently the responsibility of AAIH/ABET), etc.
<P>
<LI>Task Forces: Most of the implementation activities which emerge from Board
     policy determinations will be carried out by time and task- specific Task Forces,
     supported by staff.  No Task Force will assume an "in perpetuity" role.  Task Forces will
     be accountable to the Board, reporting on progress to date vis a vis pre-determined
     benchmarks, useful in carrying out specific assignments in a timely manner. 
</OL>

<H2>Special Interest Groups (SIGs):</H2>

SIGs will be established to provide for the wide variety of special professional interests,
originating from the workplace (academe, government, chemical industry, etc.), specialty, or
interests which transcend a specific workplace, e.g. labor. 
<P>
It is envisioned that participation in one SIG might be included in base member dues. Fees for
participation in more than one SIG will need to be determined. Guidelines will spell out criteria
for starting a SIG, entitlements as a SIG member, staff support for SIGs, and the method of
setting participation fees.
<P>
SIGs can play an important role in developing public policy positions, as a first level of a
strategic planning process, and as grassroots entities which can keep member needs, wants and
expectations before the Board. 
<P>
SIGs meet a critical member need for networking opportunities, and along with committees and
task forces, also serve as training grounds for future leaders. 


<H2>Local Sections:</H2>

Attention to local sections will be important. Headquarters should be able to provide service to
all local sections which meet whatever minimum standards are mutually established for sections.
Local sections also provide leadership identification and training opportunities, have the entree
needed to carry national public policy initiatives to local officials, can attract and keep members,
and offer local programs of professional interest to members and prospective members. 
<P>
Unresolved by the UTF is the larger question of whether there should be co-extensive
membership required between national and its sections, i.e. should every member have to be, or
automatically become, a member of both the national and a local section.  This issue should be
on an early agenda for resolution.
<P>
State Government Affairs Organizations (SGAOs), currently active within AIHA in ten states,
are an entity that calls for expansion and investment.  With so many issues, such as licensure,
regulation and workplace legislation appearing on more and more state legislative agendas, the
SGAOs should become an increasingly active part of a consolidated organization's operations. 

<H2>Subsidiary Organizations:</H2>

Soon after the UTF began its task, it became apparent to all that certain activities and programs
required a high level of independence in order to assure the integrity and credibility of those
activities and programs.  The key programs which fell into this category were the development of
exposure guidelines, e.g. TLVs and BEIs; laboratory accreditation programs; and professional
certification. 
<P>
The UTF was determined to find a way to insulate these programs and activities from any undue
interference in the content of the programs and activities. Each of the new models considered
provided some degree of protection. The consolidated model ultimately offered the most,
including improvement over the status quo, by placing each of these activities into a subsidiary
corporation. The Board of each subsidiary will be totally independent of the parent organization
vis a vis who serves on the subsidiary Board, and as well as for the creation of programs and
products.
<P>
This was accomplished through the establishment of subsidiary corporations for creating
exposure guidelines, for certification, and for lab accreditation, as described in the following chart.
<P>
Subsidiaries are designed for programs and services which require independence to assure the integrity and credibility of those programs, services and products. Each subsidiary will have a staff director, who will report to the subsidiary board on all content matters, and dedicated staff to support programs. Administration and services will be purchased via contract from the parent organization. Royalty and other fiscal arrangements will be mutually determined between parent organization and subsidiary.
<TABLE BORDER=2>
<CAPTION ALIGN=top>Subsidiary Corporations</CAPTION>
<TR><TH></TH><TH>Exposure Guidelines</TH><TH>ABIH</TH><TH>Lab Accreditation</TH></TR>
<TR><TH>Board Size:</TH><TD>~12 (up to 3 public members)</TD><TD>~15</TD><TD>~10</TD></TR>
<TR><TH>Requirements:</TH><TD>Only from Government or Academe</TD><TD>CIH</TD><TD>2/3 of Board must meet requirements of lab director definition of the accred program</TD></TR>
<TR><TH>Recommended by:</TH><TD>Member org and sub</TD><TD>Member org and sub</TD><TD>Member org and sub</TD></TR>
<TR><TH>Nominated and elected by:</TH><TD>Exposure Guideline Board</TD><TD>ABIH</TD><TD>Lab Accreditation Board</TD></TR>
<TR><TH>Miscellaneous</TH><TD>Has committees on which non-members may serve</TD><TD>Meets standards for a certifying board</TD><TD>Has committees</TD></TR>
</TABLE>
<P>
<H4>Notes:</H4>
<UL>
<LI>Each subsidiary will have articles of incorporation and bylaws, with full control of amendment process.
<LI>Subsidiary retains all rights to control content and quality of programs, services, and products.
<LI>Parent receives license to produce, sell and distribute programs, services and products, thereby receiving gross revenues.
<LI>Parent handles all finances of subsidiaries, including arrangements for audit, payment of bills, handling receivables, maintaining headquarters, etc. Subsidiaries develop own budget.
<LI>All subsidiaries and parent are housed in a sigle facility, in separate wings.
<LI>Subsidiaries are prohibited from ever becoming membership organizations.
<LI>Prohibitions are in place to dissuade subsidiaries from considering total separation from parent.
<LI>Maximum degree of independence provided for subsidiaries, with minimum control by parent.
<LI>The IH Foundation will maintain existing scholarship programs and examine possible new and expanded directions and utilization of the Foundation.
</UL>
<H2>Membership in the Consolidated Organization:</H2>
Considerable attention was directed to providing equitable and defensible membership categories and benefits. The categories suggested below preserve the Diplomate status for CIH's; provide full Fellow status for all appropriately credentialled members of the profession; and enable non-degreed technicians and degreed nurses the ability to participate. Dues schedules were calculated to cover as much of the core costs of membership for most categories, with recognition that both students and retirees would continue to receive some membersgip support from the organization.

<TABLE BORDER=2>
<TR><TH>MEMBER TYPE</TH><TH>WORKING DESCRIPTION</TH><TH>HOLD OFFICE</TH><TH>VOTE</TH><TH>DUES</TH><TH>JOURNAL</TH></TR>
<TR><TH>Honrary</TH><TD>Non-member making significant contribution to occupational and environmental health</TD><TD>No</TD><TD>No</TD><TD>Zero</TD><TD>No</TD></TR>
<TR><TH>Diplomate</TH><TD>Full member plus CIH</TD><TD>Yes</TD><TD>Yes</TD><TD>X</TD><TD>Yes</TD></TR>
<TR><TH>Fellow</TH><TD>Full member plus CSP, CHP, PE, MD*, COHN, practicing at least 50% of his/her time</TD><TD>Yes</TD><TD>Yes</TD><TD>X</TD><TD>Yes</TD></TR>
<TR><TH>Full</TH><TD>Baccalaureate degree in science or engineering, practicing O&EH at least 50% of time</TD><TD>Yes</TD><TD>Yes</TD><TD>X</TD><TD>Yes</TD></TR>
<TR><TH>Affiliate</TH><TD>Non-degreed technicians and non-degreed nurses who practice within the profession; vendors</TD><TD>No</TD><TD>No</TD><TD>X</TD><TD>Yes</TD></TR>
<TR><TH>Student</TH><TD>Graduate or undergraduate, full or part-time</TD><TD>No</TD><TD>Yes</TD><TD>.2X</TD><TD>No</TD></TR>
<TR><TH>Retired</TH><TD>Retired from O&EH practice</TD><TD>No</TD><TD>Yes</TD><TD>.5X</TD><TD>Yes</TD></TR>
<TR><TH>Organizational</TH><TD>Any organization desiring to support the occupational and environmental health profession</TD><TD>No</TD><TD>No</TD><TD>5X</TD><TD>No</TD></TR>
</TABLE>

<H4>Notes:</H4>
<OL>
<LI>The necessary independence of TLV's, BEIs, lab accreditation and certification will be protected through the organization's structure and governance, i.e. the subsidiary corporations, rather than through membership categories.
<P>
<LI>Detailed criteria and entitlements for each category will need to be more clearly defined during the transition period, and in the consolidated organization's bylaws.
<P>
<LI>Special professional interests are provided for through the creation of the Special Interest Groups (SIG's).
</OL>
<H4>Legend:</H4>
"X" equals an amount of dues, to be finally determined during transition. A working number, used to create the pro forma budget, indicates that X=$110. Therefore, .2X=$22, .5X=$55 and 5X=$550.
<P>
*This MD category is for MD's who are Board certified in occupational medicine.

<H2>Key Activities of the Consolidated Organization:</H2>

UTF interest in the possibilities offered by unification was strengthened when programs and
services, as well as image and identity, were considered.  Again, this was always considered in
relation to the best interest of the profession of industrial hygiene and of the industrial hygienist,
with the overarching objective of workplace safety and health. 

<H3>A. Programs and Services:</H3>
<OL>
<LI>Programs to continue and strengthen, already reflected in the design and structure
     of the consolidated organization:
<P>
<UL>
<LI>A professional certification and re-certification program that promotes
          high technical standards, integrity and excellence in occupational health/industrial
          hygiene professionals so designated.
<LI>An academic accreditation program which approves and endorses those
          undergraduate and graduate collegiate curricula meeting desired technical,
          educational and professional standards.
<LI>A strong accreditation program for occupational health, safety and related
          environmental laboratories.
<LI>A premier, independent body and process to develop, evaluate and promulgate recognized national/international occupational exposure values and workplace guidelines.
<LI>A government affairs branch with strong legislative and regulatory
          lobbying capabilities.
<LI>A sought after resource for state and federal agencies.     
<LI>A Foundation to support and provide educational scholarships.
<LI>Strong local sections.
</UL>
<P>
<LI> Overlapping Programs And Services To Consolidate:
<UL>
<LI>       A code of ethics which is actively promoted.
<LI>       Technical symposia, conferences and workshops.
<LI>       Development of workplace guidelines.
<LI>       Distribution and sale of quality, technical publications.
<LI>       Publication of a single membership newsletter.
<LI>       Publication of a single membership directory.
<LI>      An international outreach program which identifies with the occupational
          and environmental health and hygiene profession world-wide.
<LI>       Publication of a single technical, peer-reviewed journal. (Note: Such a
          consolidation can avoid the competition for advertising apparent in the status quo,
          which in turn might make it possible to increase advertising rates; increase the
          number of scholarly submissions which in turn should improve quality of peer
          reviewed papers; maintain one editorial Board, reflective of membership).
<LI>               Management of allied professional organizations.
<LI>               Awards.
<LI>               Active liaison with other organizations and agencies.
</UL>
<P>
<LI>Programs and Services To Expand or Develop:
	<UL>
	<LI>               Provision of management and business training for the workplace to
          facilitate ability of industrial hygienists to assume management positions.
	<LI>               Provision of training for association leadership.
	<LI>               Address issues of ethics violations.
	<LI>               Active role in ANSI, ISO and other standards developing organizations.
	<LI>               Quicker ability to identify and respond to shifting needs of membership.
	<LI>               Aggressive outreach program to non-member industrial hygienists and
          related professionals.
	<LI>               Worker training materials for member use.
	<LI>               Expanded employment services so that the organization becomes pre-eminent in job search, placement and consulting services support.
	<LI>               Special interest forums on issues that are occupational or community
          health related.
	<LI>               Information systems and tools for the industrial hygiene practitioner.
	<LI>               Encourage and facilitate research in the academic, business and R&D
          arenas.
	</UL>
</OL>

<H3>B.  Image and Identity:</H3>

    The consolidated organization will focus on both an internal image and identity (for
members and prospective members) and an external image and identity (for all other significant
publics). 
    <P>
    Identity was defined as, "What an organization is and does", while image was defined as,
"The perception of what the organization/profession is and does". 
<P>
    To assure the desired internal image and identity for members and prospects, the
organization will:
<OL>
<LI>"Help me do my job better."  This was seen as the fundamental issue.
<LI>Promote its members' professional status to employers, clients, government, academia
and other external interest groups.
<LI>Be the best source for continuing education and technical publications, on a consistent
basis.
<LI> Insure a meaningful certification program.
<LI> Have a governance structure that is sensitive to a diverse membership. 
<LI> Meet member needs.
<LI>Be responsive to technical and political issues, and be able to address those issues
through fast, flexible and accurate mechanisms.
<LI>Provide networking opportunities for special interest groups.
<LI>Maintain high professional standards for membership.    
</OL>

Some of the key external publics identified were the media, through which the public-at-large is
primarily reached; the government (legislators and regulators); allied professional societies;
employers and clients; and international publics.
<P>
    To assure the desired image and identity for external publics, the consolidated organization
will be recognized as:

<OL>
<LI>The authoritative experts in occupational and environmental hygiene.
<LI>The accrediting body working with ABET for professional and academic programs.
<LI>The certifying body for the occupational and environmental hygiene profession.
<LI>A proponent of the value of certification.
<LI>Active participants in public policy activities relevant to occupational and
environmental health, so as to "serve and protect" the profession.
<LI>Protectors of the occupational and environmental health of the workforce and the public.
<LI>A primary source of occupational standards and guidelines, worldwide.
</OL>

<H2>Pro Forma Budget:</H2>

In order to complete its rationale for recommending consolidation, the UTF gave serious time
and attention to the fiscal implications of this action. 
The approach taken in the pro forma budget, which is attached as <A HREF="utfc.html">Addendum C</A>,
was to be as conservative as possible in regard to income and as liberal as
possible in regard to expenses.  This approach guarantees that no promises are being made
through the pro forma budget which cannot be actualized in the early years of operation.
<P>
It is important to note that the one time costs for consolidation will be about 
$ 1,125,000.  This figure was seen as an investment in the future.
<P>
The anticipated bottom line does not include any income from any of the new or expanded
programs and services being considered or from any change in advertising revenue, and projects
a possible first year loss of some members.  Once again, this is using a generous allowance for
expenses and very cautious projections for revenues.
<P>
-- Total revenues, status quo:                    $ 17,300,000<BR>
-- Total revenues, consolidated organization:       16,595,950<BR>
<BR>
-- Total expenses, status quo:                    $ 16,591,100<BR>
-- Total expenses, consolidated organization:       15,483,800<BR>
<BR>
-- Excess (loss), status quo:                   $      708,900<BR>
-- Excess (loss), consolidated organization:         1,112,150<BR>
<P>
The net revenues available for reinvestment into programs and services in the consolidated
organization are impressive.  This is even more impressive when the individual dollar
investments of industrial hygienists are factored in.  For people who are CIH and currently
members of both ACGIH and AIHA, the total dues per year are now $240.  In the consolidated
organization, the annual dues are projected at $110, plus an additional fee of $50 per year (down
from the current $70 per year) to maintain the CIH. For those who are only regular members of
ACGIH, dues will increase from $70 to $110.  For those who are only regular members of AIHA,
dues will increase from $100 to $110. 
<P>
The average operating margin (excess of revenue over expense divided by total revenue) of
existing organizations is 4.1 %.  The pro forma budget is based on an operating margin of 6.7%,
as suggested by Board members at the feedback meeting on March 17.  Should there be a
decision to return to a narrower operating margin, it would in turn reduce both the fund balance
and individual dues. 
<P>
The suggested dues level of $110 is calculated to produce this 6.7% operating margin, along with
other sources of income and reductions in expenditures.  For purposes of perspective and
comparability, if the existing organizations were now operating at a margin of 6.7%, the regular
dues for these organizations would now be: $106 for ACGIH; $129 for AIHA; and $79 for
ABIH/AIHA.
<P>
It is the fund balance (sometimes called reserves) which enables new projects, programs and
services. In order to assure adequate funds for ongoing and emerging programs and services, the
UTF developed a budget with a 6.7% operating margin.

<H2>Legal Considerations:</H2>

Although the responsibility for assuring legal compliance for everything from membership votes
on consolidation to determining the most advantageous tax status for the consolidated
organization and its subsidiaries will rest with legal counsel working with the Board of each
existing organization, the UTF pursued legal advice necessary to complete its charge.
<P>
During a December 22, 1995 conference call with Jerald Jacobs, Senior Partner with Jenner &
Block in Washington, DC and an expert in association law, five UTF members and the facilitator
asked if consolidation was possible, what form(s) it might take, and how the integrity and
independence of the TLVs, BEIs, lab accreditation program and professional certification could
be protected, while minimizing liability exposure. 
<P>
Mr. Jacobs advised that there were many ways to accomplish these objectives.  Most approaches
suggest the establishment of one or more subsidiary corporations. He urged the UTF to keep in
mind that the closer the relationship between the parent and the subsidiary, the greater the
liability exposure of the parent, with a direct link between the level of control and the level of
liability.
<P>
To protect the integrity of the TLV and BEI process in a subsidiary corporation, safeguards can
be built in which will assure who is eligible to draft guidelines or serve on a board. Similarly,
revenue streams can be protected by setting up irrevocable methods, e.g. through a royalty or
licensing arrangement, to assure an income stream to the parent organization. 
<P>
In answer to specific questions, Mr. Jacobs assured the UTF that the TLV and BEI programs
could be set up so that only government employees or academics could sit on the governing body
and as voting members of committees of the Exposure Guidelines subsidiary.  The question of
who owns the TLVs and BEIs could be addressed by allowing the subsidiary to own the
copyright for the guidelines, while providing that only the parent is licensed to sell them. None
of these subsidiaries would have members or charge dues.
<P>
It is also possible to build in protections which will make future separation untenable, by putting
in place penalties or an absolute prohibition.  These "fire walls" can protect the integrity of the
programs from unwarranted incursions by the parent organization yet keep these activities within
the consolidated organization, as subsidiary corporations, and provide as much liability
insulation as possible.
<P>
The opinion of Mr. Jacobs was later reinforced in an April 1, 1996 telephone call with Mr.
Steven Fellman, a partner in Galland Kharasch Morse & Garfinkle, a firm with a large and
respected association practice.  Mr. Fellman advised the UTF that a subsidiary could determine
its own need for dedicated staff, even if some services would be contracted from the parent
organization.  A subsidiary can be structured so that the Board can choose its own chief staff
officer, who will then report to that Board and also maintain a relationship with the Executive
Director of the parent organization. 
<P>
To further clarify the issues raised for the UTF, Richard Bar, also a partner with Galland
Kharasch Morse & Garfinkle, responded to two specific questions:
<P>
<EM>1)  Can the structure of the consolidated organization be such that a subsidiary may retain
absolute control over its bylaws and articles of incorporation and any amendments to them? </EM>
<P>
    Yes, the organization can be structured so that the subsidiary will retain absolute control
over its bylaws and articles of incorporation....The composition of the initial Board should be
specified in the articles of incorporation and the bylaws.  Thereafter, the bylaws should state that
each successive Board is to be elected by the current Board, and list the criteria that each Board
member must meet in order to qualify as a member of a particular Board, e.g. assuring that only
industrial hygienists from academe or government could be elected to the Board of the Exposure
Guideline subsidiary. 
<P>
<EM>2)  Can these corporate structures be set up so that a subsidiary will be prohibited from
becoming a membership organization?</EM>
<P>
    The subsidiary organizations can be structured so that they will not become membership
organizations. This could be clearly set forth in the organizational documents. 
<P>
Mr. Bar also reinforced the UTF decision that the subsidiary corporations and the parent Board
not have overlapping Boards.
<P>
Bylaws, and the right to amend them are therefore protected from incursion by the parent in all
matters except finances, licensing or other contractual arrangements. These issues can be
addressed through separate agreements between the parent and subsidiary corporations which
would clearly define where the revenue generated by each organization is to be deposited and
how allocated. Separate budgets and ledgers would be maintained for the parent and each
subsidiary. There is every reason to believe that fiscal agreements can be reached which will be
acceptable to all entities and assure sufficient funding for each.
<P>
Subsidiaries were created by the UTF to assure adequate protection of key processes and to
provide an adequate comfort level for all as well. Ultimately, the UTF was pleased to have
created a structure that provides a higher level of programmatic independence for each subsidiary
corporation than the degree of independence enjoyed today.  
<P>
At the time of this writing, it appears as if the most favorable tax exempt status (under the
Internal Revenue Code) for each corporation would be:
<P>
--      For the parent organization: 501 (c) (6)<BR>
--      For ABIH: 501 (c) (6), as it is currently<BR>
--      For the laboratory accreditation corporation: 501 (c) (6)<BR>
--      For the exposure guidelines corporation: 501 (c) (3)<BR>
--      For the Foundation: 501 (c) (3), as it is currently<BR>
<P>

On another matter, the UTF wanted to eliminate any misconceptions concerning the involvement
of military personnel in individual membership organizations.  The ruling provided for the
Department of Defense, Standards of Conduct Office (in Document Number 550.TR Section 3-301), clearly states that any individual may become a member and may participate in the
management of non-federal entities as individuals in a personal capacity, provided that he/she
acts exclusively outside the scope of his/her official position. Further examination of this issue
revealed that although government employees are prohibited from personally lobbying, an
individual may belong to an organization which engages in lobbying.
<P>
Most reassuring were the responses to all UTF concerns, expressed by three eminent attorneys,
each working extensively within the association community, that consolidation, with all the
protections requested by the UTF, is eminently doable.

<H2>Transition Issues:</H2>

Once the concept of consolidation is approved by each Board and the memberships endorse
forward movement, there are several critical transition issues and processes to address. In many
consolidations, a transition team oversees the process, often working with subcommittees on
special parts of the process. Areas that need attention during the period between endorsement of
the concept by the membership and final approval of the bylaws changes necessary to effect the
consolidation, include:

<H3>1)  Search Committee:</H3>

    The establishment of a search committee to work with whatever search consultant is
retained to help design the job description, role delineation, education and experience
requirements, salary and benefit range and profile for the first Executive Director of the
organization.
<P>
    The UTF recommends early attention to this critical task so that an Executive Director can
be hired with dispatch, to work with the transition teams and help put in place the staffing
required for a smooth transition. 

<H3>2)  Addressing Governance Issues:</H3>

    Careful preparation for new governance, including appointment of the first Nominating
Committee, the creation of guidelines  that require governance to be reflective of the diversity of
the membership, and the responsibility for holding open elections, is essential.  Because all
systems will be new, it is vital that the first effort work as smoothly and equitably as possible. 
Above all, this would be an early occasion to demonstrate the association's ability to meet the
promises made. 
<P>
    During this activity, the issues of leadership succession, i.e. dealing with placement of
those members now about to assume leadership in each of the participating organizations, must
be considered.

<H3>3)  Additional Legal Work:</H3>

    Ultimately, there will have to be a "due diligence" review of all legal issues, outstanding
contracts and commitments, reconciliation of pension plans and other documents, and a fiscal
audit, all intended to protect the boards and members of each organization. A summary of the due
diligence findings should be included when the plan is finally presented to the members of each
organization for ratification and approval of the bylaws changes required. 
<P>
    The state where each participating organization is now incorporated will dictate the
requirements for member votes on the consolidation. In Pennsylvania (site of incorporation of the
ABIH) and in Ohio (site of incorporation for ACGIH) a majority vote of the membership is
required.  In Illinois (site of the incorporation of AIHA), a 2/3 membership vote is required.
<P>
    Since it is possible to consolidate two or more organizations by dissolving all participating
organizations and creating a new one, and also possible to consolidate organizations by retaining
one as the corporate shell, there are major decisions to be made in this area, decisions which
should be made with outside counsel.  The decision as to which path to take is usually    dictated by which is the more expedient method, i.e. which is easier, cheaper and safer, and
which is acceptable to existing organizations.
<P>
    Finally, bylaws will need to be drafted for the consolidated organization.

<H3>4)  Headquarters:
</H3>
    Since the consolidation plan calls for a single headquarters with separate "wings" for each
subsidiary organization (and the pro forma budget anticipates this), it will be necessary to
consider all headquarters-related issues during the transition.  
    This will include selecting a site, phasing out existing space contracts, sensitivity to staff
disruptions and concerns, etc.

<H3>5)  Publications:</H3>

    Consolidation of the AIHA and ACGIH Journals and other appropriate publications, e.g.
newsletters and membership directories.

<H3>6)  Guidelines:</H3>

    Guidelines for establishing public policy and utilizing member input, as well as for
determining which initiatives to pursue, must be crafted. 

<H3>7)  Master Calendar:</H3>

    Development of a master calendar, to assure that support of scheduled programs, services,
conferences, etc. is maintained.

<H3>8)  Fiscal Issues:</H3>

    These fall into two categories.  The first deals with funding the transition. 
<P>
    The second deals with completing an actual budget for the first full year of operations of the consolidated organization, for presentation and approval by the first Board when it is duly elected and seated.

<H3>9)  Name and Logo:</H3>

    The UTF made an early decision to leave these issues to the transition teams.  
<P>
<STRONG>It is anticipated that all transition activities can be completed, including the final membership
votes on bylaws, in time to launch the consolidated organization at the May, 1997, AIHCE
Conference. </STRONG>
      
<H2>Conclusion:</H2>

All the members of the UTF expressed appreciation for having been selected to work on this
important and ambitious project, and expressed thanks to their respective organizations for the
privilege of serving.  They completed their work with increased respect and admiration for each
other and for the work of each participating organization.
<P>
John Adams wrote of the First Continental Congress, "Every man was an orator, a critic and a
statesman, and therefore every man upon every question must show his oratory, his criticism and
his political abilities."  With questions of such lasting importance before that Congress, all of us
remain grateful that  "Every question was discussed with a moderation, acuteness and minuteness
equal to that of Queen Elizabeth's Privy Council!".  
<P>
During all UTF meetings, every person certainly demonstrated his / her critical, statesman, and
political skills as well. And every item was reviewed in as much detail and with as much care as
was possible.  John Adams and Queen Elizabeth I would have been proud! Inestimable hours at
formal meetings and at work on interim assignments were generously offered, and always
without complaint.
<P>
While the First Continental Congress anticipated a negative reception to its work in London, and
therefore voted to meet again after their formal tenure was over, the UTF believes it has fully
executed its charge and fully completed its business.  It does not expect to meet again.
<P>
The UTF anticipates that this report will receive a careful review by Boards and members, in an
environment which looks at what might be, rather than at what is.  If this report receives less than
that, it will end up a "filing cabinet" report. 
<P>
These recommendations are offered as the UTF's best efforts to position the profession for the
future. AAIH, ABIH, ACGIH and AIHA may accept or reject some or all of these
recommendations, but those decisions should be made as objectively as possible, attentive to the
best interests of industrial hygienists and those they serve. 
<P>                          
<CENTER>
Report  prepared by Dadie Perlov, CAE, Founder and Principal<BR>
                   Consensus Management Group<BR>
                          914-783-4714<BR>
                    Facilitator for the UTF<BR>
                          May  9, 1996<BR>
</CENTER>
