<HEAD>
<TITLE>AIHCE Call for Abstracts</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG SRC="graphics/97logo.gif"ALT="[AIHCE  97 Logo]"><BR>
<H1>Announcing . . . Call for Abstracts</H1>
<H2>Platform and Poster Presentations</H2>
<H3>American Industrial Hygiene Conference & Exposition</H3>
<B>May 17-23, 1997</B><BR>
<I>Dallas Convention Center<BR>
Dallas, Texas</I>
<P>
Cosponsored by the American Industrial Hygiene Association and the American Conference of
Governmental Industrial Hygienists <BR>
<P>
<H2>Taking Responsibility: Building Tomorrow's Profession</H2>
Recognizing that occupational and environmental health and safety is at a crossroads, do you
count yourself as one of the profession's new pioneers? Evaluating the horizon, are you willing to
seize the opportunity to shape the future of the profession, to anticipate the right directions?
<P>
The 1997 AIHCE Program Committee invites members of AIHA and ACGIH, as well as
nonmembers, to submit abstracts on occupational health and safety and related topics.

<H2>Abstract Instructions</H2>
All abstracts must be received by October 17, 1996. All instructions must be followed for an
abstract to be considered by the 1997 AIHCE Program Committee, comprised of the Permanent
Conference Committee and the 1997 Technical Committee.<BR>

<H3>Requirements of Abstract Content</H3>
<DL>
<DT>1. Your abstract must be NO MORE than 300 words,  contained within the lined
boundaries of the form and appear in Helvetica, Courier or Times Roman fonts.<BR>
<DT>2. Abstracts that suggest commercialism, either through writing style or trade names, will
be rejected.<BR>
<DT>3. Abstracts should not contain tables, figures, structural formulas, or bibliographic
references.<BR>
<DT>4. The substance of the abstract must not have been presented or published
previously.<BR>
<DT>5. Promissory statements, such as "will be discussed, will be presented, will be studied, or
will be analyzed," cannot be accepted.<BR>
<DT>6. The program committee's decision to accept or reject an abstract will be based on
inclusion of the following items: (NOTE: There will be NO opportunity for abstract
revisions.)<BR>
<DD>A. Purpose and reasons for work: Is the purpose clearly stated, creative, or original?
<DD>B. Experimental procedures and discussion: Are procedures well described, clear,
organized, authoritative, specific and analytical? Is supporting data included?
<DD>C. Application to the practice of industrial hygiene: Is there a direct application?
<DD>D. Conclusions: Are they based on data or substantiated recommendations? 
<DD>E. Audience appeal: Will other industrial hygienists want to attend this presentation? Is it
suited for a poster or platform?
</DL>
<H3>Topic Preference</H3>
Identify three subject areas to which the paper is best suited. Type the topic numbers in the
spaces provided on the abstract form.<BR>
<DL><DT>1. Aerosols          
<DT>2. Agricultural Health and Safety       
<DT>3. Air-Sampling Instrument Performance       
<DT>4. Applied Engineering (not Ventilation)          
<DT>5. Bioaerosols      
<DT>6. Biological Monitoring      
<DT>7. Biosafety and Biotechnology          
<DT>8. Computer Applications      
<DT>9. Community Environmental Health and Safety      
<DT>10. Communication and Training          
<DT>11. Confined Spaces      
<DT>12. Construction
<DT>13. Contaminant Control       
<DT>14. Ergonomics      
<DT>15. Exposure Assessment Strategies      
<DT>16. Fibers (MMMF)        
<DT>17. Gas and Vapor Detection        
<DT>18. Hazard Communication      
<DT>19. Hazardous Waste      
<DT>20. Health Care Industries         
<DT>21. Indoor Air Quality        
<DT>22. Industrial Hygiene General Practice      
<DT>23. International Occupational Hygiene Issues          
<DT>24. Ionizing Radiation/Radon       
<DT>25. Laboratory Health and Safety        
<DT>26. Lead       
<DT>27. Management/Leadership          
<DT>28. Noise      
<DT>29. Nonionizing Radiation          
<DT>30. Occupational Epidemiology      
<DT>31. Occupational Medicine          
<DT>32. Personal Protective Clothing and Equipment         
<DT>33. Process Hazards Management and Engineering         
<DT>34. Product Health and Safety/Product Stewardship      
<DT>35. Respiratory Protection         
<DT>36. Risk Assessment (Risk Management)        
<DT>37. Sampling and Lab Analysis      
<DT>38. Social Issues        
<DT>39. Standards of Good Practice          
<DT>40. Taking Responsibility: Building Tomorrow's Profession*
<DT>41. Toxicology      
<DT>42. Ventilation
<DT>43. Other:_________________________________
</DL>
*Note: We welcome abstracts written on the 1997 theme, Taking Responsibility:
Building Tomorrow's Profession. If enough papers are generated, a session will be formed.
<P>
<H3>Select Presentation Style</H3>
Choose platform or poster presentation and indicate your choice in the space provided on the
abstract form. The Program Committee will do its best to comply with the author's first
preference; however, it reserves the right to assign papers according to space limitations and
other factors. 
<BR>
<B>Platform:</B> An oral presentation limited to 20 minutes (strictly enforced) that may be
accompanied by 35-mm slides. No other audiovisual equipment is permitted. 
<BR>
<B>Poster:</B> A visual display (approximately 8 ft. x 4 ft.) on fiberboard. The scheduling of
poster sessions includes a two-hour period during which the author is in attendance to answer
questions and a period of time when the poster will be unattended but available for walk-by
viewing.
<BR>
<H3>Preparing Your Abstract for Mailed Submission Only: Read Carefully!</H3>
<DL><DT>1. Abstracts must clearly typed or printed, and free from grammatical errors. Type
must appear in Times Roman, Courier, or Helvetica fonts. There is no minimum word
requirement; the maximum word limit is 300 words.<BR>
<DT>2. Make the title brief, clearly indicating the nature of your abstract. Type the title in ALL
CAPS starting on the first line at the top of the abstract form.<BR>
<DT>3. Leave two spaces after the title, continue with the author information: INITIALS then
LAST NAME, employer, and complete address of each author. List the presenting author first.
Underline the initials and last name of presenting author only.<BR>
<DD>a. For authors who have the same employer and address, list all names, separated by
commas, and then employer and address.
<DD>b. Do not use titles or degrees after the authors' names.<BR>
<DT>4. Leave a blank line between the heading and abstract text. Single-space throughout
paragraphs, and double-space between paragraphs. DO NOT INDENT.<BR>
<DT>5. Abstracts should be written without touching or going beyond the lines on either side.
Only one-page abstracts, submitted on the original abstract form, will be considered.<BR>
<DT>6. Use standard abbreviations and symbols (refer to <I>American Industrial Hygiene
Association Journal,</I> published by AIHA, or <I>Applied Occupational and Environmental
Hygiene,</I> published by ACGIH). Keep abbreviations to a minimum, and define each one
when used for the first time.<BR></DL>
Since only original abstract forms will be accepted, it is recommended that you first practice
printing out or typing your abstract on a photocopy of the form.

<H3>Submission of Abstracts</H3>
NEW this year! Three ways to submit your abstract! Submit your abstract via mail, fax, or the
Internet!<BR>
1. Mailing your abstract:<BR>
<UL><LI>Mail all abstracts flat (do not fold). A cardboard backing is recommended,
particularly for overseas mailings.
<LI>Complete the acknowledgment card; it is the ONLY notice of receipt you will receive. Do
not staple or tape anything to the original form.
<LI>Before mailing, use the checklist provided in this brochure to ensure that your submission
is correct and complete.
<LI>Mailing address: American Industrial Hygiene Conference & Exposition, Attn.:
Conference Programs Coordinator, 2700 Prosperity Ave., Suite 250, Fairfax, VA 22031.</UL>
2. Please take the following steps to ensure a clear submission when faxing your abstract:<BR>
<UL><LI>Use an original abstract form.
<LI>Type all information on the form. 
<LI>Fax on a FINE RESOLUTION setting.  
<LI>Before faxing, use the checklist provided in this brochure to ensure that your submission is
correct and complete.
<LI>Fax to: (703) 207-3561. Plan ahead: Fax early!</UL><BR>
IMPORTANT NOTICE: AIHCE will not be able to send confirmation notices for faxes. Please
DO NOT call to verify receipt of your fax. If your fax is illegible, we will make two attempts to
call you for a re-submission. All faxes must be received on or before October 17, 1996.
<P>
3. Using the web form:<BR>
<UL><LI><A HREF="./aihce97/abform.html">Access the 1997 AIHCE Abstract Submission
Form</A></UL>

<H3>Deadline for Submitting Abstracts</H3>
1. Abstracts must be received by October 17, 1996. ONLY THOSE ABSTRACTS RECEIVED
BY THE DEADLINE WILL BE CONSIDERED BY THE PROGRAM COMMITTEE. NO
EXCEPTIONS WILL BE MADE.<BR>
2. Abstracts received after the October 17, 1996, deadline will be returned to the author.

<H3>Notifications</H3>
1. Presenting authors will receive all correspondence concerning the abstract. Secondary authors
will not receive notification.<BR>
2. The AIHCE office will acknowledge receipt of the abstract by returning to you the enclosed
postcard in mailed submissions. Fax and web submissions will not receive a return postcard. If
the presenting author does not receive notification in one month, the AIHCE office should be
contacted.<BR>
NOTE: Acknowledgment does not indicate acceptance for presentation.<BR>
3. Presenting authors will receive notification of abstract acceptance or rejection by January 31,
1997.<BR>

<H3>Abstract Preparation Tips</H3>
Follow these tips to avoid making mistakes that may result in the abstract's rejection by the
Program Committee.<BR>
<P>
<B>Abstract Tips</B>
<DL><DT>1. Title should be in all caps and should fill area from left to right margin before
beginning next line at left margin.
<DT>2. Presenting author must be underlined.
<DT>3. Authors' first and middle initials followed by last names should be provided.
<DT>4. Complete addresses should be listed for all authors.
<DT>5. Copy lines should not exceed lined area.
<DT>6. Work cannot have been previously published or submitted for publication.
<DT>7. Type must be no less than 12 characters per inch (CPI) or 10 pt. font size.
<DT>8. Do not excessively use company names; this suggests commercialism.
<DT>9. Company product should not be commercialized.
<DT>10. Abstract should not refer to another work; it should stand on its own.
<DT>11. Purpose for work must be indicated.
<DT>12. Data or description of evaluation process must be included.
<DT>13. Conclusions must be offered.
<DT>14. Promissory statements suggest work still in progress. Abstract should not be submitted
unless work is completed.
<DT>15. References are not permitted in abstracts.
<DT>16. Check abstract carefully for typographical errors.
</DL>
THE QUALITY OF THE ABSTRACT IS THE SINGLE MOST IMPORTANT FACTOR IN
THE PROGRAM COMMITTEE'S DECISION TO ACCEPT OR REJECT THE  ABSTRACT.

<H3>Example of a High-Quality Abstract</H3>
A high quality abstract, in addition to the requirements specified in this brochure, also
incorporates the following:<BR>
1. Acceptable font and type size.<BR>
2. Copy within the lined area.<BR>
3. Clean copy, no typographical errors.<BR>
4. Application to the practice of industrial hygiene.<BR>

<H3>Changes, Cancellations, Withdrawals</H3>
<UL><LI>Under no circumstances can an abstract that has been submitted for presentation be
changed. A submitted abstract is regarded by the Program Committee as a commitment to
present.
<LI>Cancellations, particularly after the abstract has been accepted, are viewed by the Program
Committee as highly unprofessional. 
<LI>If extenuating circumstances prevent the presenting author from making the presentation, it
is that author's obligation to find an alternate presenter. 
<LI>Withdrawals must be in writing to the AIHCE office as soon as possible.</UL>

<H3>Publication Policy</H3>
The <I>American Industrial Hygiene Association Journal,</I> published by AIHA, and
<I>Applied Occupational and Environmental Hygiene, </I>published by ACGIH, have first
publication rights to all papers presented at the AIHCE. If an author plans to publish the paper, it
must be submitted after presentation at the AIHCE.

<H3>Checklist</H3>
Before submitting your abstract to the American Industrial Hygiene Conference & Exposition,
please check the following list. Omission of any of the following items will result in the rejection
of your abstract.
<UL><LI>Is the abstract written in compliance with the "Requirements of Abstract Content?"
<LI>Have you indicated three subject areas to which the paper is best suited?
<LI>Have you carefully followed all the specifications outlined in the section "Preparing Your
Abstract?"
<LI>Have you used an original abstract form? (Do not fold if mailing.)
<LI>Have you filled out and enclosed the acknowledgment card for mailed submissions?
<LI>Have you mailed, faxed, or e-mailed your abstract in sufficient time to reach the AIHCE
office on or before October 17, 1996?</UL>

<H3>Speaker Registration</H3>
All technical session speakers must register for the conference. Speakers attending ONLY the
technical session where they must make a presentation may contact the conference programs
coordinator about obtaining a speaker's pass valid for the two- to four-hour session only.
Members of AIHA and ACGIH are not eligible to use this pass. In all other cases, full conference
registration or one-day registration fees apply.

<H3>Certification Maintenance Points</H3>
The American Board of Industrial Hygiene (ABIH) will award 0.5 CM point per presentation for
ABIH certified industrial hygienists (CIHs) who give a poster presentation at AIHCE. During a
Diplomate's six-year CM cycle, 20-minute platform presentations may be accumulated to equal
one hour which is awarded 0.5 CM point.
<P>
ABSTRACTS MUST BE RECEIVED AT THE AIHCE OFFICE BY OCTOBER 17, 1996.
ABSTRACTS RECEIVED AFTER THE DEADLINE WILL NOT BE CONSIDERED FOR
PRESENTATION; THEY WILL BE MAILED BACK TO THE AUTHOR.

<H2>Mark Your Calendar!</H2>
<DL><DT>October 17, 1996<DD>Deadline for receipt of 1996 AIHCE abstract submissions
<DT>November 4, 1996<DD>PCC Review Meeting
<DT>December 3, 1996<DD>PCC Planning Meeting
<DT>December 4, 1996<DD>Session Arrangers Meeting
<DT>February 1997<DD>1997 AIHCE Advance Program containing registration and housing
materials to be mailed
<DT>May 17-23, 1997<DD>American Industrial Hygiene Conference & Exposition, Dallas,
Texas</DL><BR>
<P>
<P>
