<head>
<title>AIHA Board of Directors Meeting</title>
</head>
<body>
<center><h1>Board of Directors Meeting</h1>
<b>March 14, 1996<BR>
Tyson's Corner Marriott
Tyson's Corner, Virginia</b></center>
<HR>
<H3>Officers Attending:</H3>
V. Rose, Z. Mansdorf, J. Burton, J. Lynch, J. Thornton, L. Anderson
<H3>Directors Attending:</H3>
D. Bissonnette, P. Brogan, W. Dyson, M. Herr, J. Lee, G. McCluskey, A. Nichting, D. Reid, U.
Wright, S. Wroblewski
<h3>Guests:</h3>
S. Shattuck, R. Coyne, Local Sections Council, S. DiNardi
<h3>Staff:</h3>
O. G. Banks, B. Morrison 
<h3>Staff Guests:</h3>
J. Lawrence, C. Tobin, A. Dees, D. Ethier, M. Gomez, A. Trippler
<HR>

<h3>1. Call to Order/Quorum Verification</h3>
President Rose called the meeting to order at 8:00 a.m.  Secretary Thornton confirmed a
quorum present.

<h3>2.  Secretary's Report - Thornton</h3>
Thorton briefly reviewed the minutes of the December 20, 1995 and asked for corrections
and/or revisions.  Hearing none, the following motion was presented:
<b>MOTION:</b>   Approve the minutes of the December 20, 1995 meeting as presented.
Passed.
<b>MOTION:</b>   Adopt and ratify the results of mail ballots and votes by telephone occurring
since last Board meeting. Passed
Thornton asked that board members update Action Item list and submit them to him.

<h3>3.  Treasurer's Report - Anderson</h3>
Anderson commended the Board and staff for their 1995 performance as the association
ended the year with a $600,000+ surplus over budget.  The annual audit looks very good with no
changes anticipated for year-end 1995.  Only minor management changes are expected in the
auditor's letter.  The sale of the Akron, Ohio building is not finalized.  A counter offer has been
made on the current contract, but it is not expected to be accepted.  An offer is expected next
week from a physician.  

<h3>4.  Conflict of Interest and Antitrust Policies - McCluskey</h3>
Discussion on the aspect of more members becoming consultants and the anticipated need
to have a way to deal with conflict of interest and antitrust issues.  It was a sense of the board to
get additional information from Attorney Herold and revisit the issue on the May agenda. 
Motion was withdrawn until the May meeting.

<h3>5. Policy Manual - Burton</h3>
Discussion of the Task Force's objectives.  Burton and Morrison met and reviewed the
ASAE's Board Policy Manual.  The project is to start with simply collecting and reviewing
existing policies and reviewing the Motion Log for other policies that should be part of the
manual.  This project has a 1997 due date.

<h3>6. Update OHSMS - Lee/McCluskey</h3>
There will be an ANSI meeting on May 7 and 8.  The Task Force would like a final
format to present at that meeting.  Draft 5 will be complete and sent out for mail ballot prior to
that time.  This is a should/shall document.  The shall is effective once a company accepts the
document for implementation.  Editorial changes are due by Friday, March 22 to Dave Dyjak.

<h3>7. Emerging Issues Committee Update - Burton</h3>
The second draft of emerging issues is complete; the third draft will be ready in May. 
Discussion centered on the fact that the Committee needs fewer listed items.  The Board feels the
Committee should present ideas with the effects of AIHA members in a complete report rather
than a string of listed topics.  Rose and Mansdorf will work with the Committee to get them
integrated into the Strategic Plan and request the Committee Chair participate in the Friday
Board meeting during the 2-hour Strategic Plan discussion so that they provide input for the
August Strategic Planning meeting in Boston. 

<h3>8.  Travel Expense Guidelines - Anderson</h3>
During the last budget development process for Committees, the Finance Committee
requested that a document outlining the Travel Expense Reimbursement Guidelines for
Committees be developed.  After much discussion, the Board has recommended that the
Guideline that was presented in the Board packet be broadened for Task Forces, Board members,
etc.  With that assignment, Anderson and Morrison will rework the document.  It will then be
sent out for mail ballot approval.  The Motion presented was withdrawn pending the document
revision.

<h3>9. Establishment of a Joint Ethics Education Committee - Nichting</h3>
After discussion of how to proceed, it was determined that we should move forward with
a Joint Ethics Education program.  It was decided that appointment of the four AIHA
representatives to the Joint Ethics Education Committee would also be the same individuals
appointed to the AIHA Ethics Committee.<BR>
<b>MOTION:</b>   Approve the creation of a Standing Joint Ethics Education Committee.
Passed.

<h3>10.  Changes to Investment Policy - McCluskey</h3>
A mail ballot was approved in May 1994 giving responsibility for the Investment Policy
to the Finance Committee.  The Board now wishes to rescind that decision and revise the
Investment Policy.<BR>
<b>MOTION:</b>   Move that the Investment Policy (dated 11/21/95) be revised as
follows:<br>
<i>Procedure 1B</i> - "Recommendations for any revisions or modifications will be made by
the
Treasurer, Executive Director and Comptroller to the Finance Committee and approved by the
Board of Directors."<BR>
<i>Procedure 4B</i> - "The Executive Director and Comptroller will review the candidate(s)
and make
a recommendation to the Board of Directors for approval."
Passed.

<h3>11.  Consultants' Task Force Survey - Burton</h3>
The Task Force feels that the long term future will require a Special Interest Group for
Consultants within the association.  They would like to see this pursued.  Mansdorf also reported
that there will be a Consultants' Symposium in November in Las Vegas.

<h3>12.  Supporting Research and Technical Development at AIHF - Burton</h3>
Burton stated that after discussing this idea with several persons involved with the
Foundation fundraising campaign this issue would be better discussed at a later date.  Burton
rescinded his Motion and will submit after the fundraising campaign is complete.

<h3>13.  Use of Titles in Database and Directory - Banks</h3>
Discussion of various options of choosing 1, 2, 3 or no designations.  It was finally
determined that AIHA will list any and all designations submitted by the member for inclusion in
the database and Directory.  However a disclaimer will be listed indicating that no verification or
checking as to the validity of designations has been done.

<h3>14.  Update Priority Issues - Burton</h3>
<UL><LI>OSHA Reform - The House is delaying action until next year.  OSHA may receive a
10% budget cut.
<LI>NIOSH still does not have an approved budget for this year.
<LI>Indiana has passed a Title Protection Bill.
<LI>Six states have passed Title Protection.
<LI>Multiple Chemical Sensitivities - Reid - Draft document is almost ready and will be
issued soon.
<LI>Reproduction Hazards - Reid - Many problems with the Task Force.</UL></LI>

<h3>15.  11 Board Issues - Rose</h3>
<UL><LI>The National Occupational Research Agenda (NORA) meeting will be April 29, 1996
in D.C. to celebrate NIOSH's 25th anniversary.
<LI>Rose, Mansdorf, Burton and Trippler met with Joe Dear on March 13, 1996.
<LI>Community Service - R. Sheriff sent memos to the Board on outreach opportunities
through the Local Sections.
<LI>Officer/Director Time - This is obviously still a concern evidenced by the difficulty we
had in obtaining candidates for the 1996 Board election.</UL></LI>

<h3>16.  Standards of Good Practice Update - Burton</h3>
This Task Force surveyed the technical committees.  IAQ and Ergonomics want to write
Standards of Good Practice for their specific areas of expertise.  The Task Force will present
recommendations in May.  AIHA needs to develop a number of levels of standards, guidelines,
etc.  Board is to submit responses, ideas, etc. to the Task Force.  

<h3>17.  Status Report on NIOSH Book - Rose/DiNardi</h3>
DiNardi gave a status-to-date review of the book.  The final publication will have 52
chapters.  He has enlisted 50 authors.  Drafts for the chapters are due either May 1 or June 1;
each being approximately 30 chapter pages.  Final drafts are due November 1.

<h3>18.  Technical Committees - Burton</h3>
The Interim Draft Report was presented.  The Board is to provide written feedback to the
Task Force on this draft report within two weeks.

<h3>19.  Leadership Workshop/Local Sections - Mansdorf</h3>
91 attendees are expected at the Leadership Workshop.  Having the Board Coordinators
call their individual committees and local sections really seemed to boost the interest and
attendance.  
<P>
Joint expectations is the issue with Local Sections.  The Board approved Local Section
partnership from December was sent to the Local Sections last week.  Results are due back in
mid-April.  The needs assessment is still in the working stage.  
<P>
The Student Local Section Award was received as a good idea by the Board.  The sense
of the Board was that AIHA would fund the award.  The specific information will be in the May
Board packet for action at that time.

<h3>20.  Strategic Plan Update - Mansdorf</h3>
The Past President will have the responsibility of the strategic planning meeting.  There
will be a 2-hour strategic plan discussion at the Friday AIHCE Board meeting.  The August
Strategic Planning meeting will be in Boston.  Schedule for action this year; May - cover essence
of the major issues of the Plan; August - heavy discussion and "almost" finalization; mail ballot
to finalize; September is the due date for departmental business plans and preliminary budget
preparation; November - Finance Committee budget presentation.
<P>
Each Board member is to identify two trends and the corresponding outcomes from the
Strategic Plan that need to be redone/revised due to these trends.  Submit to A. Dees.   Rose,
Mansdorf and Burton will compile them.

<h3>21. - 26.   Information Only Reports</h3>

<h3>27.  Old Business - All</h3>
<UL><LI>Wroblewski announced that if the Board, as a group was interested, perhaps a private
tour of the White House or Capital could be arranged during AIHCE.
<LI>Lynch to pursue AIHA participation as a reviewer in Framework for Harmonization in
the area of risk assessment.
<LI>1:30 p.m. - 5:30 p.m. will be the Joint Boards' UTF meeting on Saturday, May 18 at
AIHCE.
<LI>The possibility of an Open Forum of the Joint Boards' to discuss UTF with the
membership on Tuesday, May 22 exists.</UL></LI><BR>
<b>MOTION:</b>   Move to adjourn the meeting. Passed.

<h3>Meeting was adjourned at 4:05 p.m.</h3>
<P>
<BR>
