<HEAD>
<TITLE>Addendum A: UTF Process</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H1><CENTER>Addendum A: UTF Process</CENTER></H1>
<HR>
<H2>THE UNIFICATION TASK FORCE PROCESS </H2>
                                
<H3>1. Unification Task Force</H3>

     The Unification Task Force (UTF) shall consist of three representatives from each
organization, for a total of 12.  The chief staff officer of each organization shall be expected to
attend each meeting, unless officially excused by that organization. The chief staff officer attends
as an ex officio representative with voice but not vote.

<H3>2. There will be no preconditions established. </H3>
Everything is negotiable.

<H3>3. No premature promises will be made for anything that will occur after conclusion of the talks. </H3>
Each organization will continue to handle its internal personnel issues and commitments until
then.

<H3>4. The Unification Task Force (UTF) members will remain in place until  the UTF completes its
business.</H3>

<H3>5. Full and Complete Negotiations</H3>

The parties shall negotiate fully and completely on every issue raised.

<H3>6. Timetable</H3>

The parties agree to establish agreed-upon goals as to what will be accomplished, including a
time table for accomplishing each of the major steps needed to reach those goals.  Timetables
may be subject to change in order to finish a goal properly and completely.

<H3>7. Timing of Meetings</H3>

The parties will set the full schedule of meetings for the remainder of 1995 and for the first
quarter of 1996.

<H3>8. Quorum</H3>

A meeting will be considered an official meeting if at least two voting representatives from each
organization are present.  While nomeeting will be canceled if only one voting representative
from any one organization can attend, any matter that requires a consensus decision will be
deferred until the next meeting when two voting representatives from each organization are in
attendance.

<H3>9. Agenda</H3>

Each IH organization agrees to adhere to the written agenda which will be distributed prior to
each meeting, unless there is agreement to waive this requirement for a specific meeting. 

<H3>10. Executive Summaries</H3>
The facilitator shall prepare and distribute an executive summary of each meeting.  Each
summary will be reviewed and approved at the following meeting.  The approved summaries will
be marked "Confidential/Not for Distribution."  The facilitator will also prepare an internal news
release after each meeting that can be shared through each organization's newsletter/publication.

<H3>11. Caucus</H3>

The parties accept the concept of caucus whereby any party may ask for time to discuss pending
issues privately, or with the facilitator. The facilitator may also call a caucus.

<H3>12. Executive Session</H3>

Should any organization wish to call an executive session for voting members only, that can be
done with the agreement of at least three of the organizations.  The facilitator will attend these
sessions, unless the subject is the facilitator.

<H3>13. Media and Member Communications</H3>

The parties agree that all communications to the media and to the memberships regarding any
aspect of negotiations shall be by joint release or understanding.  Each organization shall appoint
a person to serve as media contact.  No individual interview or opinion will be shared outside the
UTF.  The facilitator will not speak to the media unless authorized by the UTF.  A news release
of the meeting will be prepared by the facilitator for use by each organization in their
newsletters/publications.  All UTF members will have an opportunity to review this release and
will be requested to immediately forward comments to their staff officer.

<H3>14. Special Assignments</H3>

Special task forces or task teams may be appointed as needed, from inside and beyond the UTF
roster.  These task forces may be assigned staff support and/or the services of the facilitator,
whichever is deemed      more appropriate.

<H3>15. Organization Executive Committees and Boards</H3>

The work and recommendations of the UTF should be reviewed on a regular basis.  The final
approved Executive Summary of each meeting will be provided to each organization's board of
directors by the Chief Staff Officer.
<P>
The UTF may call a joint meeting of the Executive Committees or  Boards, with the unanimous
consent of all parties.

<H3>16. Lines of Communication</H3>

    <STRONG> a.</STRONG> All correspondence, invoices, agendas and executive summaries shall be submitted by
the facilitator to each organization.<BR>

     <STRONG>b.</STRONG> Any member of the UTF may contact the facilitator at any time. <BR>

     <STRONG>c.</STRONG> The facilitator may contact any member of the UTF, if and as necessary.<BR>

     <STRONG>d.</STRONG> Individual expenses for each UTF participant  will be handled within each respective
organization.  Breakfast, lunch and related meeting expenses will be rotated among organizations
and all expenses will be reconciled among the organizations at the end of the UTF process.  


<H3>17. Projected Meetings</H3>

The order in which large issue areas will be addressed follows, subject to amendment and
revision, by the UTF and/or the facilitator, as required:
<P>
     <STRONG>a.</STRONG> Agreement as to UTF process.<BR>
     <STRONG>b.</STRONG> Finalize plan of work and time frame.<BR>
     <STRONG>c.</STRONG> Develop a compelling vision of the future for industrial hygiene.<BR>
     <STRONG>d.</STRONG> Determine criteria against which decisions will be evaluated.<BR>
     <STRONG>e.</STRONG> Programs and services issues<BR>
     <STRONG>f.</STRONG> Role in public policy<BR>
     <STRONG>g.</STRONG> Image and identity, for the profession and the unified entity<BR>
     <STRONG>h.</STRONG> Membership criteria and categories; local groups/sections     <BR>
     <STRONG>i.</STRONG> Structure needed to accommodate all of the above.<BR>
     <STRONG>j.</STRONG> Governance desired and required<BR>
     <STRONG>k.</STRONG> Financing the operation: Drafting the first pro forma budget<BR>
     <STRONG>l.</STRONG> Headquarters and staffing issues<BR>

          
<H3>18. Unification Task Force Charge</H3>
                                
The Unification Task Force (UTF) is charged by the  Boards of Directors of the AAIH, ABIH,
ACGIH, and AIHA "with researching and analyzing all available background information and
data in order to make recommendations to the four governing bodies regarding the efficacy of
uniting the four organizations for the benefit of the profession and the respective members of the
four organizations.
<P>
These recommendations may take the form of one or more proposals ranging from maintaining
the status quo to any of a number of kinds of unification. The UTF will prioritize its
recommendations/proposals and provide appropriate rationale and explanation for each of them.
<P>
The primary thrust of the UTF will be to determine what forms, if any, of unification are
advisable and to describe them in sufficient detail to permit the respective organizations to fully
evaluate the options and make appropriate decisions on each."

<H3>19. Last Steps</H3>
      
If the UTF determines that formal unification is not in the best interest of members, then a full
report of the rationale for that decision shall be developed and presented to each respective
board.  If the UTF determines that formal unification is in the best interest of the organizations,
the UTF will provide for the preparation of a transition plan.
<P>
This process has been agreed to by members of the UTF.
<P>
<CENTER>
                   Consensus Management Group<BR>
                           PO Box 407<BR>
                       Harriman, New York<BR>
                          914-893-4714<BR>
                       FAX: 914-782-4539<BR>
</CENTER>
<P>
