<H2><A NAME="notes">NOTES & ASSUMPTIONS</A></H2>

Overall, a conservative perspective was taken on revenues and a more liberal perspective on expenses.  As a result, the pro forma excess of revenue over expense may be regarded as a minimum.

                                
<H3>NOTES</H3>

A.    Dues were calculated only after all other revenue and expense had been determined and are based on a 6.7% margin
(excess of revenue over expense as a percentage of total revenue.)  The resulting dues is $110.  No dues are allocated to program areas. The certification maintenance fee is reduced to $50.
<P>
Total dues of $1,953,950
<PRE>
         Fellow, Full & Affiliate @ $110         $1,375,000
         800 Student @ $22                           17,600
         700 Retired @ $55                           38,500
         350 org. mbrs. At $550                     192,500
      6,607 cert. maint. @ $50                      330,350
                                                 $1,953,950
</PRE>
B.    PCIH becomes the Mid-Year Conference of the new organization.  The ACGIH management contract with AAAR is assumed
by the new organization.
<P>
C.    Represents the existing two newsletters, one magazine (The Synergist), three membership directories, and three
annual reports and assumes there would be only one of each.
<P>
D.   AIHA donates $85,000 in staff and space expense to the foundation.    
<P>
E.    Assumes one journal and uses the financially larger of the two current journals for pro forma budget purposes. 
Journal income does not include any portion of dues payments; (nor do any other program areas).
<P>
F.    The savings listed are primarily the reduction in Staff.
<P>
G.   These overlapping programs had savings of direct costs and indirect costs.
<P>
H.   These non-overlapping programs had savings of indirect expenses only. e.g. some salaries, rent, utilities, etc. <P>   
I.    Because ACGIH now reimburses travel expense of volunteers more typically than does AIHA, a contingency of $300,000
is included in case those typically not reimbursed by AIHA currently begin to request reimbursement from the new
organization.  AIHA currently reimburses approximately $200,000 per year.  This contingency therefore provides an
additional $300,000.
<P>
J.    Adj./Savings of $1,107,300 breakdown:

<PRE>
              Staff                   $973,000
              Rent                     138,000
              Other                    296,000
              Contingency             (300,000)
                                     $1,107,300
</PRE>
<P>
K.   The $184,000 "Savings" is the amount of AIHCE income paid to ACGIH which amount would now remain with the
consolidated organization.
<P>
L.   Staffing is reduced by 16.9 FTEs resulting in a decrease in expense for salaries, taxes and benefits of $973,000.  


<H3>ASSUMPTIONS</H3>

1.  The starting point is the total of the 5 organizations' 1996 budgets plus 5% (AAIH, ABIH, ACGIH, AIHA, AIHAF).
<P>
2.  The assumed first year of operations is 1997.
<P>
3.  The one-time costs of consolidation are separately detailed on Page 5.
<P>
4.  Revenues and expenses are reduced by intercompany payments (e.g. AIHCE, AIHAF, AAIH, etc.).
<P>
5.  Technical publication sales remain unchanged.
<P>
6.  Funds available for investment are temporarily reduced by the one-time costs of consolidation, thus temporarily
reducing interest income in the first year of operations.
<P>
7.    Rent is assumed to be in a high cost city like Washington, D.C.  The amount of office space is reduced due to
decreased staffing.  The average annual cost per FTE of salaries, taxes, and fringe is $55,000 (1997), based on current
existing costs of the four IH organizations.
<P>
8.   No new programs and services are assumed in this pro forma budget. 
<P>
<BR>
