<HEAD>
<TITLE>The Proficiency Analytical Testing (PAT) Program 
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H1>The Proficiency Analytical Testing (PAT) Program</H1>
<P>The Proficiency Analytical Testing (PAT) Program is designed
to assist a laboratory improve its analytical performance by providing samples on a quarterly
basis, evaluating the results, and providing a report on how well the laboratory performed. 
In the same way, the PAT Program also tests the analytical competence of participating
occupational health laboratories.  Samples are developed and produced by SRI International.
 Data analysis and distribution of reports are performed by NIOSH as permitted under a
Cooperative Research and Development Agreement (CRADA) with AIHA.</P>
<P>The analytes covered under the PAT Program include: metals, silica, asbestos, and
solvents.</P>
<HR>
<UL>
<LI><A HREF="#PAT3"> Who should participate in the PAT Program?</A>
<LI> <A HREF="#PAT4"> How the program works</A>
<LI> <A HREF="#PAT5"> Are special analytical methods required?</A>
<LI> <A HREF="#PAT6"> What happens after the results are mailed?</A>
<LI> <A HREF="#PAT7"> Do all laboratories analyze all the contaminant samples?</A>
<LI> <A HREF="fax.html">Fees and application for the program</A>
</UL>
<BR>
<BR>
<H2><A NAME="PAT3">Who should participate in the PAT Program?</A></H2>
<P> If a laboratory analyzes samples taken from the workplace environment, then participation
in the in the PAT Program can provide information to clients on laboratory performance.  In
addition, a laboratory must be a part of the PAT Program to participate in AIHA's Laboratory
Industrial Hygiene Accreditation Program.</P>
<H2><A NAME="PAT4">How the program works?</A></H2>
<P> Once enrolled in the program, a laboratory will begin to receive sample kits on a quarterly
basis.  Based on what analyses are performed by the laboratory, these kits contain up to five
silica filters, five asbestos filters, five metals filters, and ten charcoal tubes (four samples, a blank
and five tubes for determination of desorption efficiency). The metals filters contain three metals
(lead, cadmium, zinc, or chromium) which are rotated on the samples that are distributed each
round.  The charcoal tubes contain three organic solvents that are also rotated each round and
include benzene, carbon tetrachloride, chloroform, 1,2-dichloroethane, 1,1,1-trichloroethane,
o-xylene, p-dioxane, toluene, trichlorethylene, or tetrachlorethylene.</P>
<H2><A NAME="PAT5">Are special analytical methods required?</A></H2>
<P>The PAT Program does not specify a particular analytical method to be used.  A laboratory
should use the same procedures when analyzing the PAT samples that it would use when
analyzing similar types of samples in normal operations.  This allows the effectiveness of the
analytical methods used by the laboratory to be tested.  Except in instances where analytical
problems are found, PAT samples should be rotated among all analysts performing similar
analyses in the laboratory, results from only one analyst should be reported. Laboratories have
approximately six weeks after receipt of samples to submit results.
</P>
<H2><A NAME="PAT6">What happens after the results are mailed?</A></H2>
<P>The results are evaluated, and all laboratories are screened for those with questionable
performance.  Details of the statistical procedures used by NIOSH to analyze the data are
provided when laboratories enroll in the program.  Each laboratory will be notified of its status
prior to the next round of samples.  AIHA assists laboratories in making corrections and
modifications prior to the next round of sampling by making repeat samples available upon
request. </P>
<H2><A NAME="PAT7">Do all laboratories analyze all the contaminant samples?</A></H2>
<P>An AIHA industrial hygiene accredited laboratory is required to analyze and submit results
for those PAT samples that are similar to the analytical work load of the laboratory, so not all
laboratories will analyze all samples.  Non-accredited laboratories that participate in the PAT
Program analyze one or more of the samples.</P>
<BR>
<H2>Test Samples</H2> 
<P>AIHA offers samples from previous rounds for laboratories wishing to evaluate analytical
procedures
and quality control systems.  Certificate of analysis are provided with the samples to permit
evaluation of how well the laboratory performed.  Kits consist of four concentration levels for
each analyte, which 
include metals, asestos, silica, and solvents.  Blanks are provided with each analyte.</P> 
<BR>
<P>For more information on the PAT program, contact Anna Narlis-Griffin at (703) 849-8888;  
<A HREF="mailto:anarlis@aiha.org">anarlis@aiha.org</A></P>
<BR>
<A HREF="accred.html">Back to Accreditation Page</A> | <A
HREF="index.html">Back to AIHA Home Page</A>
</BODY>
