<HEAD>
<TITLE>New Programs</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H1> New Performance Testing Programs</H1>
<HR>
<UL>
<LI><A HREF="#passmoni">Passive Monitor PAT
Program</A><BR>
<LI><A HREF="#pbair">Lead in Air under the ELPAT Program</A><BR>
<LI><A HREF="#empat">Environmental Microbiology Proficiency
Analytical Testing
(EMPAT)
Program</A><BR>
</UL>
<BR>
<H2><A NAME="passmoni">Passive Monitor PAT Sampler
Program</A></H2>
<P>AIHA's new passive monitor PAT sampler program is open to all
PAT participating
laboratories, and AIHA is gauging laboratory interest in
participating in the first two
practice rounds of the program.</P>
<P>It's anticipated that two rounds per year with two badges per
round will be sent to
participating laboratories.  Initially, benzene, toluene, and
xylene will be used. 
Concentrations will be reported in ppm using manufacturers
information on diffusion and
concentration factors.  Costs haven't been established yet, but
it's estimated the price will
be $185 per round.</P>
<P> Interested laboratories also must identify the manufacturer
badge it wants to use
during the trial period: 3M, SKC, or Assay Technology. 
Eventually, accredited laboratories
that currently accept passive monitors for organic analysis will
be required to participate
in the passive monitor PAT sample.</P>
<P><B>To express interest in participating in the second practice
round of the passive monitor
PAT sample program,
contact Anna Narlis-Griffin at (703) 849-8888;
anarlis@aiha.org</B></P>  
<H2><A NAME="pbair">Lead in Air Under the ELPAT Program</A></H2>
<P>AIHA announces the availability of lead in air proficiency
samples.  Laboratories accredited as part of the ELLAP
that choose to accept lead in
air samples as part of their technical capabilities must enroll
in this program.  Samples will be
mailed quarterly on January 1, April 1, July 1, and October
1.</P>
</P>Note this schedule is different than the other ELPAT
matrices.  Results will be reported to
NIOSH and a detailed report will be sent approximately one month
after receipt of results. 
Laboratories desiring to add lead in air to their ELLAP
accreditation will be provided with an air
volume, be required to calculate the air concentration, and must
report the lead results on a
special
form.  In addition, an updated application, including appropriate
QA/QC information covering
the
lead in air matrix, must be submitted to AIHA and two consecutive
rounds with no more than
one
outlier will have to be reported to be considered proficient. 
Laboratories currently enrolled in the
PAT Program for metals will be required to report the lead
results twice; once for the PAT
Program and once for the ELPAT Program.  Separate forms will be
provided.</P>
<P>Laboratories interested in this program must notify Carl Bell
at AIHA (703) 849-8888. 
There
will be no additional charge for laboratories already enrolled in
the PAT Program for
metals.</P>
<BR>
<H2><A NAME="empat">Environmental Microbiology Proficiency
Analytical Testing
(EMPAT)
Program.</A></H2>
<P>The purpose of the program is
performance evaluation of environmental Microbiology
laboratories.  It has been developed for
microbiology laboratories specializing in analysis for
microorganisms commonly detected in air,
fluids
and bulk samples collected from schools, offices, hospitals,
industrial, agricultural and other
work
environments.  Environmental microorganisms in the EMPAT program
will include a variety of
fungi
(molds and yeasts) and mesophilic, thermophilic and psychrophilic
bacteria.</P>
<P>The initiation of the EMPAT program is the stepping stone to
an accreditation program for
environmental microbiology laboratories, similar to the current
AIHA accreditation for industrial
hygiene and environmental lead laboratories.  The program will
consist of three sample rounds
per
year.  Each round will include six samples (three bacteria and
three fungi) for microbial isolation
and
identification.</P>
<P>The program for 1997 will consist of 3 sample rounds.  The
first round will be mailed on February 1, the second round June
1, and the third round October 1, 1997.  The evaluation and
reporting fee for participation in this program is $900.  The fee
for the samples, beginning with the February round, is $900 ($300
for each of the three sample rounds).</P>
<P>For more information, contact Anna Narlis-Griffin at AIHA at
(703) 849-8888 or  <A
HREF="mailto:anarlis@aiha.org">anarlis@aiha.org</A>
<BR>
