<HEAD>
<TITLE>Lead Accreditation; 402/404C Final Rule Published</TITLE>
</HEAD>
</BODY>
<H1>Lead Accreditation; 402/404C Final Rule Published </H1>
<H3>(Vol 61; #169, p. 45777;
8/29/96)</H3>
<P>The Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) has recently published final rules for
lead-based paint
activities that require all samples be sent for analyses to a laboratory recognized by the EPA as
capable
of performing paint chip, soil, and dust wipe analyses  (EPA: 40CFR Part 745 "Lead
Requirements for
Lead-Based Paint Activities in Target Housing and Child-Occupied Facilities: Final Rule."). 
NLLAP
Recognition under National Lead Laboratory Accreditation Program (NLLAP) will be required
by clients
in order for a laboratory to analyze paint chip, dust, and/or soil samples associated with the
control and
abatement of lead-based paint.  For example, the most recent draft of the HUD Guidelines, now
recommends that laboratories be recognized through the EPA National Lead Laboratory
Accreditation
Program (NLLAP) and that property owners, risk assessors, inspector technicians, and
contractors ensure
that laboratory analyses are performed by an EPA recognized laboratory.<P> 
<P>Under legislative directive of Title X of the Housing and Community Development Act of
1992, the
EPA has established the NLLAP to recognize laboratories performing analysis associated with
lead
abatement.  NLLAP recognition of laboratories analyzing lead in paint chips, soils, and dust
wipes has
two requirements. (1) Successful participation in proficiency testing using real world matrices;
and (2)
laboratory accreditation including on-site assessment of laboratory operations.  NLLAP
requirements are
based upon the recommendations of a Federal Interagency Taskforce on Lead-Based Paint, a
group of 17
federal agencies involved with lead issues, that recognition should be based upon both
proficiency
testing and laboratory accreditation.<P>
<P>Laboratories interested in obtaining accreditation information such as the program
requirements,
time needed to complete the process, and cost should contact the American Industrial Hygiene
Association (AIHA).  Currently, over 100 laboratories are accredited and recognized by NLLAP
as
capable of performing paint chip, soil, and dust wipe analyses.  You should understand that
laboratory
accreditation can take months to achieve.  Laboratory accreditation involves submittal of an
application
including a description of your quality system and manual to the AIHA and an on-site evaluation
of
laboratory operations including equipment, facilities, analytical methods, staff, and internal
quality
control by AIHA assessors.  Only accredited laboratories which are NLLAP recognized are
included on
the list of laboratories used by the National Lead Clearinghouse to refer potential laboratory
clients.<P>
<P>Participation in the ELPAT proficiency testing program will continue to be open to all
interested
laboratories, however, the National Lead Clearinghouse will only provide a list of accredited
laboratories
to prospective laboratory users.  Only laboratories that have been accredited will be NLLAP
recognized
according to the final rules published by EPA.  Therefore, if analysis of lead in paint chip, dust
and soil
samples is important to your laboratory business, it is imperative that your laboratory begin the
accreditation process now.<P>
<P>Please contact <A HREF="mailto:cbell@aiha.org">Carl Bell at AIHA,</A> 2700 Prosperity
Ave.,
Suite
250, Fairfax, VA 22031, telephone number 703-849-8888 for more information and an
application.<P>
For more info on AIHA Lead Accreditation <A HREF="ellap1">Go to ELLAP</A> 
<BR>
<BR>
