<TITLE>AIHA Co-Sponsors Traveling Museum</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<BR>
<CENTER><H1>FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE<BR>
PRESS RELEASE</H1></CENTER>
<HR>
Contact:<BR>
<A HREF="mailto:cfeheley@aiha.org"> Christine Feheley</A><BR>
<A HREF="mailto:vpatterson@aiha.org"> Valerie Patterson</A><BR>
(703) 849-8888 <BR>
(703) 207-3561 fax <BR>
<HR>
<H2><CENTER> AMERICAN INDUSTRIAL HYGIENE ASSOCIATION CO-SPONSORS
FIRST TRAVELING MUSEUM EXHIBIT HIGHLIGHTING THE
PROFESSION</CENTER></H2>
<P>
(Washington, Oct. 18, 1996) -- The American Industrial Hygiene Association (AIHA), in
conjunction with the Baltimore Museum of Industry, ACGIH and ABIH, has developed a mobile
exhibit designed to profile the history, development and current work of the industrial hygiene
profession.  Currently hosted by the Baltimore Museum of Industry, this multi-paneled, multi-media exhibit will travel from one museum to another to heighten public awareness of the
industrial hygiene field.
<P>
"I think the exhibit will help reach people, especially young people, and let them know about a
very important profession that improves the quality of their lives, but one they probably never
knew existed," say John Serocki and Linda Rubin, members of the AIHA task force that helped
develop the exhibit.  Colorful photographs, graphics and text illustrate historic workplace perils,
modern environmental hazards and their control, the evolution of industrial hygiene,
occupational health pioneers, and legislation affecting industrial hygiene, including protective
standards and exposure limits.
<P>
Among those joining forces to complete the exhibit are local AIHA sections and individual
AIHA members, the Baltimore City Health Department, Johns Hopkins University's School of
Hygiene and Public Health, and ACGIH.  These parties contributed photographs, historic
instruments, respirators and other industrial hygiene artifacts and documentation.
<P>
For more information on the exhibit, please contact Vanessa Char, Chesapeake Local Section, at
(410) 671-4086 or the Baltimore Museum of Industry at (410) 727-4808.
<P>
The American Industrial Hygiene Association, with more than 12,000 members, is
the world's largest association serving occupational and environmental health and safety
professionals.

<P>
