<H2><CENTER> AIHA NAMES ITS TOP 10 ISSUES FOR 1997-1998</H2></CENTER>
<P>
(WASHINGTON, Jan. 2, 1997)   The American Industrial Hygiene Association (AIHA) has
chosen 10 issues as primary areas of interest for the association to focus on in 1997 and 1998. 
By concentrating on these essential proactive issues, AIHA is striving to remain a leader in the
occupational and environmental health and safety fields.  AIHA's top 10 list includes:
<P>
<B>(1) OSHA Reinvention, including:</B><BR>
Health/Safety Programs <BR>
Standard Setting Process <BR>
Permissible Exposure Limits <BR>
Third Party Audits/Self-Inspection <BR>
Assistance to Small Business <BR>
<BR>
<B>(2) Professional Recognition </B><BR>
Title Protection <BR>
Training and Certification (Single-Substance Issue)<BR>
<BR>
<B>(3) Laboratory Accreditation <BR>
<BR>
(4) Permissible Exposure Limits (PELs)<BR>
<BR>
(5) Health/Safety Program Standard <BR>
<BR>
(6) Generic Exposure Assessment Standard <BR>
<BR>
(7) Ergonomics Standard <BR>
<BR>
(8) Risk Assessment <BR>
<BR>
(9) Occupational Health and Safety Management System (OHSMS)<BR>
<BR>
(10) Indoor Air Quality <BR></B>
<P>
The American Industrial Hygiene Association, with more than 12,000 members, is the world's
largest association serving occupational and environmental health and safety 
professionals.
