<Title> AIHA Recognizes Joe Dear's Achievements as He Steps Down </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<BR>
<CENTER><H1>FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE<BR>
PRESS RELEASE</H1></CENTER>
<HR>
Contact:<BR>
<A HREF="mailto:cfeheley@aiha.org"> Christine Feheley</A><BR>
<A HREF="mailto:vpatterson@aiha.org"> Valerie Patterson</A><BR>
(703) 849-8888 <BR>
(703) 207-3561 fax <BR>
<HR>
<H2><CENTER> AIHA RECOGNIZES JOE DEAR'S ACHIEVEMENTS AS HE STEPS
DOWN FROM HIS POSITION WITH OSHA</H2></CENTER>
<P>
(Washington, Dec. 23, 1996)   The American Industrial Hygiene Association (AIHA)
acknowledges Joe Dear's contributions to the safety and health field as he resigns as assistant
secretary of labor for the Occupational Safety and Health Administration (OSHA).  "Joe Dear
will be sorely missed.  He was an excellent administrator and a very good ally for the
profession," said Zack Mansdorf, president of AIHA.
<P>
Among his accomplishments, Dear began the reinvention of OSHA and made great strides in
building a bridge between labor and business groups.  A team player, Dear's leadership was
potent as well as timely.
<P>
AIHA has worked to maintain a strong relationship with OSHA and is looking forward to
continuing a tradition of good will with Dear's successor.
<P>
The American Industrial Hygiene Association, with more than 12,000 members, is
the world's largest association serving occupational and environmental health and safety 
professionals.
<P>
