<Title> AIHA Ergonomics Guide of Hand Tools</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<BR>
<CENTER><H1>FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE<BR>
PRESS RELEASE</H1></CENTER>
<HR>
Contact:<BR>
<A HREF="mailto:cfeheley@aiha.org"> Christine Feheley</A><BR>
<A HREF="mailto:vpatterson@aiha.org"> Valerie Patterson</A><BR>
(703) 849-8888 <BR>
(703) 207-3561 fax <BR>
<HR>
<H2><CENTER> GETTING A GRIP ON THE ERGONOMICS OF HAND TOOLS IS EASY
WITH AIHA'S NEW GUIDE</H2></CENTER>
<P>
(Washington, August 19, 1996)--Ensuring hand tools accomplish what they are designed to do
without having a negative impact on the worker's well-being is an important ergonomic issue. 
AIHA's new publication,<I> An Ergonomics Guide to Hand Tools</I>, addresses this issue by
discussing in detail the ergonomic concerns of hand tools.
<P>
Topics discussed in detail include: optimization of force; distribution of contact pressures;
anatomical considerations; anthropometric considerations; and material and weight for tools and
handles.
<P>
Other topics addressed in this valuable reference include hand tool selection criteria, process
engineering requirements, human operator limitations, workstation and task factors, vibration, and
tool accessories.  
<P>
An <I>Ergonomics Guide to Hand Tools</I> is available to AIHA members for $16 and to
nonmembers for $20; use Stock No. 203-ER-95 to order. The American Industrial Hygiene
Association is devoted to promoting, protecting, and enhancing the profession to affect positively
the health and well-being of workers and members of the community.

<P>
