<HEAD>
<TITLE> Do I Work in a Sick Building? </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H1> Do I Work in a Sick Building? </H1>

Indoor air quality (IAQ) is the subject of much attention these days, and for good reason.  There
is more and more evidence that the quality of the indoor environment can have profound effects
on the health of building occupants.  The World Health Organization estimates that up to 30
percent of office buildings worldwide may have significant problems with 10 to 30 percent of the
occupants of the buildings experiencing health effects which are, or are perceived to be, related
to poor IAQ.
<P>
Although serious health problems related to IAQ are rare, the perception of endangered health is
increasingly common among building occupants.  In the United States, the National Institute for
Occupational Safety and Health recently had 3,000 telephone calls relating to poor IAQ in a
single week, 90 percent requesting investigations of the buildings they occupy or manage.
<P>
The causes and consequences of poor IAQ are a long way from being completely understood.  It
has been the experience of the American Industrial Hygiene Association (AIHA) that building
owners, managers, employers and occupants want to know more about the issue than has been
provided by the news media, whose stories have generally raised fears without offering solutions.
<P>
AIHA has developed this brochure to provide building owners, managers and occupants with a
summary of the current state of knowledge on IAQ.  The goal of this brochure is to inform the
reader so that you can make intelligent decisions about the present condition of your building.
<P>
<H3> The following topics are covered in the brochure: </H3>
<UL>
<LI> What is good indoor air quality?
<LI> What are common complaints about IAQ?
<LI> When are IAQ complaints most likely?
<LI> What are common sources of IAQ problems?
<LI> Why is ventilation important?
<LI> What can be done about IAQ complaints?
<LI> When should air testing be done?
<LI> How can IAQ problems be prevented?
<LI> What can be done to control indoor air contaminants?
<LI> When should I seek outside help?
<P>
<B><I>Cost: $10/pack of 50</B></I>
<P>
To request additional information or to order <I> Do I Work in a Sick Building? </I>:
<P>
E-mail: <A HREF="mailto:infonet@aiha.org">AIHA</A><BR>
Phone:  (703) 849-8888<BR>
Fax:    (703) 207-3561<BR>
