<H1> Mentoring Minority Youth through AIHA</H1>
<P>
The American Industrial Hygiene Association (AIHA) and the AIHA Foundation have
committed to a three-year action plan designed to increase diversity within the ranks of
occupational and environmental health and safety.  To achieve this goal, AIHA has embarked on
an ambitious mentoring program for minority youth.  Minority high school students, specially
selected based on their academic achievement and interest in science, will be matched up with
AIHA members in their communities.  We believe that these youths will benefit from the insight
and wisdom of experienced professionals, and in turn consider occupational and environmental
health and safety as a career.
<P>
A targeted number of AIHA local sections will be working in conjunction with a national
not-for-profit organization called INROADS, Inc..  This group, founded in 1970, has found great
success placing college-age students in internship and mentoring programs around the country. 
Nearly 5,000 students have graduated from the INROADS internship program so far.  The
majority were offered jobs with the companies for which they interned, a testament to the
program's success.
<P>
Through its Pre-College Component, INROADS offers organizations like AIHA the opportunity
to reach out to the minority community even earlier when so many important life decisions are
being made.  It is at this age that a mentor can have a profound impact on the choices of a young
person, including college, field of study, consideration of graduate school, and career path.
<P>
The AIHA Foundation has received a grant from Exxon, matched with funds from the National
Environmental Education and Training Foundation, to fund the activities under this outreach
program.  In cases where INROADS does not have a local coordinating office to assist the AIHA
local section, these guidelines will assist members in setting up the program themselves.
<P>
In addition to the goal of increasing minority representation in the field of occupational and
environmental health and safety, AIHA's other goals include:
<P>
<UL>
<LI>Fostering the development of interest in environmental health and safety;
<LI>Providing educational information on career opportunities; and
<LI>Providing a concrete action plan for community outreach.
</UL>
<P>
AIHA wants to work closely with its members to achieve these goals.  A limited amount of
funding is available for local sections to use in mentor-related activities, such as mailings to
recruit members to serve as mentors, the development of materials, hosting a social function for
mentors and students, etc.  The AIHA Member Services Division should be contacted directly to
discuss funding possibilities.
<P>
Attaining the long-term goals set by AIHA will take time and effort on the part of AIHA
members, but we believe that both the mentors and the students will find the program gratifying. 
We look forward to working with local sections and members on this worthwhile endeavor.
<P>
